{"title_page": "Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak", "text_new": "{{Infobox religious building\n| religious_affiliation = [[Jainism]]\n| image          = File:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Main (2).jpg\n| alt            = Vallabh Smarak Jain temple\n| caption        = Vallabh Smarak Jain mandir tirth\n| map_type       = \n| map_alt        = Vallabh Smarak Jain temple\n| map_caption    = Location within Delhi\n| map_size       = 200\n| coordinates    = {{coord|28|46|38.7|N|77|08|25.9|E|region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| location       = [[Nangli Poona]], [[Delhi]]\n| festivals      = [[Mahavir Jayanti]]\n| deity          = [[Parshvanath]]\n| established    = 1984\n| creator        = Mahattaraa Mrigavat\n| governing_body = Shree Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak Shikshan Nidhi\n| temple_quantity = 8\n}}\n\n'''Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak''' or '''Vallabh Smarak Jain Mandir Tirth''' is a [[Jainism|Jain]] temple located in [[Nangli Poona]], [[GT road]], [[Delhi]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe temple's construction was completed in 1989 by the followers of Acharya Vijay [[Vallabhsuri]],{{Sfn|Schnapp|2014|p=431}} to whom the temple is dedicated as a memorial. He is known for establishing several educational institutes in [[Punjab, India|Punjab,]] [[Delhi|Haryana,]] [[Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh, Rajasthan, Gujarat & Maharashtra]] including Mahavira Jain Vidhyalaya. He also worked to improve the religious and social life of the people in [[Punjab]], earning him the honorific ''Punjab Kesari''.{{Sfn|Shah|2004|p=55}} The construction of the temple was led by Acharya Samudrasuri to start with and then Acharya Indrdinsuri with Mahattaraa Mrigavati being the torch bearer for this project.{{Sfn|Shah|2004|p=44}} At present the activities of this Smarak are carried out in the guidance of Acharya Nityanandsuri\n\nThe temple is managed by Shree Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak Shikshan Nidhi.{{Sfn|Titze|1998|p=136}}\n\n== Architecture ==\n\nThe main hall of the temple is considered a brilliant example of the structural design of '''Amrutbhai Mulshankar Trivedi'''. It is built in dome-shaped internally with an external design having stepped roof.{{Sfn|Weiler|Gutschow|2016|p=118-119}} The temple belongs to [[\u015av\u0113t\u0101mbara]] sect of [[Jainism]]. The temple itself consists of ancient idols along with the manuscripts, images, sculptures dating back to the [[Medieval India|medieval period]]. The images and idol belong to [[Tirthankara]]s - 12th Tirtahnker Bhagwan Vasupujya being the main diety. Many an ancient murals and artifacts  are displayed in the basement Museum. Guru Mandir on the ground floor has a stunning sculpted image of Acharya Vallabh Suri and His charan paduka. Besides in the circular hall, of 64 feet dia and 84 feet height, are 10 panels of in exquisite three dimensional stone work depicting the illustrious life of Acharya Vallabhsuri.   These images are sourced mainly from [[Gujarat]], [[Rajasthan]] and [[Maharashtra]]. The temple also houses belongings of [[Acharya Vallabh Suri]], including Acharya's clothes, utensils, denture, and inkwell, showcased alongside Jain images and panels.{{Sfn|Schnapp|2014|pp=431-432}}\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Padmavati idol.jpg|Padmavati Idol\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Padmavati temple (2).jpg|Padmavati temple inside the temple complex\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Main Idol.jpg|Main idol\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Mural.jpg|Murals on wall\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Mrigavati Samadhi mandir.jpg|Mrigavati Samadhi mandir\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [[Jainism in Delhi]]\n* [[Lal Mandir]]\n* [[D\u0101d\u0101bad\u012b]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Citation ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Source ===\n* {{Citation | last1=Weiler | first1=Katharina | last2=Gutschow | first2=Niels | title=Authenticity in Architectural Heritage Conservation: Discourses, Opinions, Experiences in Europe, South and East Asia | publisher=[[Springer Publishing|Springer]] | date=2016 | url={{Google books|YhOfDAAAQBAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9783319305233 }} \n* {{Citation | last=Schnapp | first1=Alain | title=World Antiquarianism: Comparative Perspectives | publisher=Getty Publications | date=2014 | url={{Google books|w0skBAAAQBAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9781606061480 }} \n* {{citation | last=Shah | first=Natubhai | title=Jainism: The World of Conquerors | url={{Google books|qLNQKGcDIhsC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | volume=1 | date=2004 | origyear=First published in 1998 | publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] | isbn=978-81-208-1938-2 }}\n* {{Citation | last=Titze | first=Kurt | title=Jainism: A Pictorial Guide to the Religion of Non-Violence | publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publication | date=1998 | url={{Google books|loQkEIf8z5wC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9788120815346 }}\n\n{{Jain temples}}\n{{Jainism topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:20th-century Jain temples]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox religious building\n| religious_affiliation = [[Jainism]]\n| image          = File:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Main (2).jpg\n| alt            = Vallabh Smarak Jain temple\n| caption        = Vallabh Smarak Jain mandir tirth\n| map_type       = \n| map_alt        = Vallabh Smarak Jain temple\n| map_caption    = Location within Delhi\n| map_size       = 200\n| coordinates    = {{coord|28|46|38.7|N|77|08|25.9|E|region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| location       = [[Nangli Poona]], [[Delhi]]\n| festivals      = [[Mahavir Jayanti]]\n| deity          = [[Parshvanath]]\n| established    = 1984\n| creator        = Mahattaraa Mrigavat\n| governing_body = Shree Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak Shikshan Nidhi\n| temple_quantity = 8\n}}\n\n'''Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak''' or '''Vallabh Smarak Jain Mandir Tirth''' is a [[Jainism|Jain]] temple located in [[Nangli Poona]], [[GT road]], [[Delhi]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe temple's construction was completed in 1984 by the followers of Acharya Vijay [[Vallabhsuri]],{{Sfn|Schnapp|2014|p=431}} to whom the temple is dedicated as a memorial. He is known for establishing several educational institutes in [[Punjab, India|Punjab,]] [[Delhi]], and [[Uttar Pradesh]] including Mahavira Jain Vidhyalaya. He also worked to improve the religious and social life of the people in [[Punjab]], earning him the honorific ''Punjab Kesari''.{{Sfn|Shah|2004|p=55}} The construction of the temple was led by Mahattaraa Mrigavati.{{Sfn|Shah|2004|p=44}}\n\nThe temple is managed by Shree Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak Shikshan Nidhi.{{Sfn|Titze|1998|p=136}}\n\n== Architecture ==\n\nThe main hall of the temple is considered a brilliant example of the structural design of '''Amrutbhai Mulshankar Trivedi'''. It is built in dome-shaped internally with an external design having stepped roof.{{Sfn|Weiler|Gutschow|2016|p=118-119}} The temple belongs to [[\u015av\u0113t\u0101mbara]] sect of [[Jainism]]. The temple itself consists of ancient idols along with the manuscript, images, sculpture dating back to the [[Medieval India|medieval period]]. The images and idol belong to [[Tirthankara]]s and mother goddess [[Ambika (Jainism)|Ambika]], with images of [[Yaksha]] and [[Yakshi]] displayed in the basement panel. These images are sourced mainly from [[Gujarat]], [[Rajasthan]] and [[Maharashtra]]. The temple also houses belongings of [[Acharya Vallabh Suri]], including Acharya's clothes, utensils, denture, and inkwell, showcased alongside Jain images and panels.{{Sfn|Schnapp|2014|pp=431-432}}\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Padmavati idol.jpg|Padmavati Idol\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Padmavati temple (2).jpg|Padmavati temple inside the temple complex\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Main Idol.jpg|Main idol\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Mural.jpg|Murals on wall\nFile:Shri Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak - Mrigavati Samadhi mandir.jpg|Mrigavati Samadhi mandir\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [[Jainism in Delhi]]\n* [[Lal Mandir]]\n* [[D\u0101d\u0101bad\u012b]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Citation ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Source ===\n* {{Citation | last1=Weiler | first1=Katharina | last2=Gutschow | first2=Niels | title=Authenticity in Architectural Heritage Conservation: Discourses, Opinions, Experiences in Europe, South and East Asia | publisher=[[Springer Publishing|Springer]] | date=2016 | url={{Google books|YhOfDAAAQBAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9783319305233 }} \n* {{Citation | last=Schnapp | first1=Alain | title=World Antiquarianism: Comparative Perspectives | publisher=Getty Publications | date=2014 | url={{Google books|w0skBAAAQBAJ|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9781606061480 }} \n* {{citation | last=Shah | first=Natubhai | title=Jainism: The World of Conquerors | url={{Google books|qLNQKGcDIhsC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | volume=1 | date=2004 | origyear=First published in 1998 | publisher=[[Motilal Banarsidass]] | isbn=978-81-208-1938-2 }}\n* {{Citation | last=Titze | first=Kurt | title=Jainism: A Pictorial Guide to the Religion of Non-Violence | publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publication | date=1998 | url={{Google books|loQkEIf8z5wC|page=|keywords=|text=|plainurl=yes}} | isbn=9788120815346 }}\n\n{{Jain temples}}\n{{Jainism topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:20th-century Jain temples]]\n", "name_user": "GS AV Mahasangh", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added the description of Smarak and its contents. Edited by: Ashok Jain, Honorary Secretary - Shree Atma Vallabh Jain Smarak Shikshan Nidhi.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shri_Atma_Vallabh_Jain_Smarak"}
{"title_page": "Lydia Darragh", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=May 2019}}{{Infobox spy\n|name    = Lydia Darragh\n|image   = Lydia Darrah School.JPG\n|caption = Lydia Darrah School on the NRHP since December 4, 1986. At 708\u2013732 North 17th St., Philadelphia, in the Fairmount neighborhood of North Philly.\n|birth_date=1729\n|birth_place=[[Dublin]], [[Ireland]]\n|spouse=William Darragh\n|children = Charles Darragh, Ann Darragh, John Darragh, William Darragh, and Susannah Darragh\n|religion= [[Quaker]]\n|death_date=December 28, 1789\n|death_place=[[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]<ref>In John Fanning Watson's ''Historic Tales of Olden Time: Concerning the Early Settlement and Progress of Philadelphia Pennsylvania'' (published Philadelphia, 1833), there is an account of \"Lydia Darragh\" listed on page 294 under \"MISCELLANEA.\"</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Lydia Darragh''' (1729 \u2013 December 28, 1789) was an American woman said to have crossed British lines during the British [[Philadelphia campaign|occupation]] of [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] during the [[American Revolutionary War]], delivering information to [[George Washington]] and the [[Continental Army]] that warned them of a pending British [[Battle of White Marsh|attack]].<ref>Darrah's exploits were first documented in the article ''Lydia Darragh: One of the Heroines of the Revolution'' by Henry Darrach, published in 1915 by the City History Society of Philadelphia.  A copy of this article is online [http://www.frankfordgazette.com/doc/darragh3.pdf here ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090320141013/http://www.frankfordgazette.com/doc/darragh3.pdf |date=2009-03-20 }}</ref>  Contemporary sources claim Darragh's uncorroborated story is historically unsubstantiated.<ref name=\"cia\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/csi-publications/books-and-monographs/intelligence/pers.html |title=CIA.gov: Intelligence in the War of Independence - Personalities |accessdate=2 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114123526/https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/csi-publications/books-and-monographs/intelligence/pers.html |archivedate=14 January 2009 }} \"Family legend contributes the colorful but uncorroborated story of Lydia Darragh and her listening post for eavesdropping on the British.\"</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLydia Barrington Darragh was born in 1728 in Dublin, Ireland to John and Mary (Aldridge) Barrington, the youngest child of six. On November 2, 1753, she married the family's tutor, William Darragh, the son of a clergyman. A few years later, they immigrated to Philadelphia, where William worked as a tutor and Lydia as a midwife. She gave birth to five children: Charles (born 1755), Ann (born 1757), John (born 1763), William (born 1766), Susannah (born 1768), and four others who died in infancy. Lydia Barrington was not well educated because her parents did not have enough money for her ass education a bad one .<!-- Didn't she marry a tutor? -->\n\n==American Revolutionary War==\nAs Quakers, the Darraghs were [[pacifist]]s. However, their oldest son Charles served with the [[2nd Pennsylvania Regiment]] of the Continental Army.\n\nLydia\u2019s \u201cClaim to Fame\u201d is saving Washington\u2019s army from an ambush at Whitemarsh in December 1777.  The story was first published in 1827, and was later elaborated on. In 1777 the British were occupying Philadelphia. Lydia Darragh\u2019s house happened to be across the street from General William Howe\u2019s headquarters, and the night of December 2nd, 1777 British officers commandeered one of her rooms for a secret conference. Lydia eavesdropped on their meeting, learning of their plan to go after Washington\u2019s army at Whitemarsh. On December 4, she requested and received a pass to leave the city to go Frankford Mill to buy flour. Once she was outside the city, she made her way toward the Continental army at Whitemarsh. On the road, she met a friend who happened to be Colonel Thomas Craig from Washington\u2019s army. Lydia passed the information of the impending British attack through him, got her flour, and headed back to Philadelphia. That night the British marched on Whitemarsh- instead of the ambush they had planned, the Continental army was at arms and ready. General Howe was forced to return to Philadelphia.[http://www.britannica.com/biography/Lydia-Barrington-Darragh]\n\nOn September 26, 1777, British troops occupied Philadelphia.  [[General William Howe]] moved across the street from the Darraghs, in a house formerly belonging to [[John Cadwalader (general)|John Cadwalader]].<ref>Bohrer, Melissa Lukeman. Glory, Passion, and Principle: The Story of Eight Remarkable Women at the Core of the American Revolution. (New York: Atria Books, 2003), 127.</ref> Darragh began regularly providing her son Charles with information regarding the enemy's plans, gathered by eavesdropping in her home and around town.  She would often write this information in simple code on pieces of scrap paper, which she hid in large buttons that she and the messengers wore.<ref>Elizabeth Leonard, ''All the Daring of the Soldier'' (New York: Penguin, 1999), 19-35.</ref><ref>{{cite | last = Howat | first = Kenna | title = \"Revolutionary Spies: Women Spies of the American Revolution\" | publisher = National Women's History Museum | year = 2017 | url = https://www.womenshistory.org/articles/revolutionary-spies}}</ref> On September 27, 1777, Major John Andre, aide to General Howe, requested use of the Darraghs home for Howe's staff. Lydia told them that they had already sent away their two youngest children to live with relatives in another city, but that they had nowhere else to go and would like to stay in their home. She protested and went straight to Howe's residence (Cadwalader House) across the street from her home ([[Benjamin Loxley house|Loxley House]]). Prior to her meeting Howe, a British officer introduced himself as Captain William Barrington of the 7th Regiment of Foot (Royal Fusiliers). She was immediately taken aback by his Irish brogue and his name Barrington, which was her maiden name. He told her that he was from Dublin and in the course of the conversation, she discovered that he was her second cousin. She explained to him the situation and he stated that he would take up her case with Howe immediately. They both walked into the residence and were taken in to see Howe who agreed to let her stay but that he and his staff would use the large house parlor for staff meetings. They were permitted to remain, as Quakers were known to be unsupportive of the war, even on the side of the colonies, and therefore posed no apparent risk to the British army.<ref>Bohrer, Melissa Lukeman. Glory, Passion, and Principle: The Story of Eight Remarkable Women at the Core of the American Revolution. (New York: Atria Books, 2003),128.</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 1777, Lydia received a request that she and her family retire early, by 8 o'clock. She was told that she would be awakened when the soldiers were finished so she could let them out.  Lydia pretended to go to sleep, but instead listened to the soldiers through the door. She learned that British troops were being ordered to leave the city on December 4 to make a surprise attack on the [[Continental army]] camped at [[Battle of White Marsh|White Marsh]], led by George Washington.  Lydia sneaked back to bed and pretended to be asleep until the officer, Major [[John Andr\u00e9]], knocked three times at her door to awaken her to follow them out and extinguish the candles.\n\nLydia decided not to share this information with her husband. The following morning she was given permission by General Howe to cross British lines in order to go to [[Frankford, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Frankford]] to get flour.  Lydia dropped off her empty bag at the mill and then headed toward the American camp. Along the way she met an American officer, Colonel Craig of the [[First Troop Philadelphia City Cavalry|Light Horse]], and told him about the impending British attack so that he might warn Washington. After the warning, Lydia made her way back to the mill, picked up her flour and started her journey home. After the British troops attempted their attack and realized that the Americans were waiting for them, the officer questioned Lydia and asked if anyone was awake on the night of the meeting, because it was obvious that someone had betrayed them. Lydia denied any knowledge of this and was not further questioned. A quote from the officer who questioned Lydia: \"We were betrayed, for, on arriving near the encampment of General Washington, we found his cannon mounted, his troops under arms and so prepared at every point to receive us that we were compelled to march back, without injuring our enemy, like a parcel of fools.\"<ref>Lincoln Diamant, ed., ''Revolutionary Women in the War for American Independence'' (Westport, Conn: Praeger, 1998), 113-115.</ref>\n\n==First Hand Account==\n<blockquote>In the Autumn of 1777 the American Army lay some time at White Marsh. I was then Commissary Gen l of Prisoners, and managed the Intelligence of the Army. \u2014 I was reconoitering along the Lines near the City of Philadelphia. \u2014 I dined at a small Post at the rising Sun about three miles from the City. \u2014 After Dinner a little poor looking insignificant Old Woman came in & solicited leave to go into the Country to buy some flour \u2014 While we were asking some Questions, she walked up to me and put into my hands a dirty old needle book, with various small pockets in it. surprised at this, I told her to return, she should have an answer \u2014 On Opening the needlebook, I could not find any thing till I got to the last Pocket, Where I found a piece of Paper rolled up into the form of a Pipe Shank. \u2014 on unrolling it I found information that General Howe was coming out the next morning with 5000 Men \u2014 13 pieces of Cannon \u2014 Baggage Waggons, and 11 Boats on Waggon Wheels. On comparing this with other information I found it true, and immediately rode Post to head Quarters \u2014<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/journalorhistori00boud#page/50/ ''Journal or Historical Recollections of American Events During the Revolutionary War''].</ref></blockquote>A [[contemporary]] account of Lydia Darrah highlights several [[grist mills]] on the [[Frankford Creek]]; also a tavern named the Rising Sun next to Frankford's main grist mill. This was not the same Rising Sun Tavern mentioned in Boudinot's Journal.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160315234910/http://frankfordgazette.com/wp1/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/Frankford-Chronicles-Lydia-Darragh.Fi%C3%B1usFi-%C3%B1us.pdf \u201cFrankford Chronicles Agent Lydia Darragh - Intelligence Operative\u201d].</ref>\n\n[[British Intelligence]] agents became aware of the \"bag of flour\" trick a bit too late. On December 6, 1777, after the British returned from [[Battle of White Marsh|Whitemarsh]], a message was published in the Philadelphia newspaper about \"a poor woman, whom we both know\" traveling to the Frankford Mill:\n\n<blockquote>The following letter was found in a bag of Indian meal, which was picked up on Saturday the fourteenth of last month, was supposed to have been dropped by some of the women who were coming into town, when the skirmish happened between the pickets.<ref>Menkevich, Joseph J. Frankford Chronicles Agent Lydia Darragh - Intelligence Operative, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania (self-published, 2012), 5</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Later life==\nIn June 1778, British troops left Philadelphia, and Darragh's children returned to their family home. William Darrgah died on June 8, 1783. Charles lost his membership to the Society of Friends on April 27, 1781. Lydia lost her membership on August 29, 1783. In 1786, Lydia and the children moved into a new house, and she ran a store until her death on December 28, 1789. They are both buried in the Quakers' burying ground at Fourth and Arch Streets, not far from their home.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2013 the National Society of the [[Sons of the American Revolution]] created the Lydia Darragh Medal. The Lydia Darragh Medal may be awarded by the incumbent President General, Vice President General, State Society President or Chapter President to the lady who has provided significant service to him during his term of office. The medal recognizes the assistance of the women who work behind the scenes supporting SAR programs.<ref>SAR Handbook.  Vol. 5. Individual Medals and Awards. 2015. pg. 34-35.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Intelligence in the American Revolutionary War]]\n* [[Intelligence operations in the American Revolutionary War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n==Further reading==\n* Darrach, Henry, et al. \"Lydia Darragh, of the Revolution.\" ''The Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography'' 23.1 (1899): 86-91. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/20085838 online]\n* Darrach, Henry. ''Lydia Darragh, One of the Heroines of the Revolution.'' (1916) [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=tcQxAQAAMAAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA377&dq=Lydia+Darragh+&ots=fl0fYrJe6w&sig=mAfe5ssH1PL4NY8mtx-URjrHkOM online]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.org/stream/journalorhistori00boud#page/n3/mode/2up \"Boudinot, Elias. Journal or Historical Recollections of American Events During the Revolutionary War. (Philadelphia: F. Bourquin, 1894)]\n*\"Lydia Darrah's House\", Muscatine ''Journal'', Friday, January 6, 1854\n*[http://frankfordgazette.com/2012/12/11/frankford-chronicles-agent-lydia-darragh-intelligence-operative/ \"Frankford Chronicles Agent Lydia Darragh - Intelligence Operative\"] at frankfordgazette.com\n*{{Find a Grave|28814348|name=lydia darragh grave}}\n*Michals, Debra.  [https://www.womenshistory.org/education-resources/biographies/lydia-darragh \"Lydia Barrington Darragh\"].  National Women's History Museum.  2015.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Darrah, Lydia}}\n[[Category:1728 births]]\n[[Category:1789 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century American people]]\n[[Category:American Quakers]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:People of Pennsylvania in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Women in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:People of colonial Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Kingdom of Ireland emigrants to the Thirteen Colonies]]\n[[Category:American spies during the American Revolution]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=May 2019}}{{Infobox spy\n|name    = Lydia Darragh\n|image   = Lydia Darrah School.JPG\n|caption = Lydia Darrah School on the NRHP since December 4, 1986. At 708\u2013732 North 17th St., Philadelphia, in the Fairmount neighborhood of North Philly.\n|birth_date=1729\n|birth_place=[[Dublin]], [[Ireland]]\n|spouse=William Darragh\n|children = Charles Darragh, Ann Darragh, John Darragh, William Darragh, and Susannah Darragh\n|religion= [[Quaker]]\n|death_date=December 28, 1789\n|death_place=[[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States]]<ref>In John Fanning Watson's ''Historic Tales of Olden Time: Concerning the Early Settlement and Progress of Philadelphia Pennsylvania'' (published Philadelphia, 1833), there is an account of \"Lydia Darragh\" listed on page 294 under \"MISCELLANEA.\"</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Lydia Darragh''' (1729 \u2013 December 28, 1789) was an American woman said to have crossed British lines during the British [[Philadelphia campaign|occupation]] of [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] during the [[American Revolutionary War]], delivering information to [[George Washington]] and the [[Continental Army]] that warned them of a pending British [[Battle of White Marsh|attack]].<ref>Darrah's exploits were first documented in the article ''Lydia Darragh: One of the Heroines of the Revolution'' by Henry Darrach, published in 1915 by the City History Society of Philadelphia.  A copy of this article is online [http://www.frankfordgazette.com/doc/darragh3.pdf here ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090320141013/http://www.frankfordgazette.com/doc/darragh3.pdf |date=2009-03-20 }}</ref>  Contemporary sources claim Darragh's uncorroborated story is historically unsubstantiated.<ref name=\"cia\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/csi-publications/books-and-monographs/intelligence/pers.html |title=CIA.gov: Intelligence in the War of Independence - Personalities |accessdate=2 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114123526/https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/csi-publications/books-and-monographs/intelligence/pers.html |archivedate=14 January 2009 }} \"Family legend contributes the colorful but uncorroborated story of Lydia Darragh and her listening post for eavesdropping on the British.\"</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLydia Barrington Darragh was born in 1728 in Dublin, Ireland to John and Mary (Aldridge) Barrington, the youngest child of six. On November 2, 1753, she married the family's tutor, William Darragh, the son of a clergyman. A few years later, they immigrated to Philadelphia, where William worked as a tutor and Lydia as a midwife. She gave birth to five children: Charles (born 1755), Ann (born 1757), John (born 1763), William (born 1766), Susannah (born 1768), and four others who died in infancy. Lydia Barrington was not well educated because her parents did not have enough money for her education.<!-- Didn't she marry a tutor? -->\n\n==American Revolutionary War==\nAs Quakers, the Darraghs were [[pacifist]]s. However, their oldest son Charles served with the [[2nd Pennsylvania Regiment]] of the Continental Army.\n\nLydia\u2019s \u201cClaim to Fame\u201d is saving Washington\u2019s army from an ambush at Whitemarsh in December 1777.  The story was first published in 1827, and was later elaborated on. In 1777 the British were occupying Philadelphia. Lydia Darragh\u2019s house happened to be across the street from General William Howe\u2019s headquarters, and the night of December 2nd, 1777 British officers commandeered one of her rooms for a secret conference. Lydia eavesdropped on their meeting, learning of their plan to go after Washington\u2019s army at Whitemarsh. On December 4, she requested and received a pass to leave the city to go Frankford Mill to buy flour. Once she was outside the city, she made her way toward the Continental army at Whitemarsh. On the road, she met a friend who happened to be Colonel Thomas Craig from Washington\u2019s army. Lydia passed the information of the impending British attack through him, got her flour, and headed back to Philadelphia. That night the British marched on Whitemarsh- instead of the ambush they had planned, the Continental army was at arms and ready. General Howe was forced to return to Philadelphia.[http://www.britannica.com/biography/Lydia-Barrington-Darragh]\n\nOn September 26, 1777, British troops occupied Philadelphia.  [[General William Howe]] moved across the street from the Darraghs, in a house formerly belonging to [[John Cadwalader (general)|John Cadwalader]].<ref>Bohrer, Melissa Lukeman. Glory, Passion, and Principle: The Story of Eight Remarkable Women at the Core of the American Revolution. (New York: Atria Books, 2003), 127.</ref> Darragh began regularly providing her son Charles with information regarding the enemy's plans, gathered by eavesdropping in her home and around town.  She would often write this information in simple code on pieces of scrap paper, which she hid in large buttons that she and the messengers wore.<ref>Elizabeth Leonard, ''All the Daring of the Soldier'' (New York: Penguin, 1999), 19-35.</ref><ref>{{cite | last = Howat | first = Kenna | title = \"Revolutionary Spies: Women Spies of the American Revolution\" | publisher = National Women's History Museum | year = 2017 | url = https://www.womenshistory.org/articles/revolutionary-spies}}</ref> On September 27, 1777, Major John Andre, aide to General Howe, requested use of the Darraghs home for Howe's staff. Lydia told them that they had already sent away their two youngest children to live with relatives in another city, but that they had nowhere else to go and would like to stay in their home. She protested and went straight to Howe's residence (Cadwalader House) across the street from her home ([[Benjamin Loxley house|Loxley House]]). Prior to her meeting Howe, a British officer introduced himself as Captain William Barrington of the 7th Regiment of Foot (Royal Fusiliers). She was immediately taken aback by his Irish brogue and his name Barrington, which was her maiden name. He told her that he was from Dublin and in the course of the conversation, she discovered that he was her second cousin. She explained to him the situation and he stated that he would take up her case with Howe immediately. They both walked into the residence and were taken in to see Howe who agreed to let her stay but that he and his staff would use the large house parlor for staff meetings. They were permitted to remain, as Quakers were known to be unsupportive of the war, even on the side of the colonies, and therefore posed no apparent risk to the British army.<ref>Bohrer, Melissa Lukeman. Glory, Passion, and Principle: The Story of Eight Remarkable Women at the Core of the American Revolution. (New York: Atria Books, 2003),128.</ref>\n\nOn December 2, 1777, Lydia received a request that she and her family retire early, by 8 o'clock. She was told that she would be awakened when the soldiers were finished so she could let them out.  Lydia pretended to go to sleep, but instead listened to the soldiers through the door. She learned that British troops were being ordered to leave the city on December 4 to make a surprise attack on the [[Continental army]] camped at [[Battle of White Marsh|White Marsh]], led by George Washington.  Lydia sneaked back to bed and pretended to be asleep until the officer, Major [[John Andr\u00e9]], knocked three times at her door to awaken her to follow them out and extinguish the candles.\n\nLydia decided not to share this information with her husband. The following morning she was given permission by General Howe to cross British lines in order to go to [[Frankford, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Frankford]] to get flour.  Lydia dropped off her empty bag at the mill and then headed toward the American camp. Along the way she met an American officer, Colonel Craig of the [[First Troop Philadelphia City Cavalry|Light Horse]], and told him about the impending British attack so that he might warn Washington. After the warning, Lydia made her way back to the mill, picked up her flour and started her journey home. After the British troops attempted their attack and realized that the Americans were waiting for them, the officer questioned Lydia and asked if anyone was awake on the night of the meeting, because it was obvious that someone had betrayed them. Lydia denied any knowledge of this and was not further questioned. A quote from the officer who questioned Lydia: \"We were betrayed, for, on arriving near the encampment of General Washington, we found his cannon mounted, his troops under arms and so prepared at every point to receive us that we were compelled to march back, without injuring our enemy, like a parcel of fools.\"<ref>Lincoln Diamant, ed., ''Revolutionary Women in the War for American Independence'' (Westport, Conn: Praeger, 1998), 113-115.</ref>\n\n==First Hand Account==\n<blockquote>In the Autumn of 1777 the American Army lay some time at White Marsh. I was then Commissary Gen l of Prisoners, and managed the Intelligence of the Army. \u2014 I was reconoitering along the Lines near the City of Philadelphia. \u2014 I dined at a small Post at the rising Sun about three miles from the City. \u2014 After Dinner a little poor looking insignificant Old Woman came in & solicited leave to go into the Country to buy some flour \u2014 While we were asking some Questions, she walked up to me and put into my hands a dirty old needle book, with various small pockets in it. surprised at this, I told her to return, she should have an answer \u2014 On Opening the needlebook, I could not find any thing till I got to the last Pocket, Where I found a piece of Paper rolled up into the form of a Pipe Shank. \u2014 on unrolling it I found information that General Howe was coming out the next morning with 5000 Men \u2014 13 pieces of Cannon \u2014 Baggage Waggons, and 11 Boats on Waggon Wheels. On comparing this with other information I found it true, and immediately rode Post to head Quarters \u2014<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/journalorhistori00boud#page/50/ ''Journal or Historical Recollections of American Events During the Revolutionary War''].</ref></blockquote>A [[contemporary]] account of Lydia Darrah highlights several [[grist mills]] on the [[Frankford Creek]]; also a tavern named the Rising Sun next to Frankford's main grist mill. This was not the same Rising Sun Tavern mentioned in Boudinot's Journal.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160315234910/http://frankfordgazette.com/wp1/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/Frankford-Chronicles-Lydia-Darragh.Fi%C3%B1usFi-%C3%B1us.pdf \u201cFrankford Chronicles Agent Lydia Darragh - Intelligence Operative\u201d].</ref>\n\n[[British Intelligence]] agents became aware of the \"bag of flour\" trick a bit too late. On December 6, 1777, after the British returned from [[Battle of White Marsh|Whitemarsh]], a message was published in the Philadelphia newspaper about \"a poor woman, whom we both know\" traveling to the Frankford Mill:\n\n<blockquote>The following letter was found in a bag of Indian meal, which was picked up on Saturday the fourteenth of last month, was supposed to have been dropped by some of the women who were coming into town, when the skirmish happened between the pickets.<ref>Menkevich, Joseph J. Frankford Chronicles Agent Lydia Darragh - Intelligence Operative, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania (self-published, 2012), 5</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Later life==\nIn June 1778, British troops left Philadelphia, and Darragh's children returned to their family home. William Darrgah died on June 8, 1783. Charles lost his membership to the Society of Friends on April 27, 1781. Lydia lost her membership on August 29, 1783. In 1786, Lydia and the children moved into a new house, and she ran a store until her death on December 28, 1789. They are both buried in the Quakers' burying ground at Fourth and Arch Streets, not far from their home.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2013 the National Society of the [[Sons of the American Revolution]] created the Lydia Darragh Medal. The Lydia Darragh Medal may be awarded by the incumbent President General, Vice President General, State Society President or Chapter President to the lady who has provided significant service to him during his term of office. The medal recognizes the assistance of the women who work behind the scenes supporting SAR programs.<ref>SAR Handbook.  Vol. 5. Individual Medals and Awards. 2015. pg. 34-35.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Intelligence in the American Revolutionary War]]\n* [[Intelligence operations in the American Revolutionary War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n==Further reading==\n* Darrach, Henry, et al. \"Lydia Darragh, of the Revolution.\" ''The Pennsylvania Magazine of History and Biography'' 23.1 (1899): 86-91. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/20085838 online]\n* Darrach, Henry. ''Lydia Darragh, One of the Heroines of the Revolution.'' (1916) [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=tcQxAQAAMAAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PA377&dq=Lydia+Darragh+&ots=fl0fYrJe6w&sig=mAfe5ssH1PL4NY8mtx-URjrHkOM online]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.org/stream/journalorhistori00boud#page/n3/mode/2up \"Boudinot, Elias. Journal or Historical Recollections of American Events During the Revolutionary War. (Philadelphia: F. Bourquin, 1894)]\n*\"Lydia 