{"title_page": "Committed relationship", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=February 2011}}\nA '''committed relationship''' is an [[interpersonal relationship]] based upon a mutually agreed-upon commitment to one another involving love, trust, honesty, openness, or some other behavior. Forms of committed relationships include [[friendship|close friendship]], [[long-term relationship]]s, [[engagement]], [[marriage]], and [[civil union]]s.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Monogamy]]: having a single long-term sexual partner\n* [[Marriage]]: a legal and social binding between two people.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Haviland |first1=William A. |last2=Prins |first2=Harald E.L. |last3=McBride |first3=Bunny |last4=Walrath |first4=Dana |year=2011 |title=Cultural Anthropology: The Human Challenge |publisher=Cengage Learning |isbn=978-0495811787 |edition=13th}}</ref> \n* [[Sexual infidelity]]: having a sexual relationship without a commitment to have no other sexual partners\n* [[Sexual fidelity]]: not having other sexual partners other than one's committed partner, even temporarily\n* [[Serial monogamy]]: having a series of monogamous relationships, one after the other\n* [[Open relationship]]: a commitment to a partner without excluding other romantic or sexual involvement\n* [[Polygamy]]: having multiple long-term sexual partners\n* [[Polyandry]]: having multiple long-term male sexual partners\n* [[Polygyny]]: having multiple long-term female sexual partners\n* [[Polyamory]]: encompasses a wide range of relationships; polyamorous relationships may include both committed and casual relationships\n* [[Promiscuity]]: having casual sexual partners at will (compare with [[chastity]])\n* [[Relationship anarchy]]: having relationships that develop as an agreement between those involved, rather than according to predetermined rules or norms.\n\n{{Human sexuality}}\n{{Human sexuality and sexology}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Committed Relationship}}\n[[Category:Interpersonal relationships]]\n[[Category:Monogamy]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=February 2011}}\nA '''committed relationship''' is an [[interpersonal relationship]] based upon a mutually agreed-upon commitment to one another involving love, trust, honesty, openness, or some other behavior. Forms of committed relationships include [[friendship|close friendship]], [[long-term relationship]]s, [[engagement]], [[marriage]], and [[civil union]]s.\n\n==See also==\n* [[monogamy]]: having a single long-term sexual partner\n* [[marriage]]: a legal and social binding between two people.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Haviland |first1=William A. |last2=Prins |first2=Harald E.L. |last3=McBride |first3=Bunny |last4=Walrath |first4=Dana |year=2011 |title=Cultural Anthropology: The Human Challenge |publisher=Cengage Learning |isbn=978-0495811787 |edition=13th}}</ref> \n* [[sexual infidelity]]: having a sexual relationship without a commitment to have no other sexual partners\n* [[sexual fidelity]]: not having other sexual partners other than one's committed partner, even temporarily\n* [[serial monogamy]]: having a series of monogamous relationships, one after the other\n* [[open relationship]]: a commitment to a partner without excluding other romantic or sexual involvement\n* [[polygamy]]: having multiple long-term sexual partners\n* [[polyandry]]: having multiple long-term male sexual partners\n* [[polygyny]]: having multiple long-term female sexual partners\n* [[polyamory]]: encompasses a wide range of relationships; polyamorous relationships may include both committed and casual relationships\n* [[promiscuity]]: having casual sexual partners at will (compare with [[chastity]])\n* [[relationship anarchy]]: having relationships that develop as an agreement between those involved, rather than according to predetermined rules or norms.\n\n{{Human sexuality}}\n{{Human sexuality and sexology}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Committed Relationship}}\n[[Category:Interpersonal relationships]]\n[[Category:Monogamy]]\n", "name_user": "Cryptopocalypse", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:Capitalization", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Committed_relationship"}
{"title_page": "Linpan in Chengdu Plain", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|date=February 2020}}\n\n\nThe '''Linpan in Chengdu Plain''', also called ''Linpan settlement'', is a traditional rural community in [[Chengdu Plain]], [[Sichuan]], [[China]], characterized by small scale farming, rectangular fields, trees and bamboo, all supported by an ancient irrigation system known as the [[Dujiangyan Irrigation System]]. The system incorporates traditional farming behavior and culture, and has been credited with contributing to the beauty and uniqueness of the rural landscape of the Chengdu Plain.<ref name=\"the rural landscape\">{{cite journal|last1=Yang|first1=Qingjuan|last2=Li|first2=Bei|last3=Li|first3=Kui|title=The Rural Landscape Research in Chengdu's Urban-rural Integration Development|journal=Procedia Engineering|date=2011|volume=21|issue=1|pages=780\u2013788|doi=10.1016/j.proeng.2011.11.2078|doi-access=free}}</ref> \n\nThe Linpan in Chengdu Plain originated during the [[:zh:\u53e4\u8700\u6587\u660e|Ancient Shu Civilization]] and formed after a long period of immigration.<ref name=\"Fan Yanzhi\" /> Linpan culture draws from the philosophy of pleasure, leisure, and freedom emphasized by Taoism, which has been historically important in the Western Sichuan Plain. This way of life is currently under threat from development and pollution.\n[[File:A Typical Linpan unit in Pi County.jpg|center|thumb|519x519px|A Typical Linpan Unit in Pi County]]\n\n==Introduction==\nThe LinPan in Chengdu Plain, as a principle rustic landscape in the Chengdu Plain, might be defined as a complex habitation mode. Generalized Linpan in Chengdu Plain refers to the Linpan Settlement system in the region of Chengdu Plain, also known as Linpan settlement. Moreover, LinPan in Chengdu Plain is representative of farming type in western Sichuan that combines production and daily life in one landscape. It is understood that the cores of Linpan in Chengdu plain are trees and bamboo, but the main features of this landscape are water, houses, and fields. It is usually inhabited by surname or clan as settlement units showing the layout in a decentralized manner and in the form of a typical natural village. Small-scale Linpan generally has only a few dozen peasant families, however large-scale Linpan may contain hundreds of households.\n\nLinpan in Chengdu Plain originated during the [[:zh:\u53e4\u8700\u6587\u660e|Ancient Shu Civilization]] and formed in a long period of immigration, which has been thousands of years history. It is not only reflected in the local farming culture but also is the crystallization of the traditional farming civilization era. The Linpan Settlement system coordinates with local farming conditions, traditional farming behavior and living life, and plays a crucial role in preserving the environment of Chengdu Plain.<ref name=\"Fan Yanzhi\">{{cite thesis |last=Fan |first=Yanzhi |date=2009 |title=\u5ddd\u897f\u6797\u76d8\u73af\u5883\u666f\u89c2\u4fdd\u62a4\u6027\u89c4\u5212\u8bbe\u8ba1\u7814\u7a76 |trans-title= |type=MSc |chapter= |publisher=Sichuan Agricultural University |docket= |oclc= |url=http://cdmd.cnki.com.cn/Article/CDMD-10626-2009258597.htm |access-date=}}</ref> Furthermore, it has society, culture, aesthetic and ecology value and make the rural landscape of Chengdu Plain different from the other area of China. The key reasons that it came into being, can be analyzed as a natural environment, farm culture, the history of immigration, society culture.<ref name=\"Linpan book\">{{cite book|last1=Duang|first1=Peng|last2=Liu|first2=Tianhou|title=\u6797\u76d8: \u8700\u6587\u5316\u4e4b\u751f\u6001\u5bb6\u56ed|trans-title=Linpan: The ecological homeland of Shu culture|date=2004|publisher=Sichuan Science Technology Press|location=Chengdu|isbn=978-7-5364-5577-1|edition=Di 1 ban.}}</ref>\n\nThe rural landscape of Chengdu can be described as patches (the vast plain of farmland), corridors (roads and irrigation Canals), and matrixes (small matrixes are thousands of Linpans, big ones are towns). Linpan is the key element that makes Chengdu rural landscape unique.<ref name=\"the rural landscape\" />\n\n==Features==\n\n===Culture===\nLinpan Settlement in Chengdu Plain inherited Chinese traditional farming culture and has a farming history for thousands of years, but it also has its own characteristics. [[Sichuan]] is a historic and typical region of traditional intensive farming culture in China, while the Chengdu Plain, is an important place of origin and development of this culture. Chengdu Plain provides the requisite conditions for the continuation and development of the farming culture, such as pleasant environmental conditions, warm and humid climate, abundant water and fertile land.\n\nIn the second place, Linpan in Chengdu Plain combines the [[Dujiangyan irrigation system]], agricultural production, family system and lifestyle, that integrates the daily life in Chengdu Plain, production and ecological environment. It is a perfect combined spatial form of cultural symbol and use value. Linpan in Chengdu Plain formed as the basis of millennial Dujiangyan irrigation works, which solved the decisive factor, water, for the farming culture development. Formed a pattern of ecological farming, which regards the Dujiangyan irrigation system as its core, Chengdu plain as its hinterland and Longquan Range as its protective screen. The intensive Linpan Settlements fully reflect the farming culture which has the Sichuan water cultural characteristic.\n\n===Ecology===\nChengdu Plain irrigated by the Dujiangyan irrigation system is a semi-natural wetland ecosystem. It provides a habitat for birds, but also provides a food base and living space for human beings. The symbiosis of people and woods even more continues today. The mainly landscape elements in this living environment are fields, woods, farmhouse and water, and these four main elements are harmony and interdependence\uff1a\n\n*Pattern of woods-water, creates the integration of woods forest network and water network.\n*Pattern of woods-fields, shows high performance in biodiversity.\n*Pattern of woods-farm house, creates a pleasant microclimate.\nIn terms of vegetation other than crops,  the dominant plant type in Chengdu Plain is evergreen broad-leaved forest because Chengdu locates in the subtropical humid monsoon climate zone. Affected by the same rainfall and heat pattern, Linpan demonstrates similar zonal characteristics in the natural distribution of plant community structure with some distinctive variations. In the Linpan landscape, the main vegetation types surrounding residential buildings are evergreen broad-leaved forests and bamboo stands with frequencies of 25% and 32%, respectively. In contrast to the overall high biodiversity of Linpan as a rural settlement, the vegetation around houses are rather uniform. In most farming Linpan, the plant structure is dominated by a single type of tree or bamboo such as Metasequoia or Cedar. The relatively mixed forests mostly exist in Linpan aiming at developing rural tourism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u5b59\u5927\u6c5f|last2=\u9648\u5176\u5175|last3=\u80e1\u5ead\u5174|last4=\u5218\u5149\u7acb|last5=\u5b59\u5927\u8fdc|last6=\u7f57\u542f\u9ad8|date=2011|title=\u5ddd\u897f\u6797\u76d8\u7fa4\u843d\u7c7b\u578b\u53ca\u5176\u591a\u6837\u6027|url=http://www.cqvip.com/qk/91109x/201101/37279682.html|journal=\u56db\u5ddd\u519c\u4e1a\u5927\u5b66\u5b66\u62a5|volume=29|issue=1}}</ref>\n\n===Form===\nThe whole Linpan settlement in Chengdu Plain that lies between the cities and towns as roads crisscross, coupled with the water-intensive. It is in space to form a \"checkerboard\" pattern, such a network, which distributed a number of scattered Linpan landscape units.<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Zhao |first=Rongming |date=2006 |title=\u6210\u90fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8fb9\u7f18\u533a\u4e61\u6751\u805a\u843d\u89c4\u5212\u8bbe\u8ba1\u9762\u4e34\u7684\u95ee\u9898\u4e0e\u5bf9\u7b56\u7814\u7a76 |trans-title= |type=MSc |chapter= |publisher=Southwest Jiaotong University |docket= |oclc= |url=http://d.wanfangdata.com.cn/Thesis/Y1019960 |access-date=}}</ref> Linpan Settlement generally based on single-family or family group as a unit, scattered among the field.\n\nIn terms of shape, it is characterized by small-scale and recognizability. The scale of the farm village in the Chengdu Plain is very small. The radius of the buildings, surrounding courtyards and [[bamboo]]s always within 30 meters. This kind of compact small village has a strong identifiable and easy for people to grasp farming activities.\n\nThe buildings in Linpan are generally typical one-story Western Sichuan folk residential buildings with a Galley or L-shape layout built by individual households respectively. Usually, 3-5 households form a small Linpan unit, and 20-30 households form a big Linpan unit, which is surrounded by tall trees and bamboos to shelter from the wind.\n\nOne of the most significant features of Linpan and almost all Western Sichuan folk housing is that the buildings always enclose a courtyard called \u201cBaba\u201d, and \u201cBaba\u201d is where most domestic and interactive activities happen. People dry crops, hang out washed clothes, talk and play [[Mahjong]] with neighbors, and even host family banquets (Baba Yan) in the \"Baba\" courtyards.\n\n== The Causes for the Formation of Linpan Culture ==\n\n=== Geographical and Environmental Conditions ===\nChengdu Plain is a relatively independent and complete geographic unit sitting in the western [[Sichuan Basin]]. The area of Chengdu Plain is about 9100 square kilometers in size and 450\u2013750 meters in altitude. Chengdu Plain is a river alluvial plain, and its fertile soil and large open flat land provide a firm foundation for farming development. In addition, the mild subtropical monsoon climate brings rich heat and abundant rainfall, making it suitable for human habitation and production. With the warm winter and the early spring, crops and bamboos can grow year-round. Another unique advantage of the Chengdu Plain is the well-developed irrigation system.  After the construction of [[Dujiangyan]], most farmlands achieved gravity irrigation. Along with ample surface and groundwater resources, the dispersed rural living pattern became possible.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.cnki.com.cn/Article_en/CJFDTOTAL-CDDB201105014.htm|title=On Causes for Formation of Linpan Culture in West Sichuan Plain--\u300aJournal of Chengdu University(Social Sciences)\u300b2011\u5e7405\u671f|website=en.cnki.com.cn|access-date=2017-11-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Economics and Production ===\nThe relatively stable climate and advanced water irrigation and management system in western Sichuan provide a powerful guarantee for the independent farming of individual households. In order to promote crop production, farmers choose to live scattered near their own land to devote more labor to intensive rice farming. In addition, the scattered pattern solves the shortcomings of long-distance transportation in the fields. Moreover, surplus manpower and large courtyards make it possible for farmers to supplement agricultural income by operating home textiles, bamboo basket weaving or raising livestock, and grow fruits and vegetables. With all these factors, the production of the Linpan gradually evolved into the current pattern.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Migration ===\nThere have been six large-scale migrations in history from other provinces to Sichuan province, creating the unique and inclusive culture of an immigrant society. Migrants promoted the social and economic development of the region in many ways and various customs they introduced created the compatible features of a new culture. During the migration process, bloodlines were broken and the concept of clans was diluted, so rather than being bind by kinships, people were more related by geography and production approximately. In the new settlements, people could be equal regardless of their origins, allowing the Linpan culture of a scattered living pattern to flourish.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Culture and Customs ===\nWestern Sichuan Plain is an important source of [[Taoism]]. Since the [[:zh:\u53e4\u8700\u6587\u660e|Ancient Shu Civilization]], people living in the region have valued nature and freedom over careers and regulations. Later generations of the Shu in the unique geographical and cultural environment also inherited the philosophy of prioritizing pleasure, leisure, and the freedom of life, which formed the social basis for Linpan culture. Another reason explaining the settlement pattern is the tradition of living separately in single-family homes, instead of large unified homes with parents and relatives. By splitting up into smaller units, there are more initiative and flexibility for households to live and produce.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Distribution of Linpan==\nLinpan Settlement mainly distributed in the Chengdu Plain, however, Chengdu Plain belongs to the Sichuan Basin. [[Sichuan Basin]] is one of the famous big basins in China, whose terrain is relatively inaccessible. It is surrounded by 1000\u20132000 meters above sea level mountain, one of the few mountains up to an altitude of 3000\u20134000 meters. Basin covers an area of about 170,000 square kilometers, mostly in elevation between 300\u2013700 meters.\n\nThe Chengdu Plain covers an area of about 23,000 square kilometers and is the largest plain in southwestern China. It lies on the marginal region of the Sichuan Basin and rivers from the high mountains to the north and west brings soil and water supply to the vast land.<ref name=\"GO CD\">{{cite web|title=What makes Chengdu the Land of Abundance|url=http://www.gochengdu.cn/culture/city-profile/what-makes-chengdu-the-land-of-abundance-a593.html|website=GO CHENGDU|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> The Chengdu Plain located among Longquan range, [[Longmen Mountains]] and [[Qionglai Mountains]].<ref name=\"Linpan book\" /> The great [[Min River (Sichuan)|Minjiang River]], together with its tributaries, runs across the Chengdu Plain to form an expansive water network.<ref name=\"GO CD\" /> Because the formation of factors, Linpan mainly distributed in flat terrain area, that the most typical ones are in the Chengdu Plain. In addition to Sichuan in China's western provinces of [[Yunnan]], [[Guizhou]] and other places also have distribution.\n\nThe typical Linpan Settlements mainly distributed in 14 districts(cities) of Chengdu Plain are [[Longquanyi District]], [[Pi County]], [[Wenjiang District]], [[Shuangliu District]], [[Xindu District]], [[Qingbaijiang District]], [[Dayi County]], [[Xinjin County]], [[Jintang County]], [[Pujiang County, Sichuan|Pujiang County]], [[Dujiangyan City]], [[Pengzhou]], [[Chongzhou|Chongzhou City]], [[Qionglai City]], covers an area of 11,711 square kilometers. According to statistics, Linpan in Chengdu Plain demonstrates a  wide distribution (area of 9482 square kilometers). a total of 141,100 existing Linpan, Linpan total area of 67,679.87 hectares, the population living within Linpan 449.03 million, accounting for 41.50 percent of the total population of the city region, representing the city 77.09% of the total rural population; Linpan per capita area of 150 square meters. The number of existing Linpan is around 141,100, with a total area of 67,679.87 hectares. The resident population of Linpan in Chengdu is about 449.03 million, accounting for 41.50% of the total population of the city region and 77.09% of the city total rural population.<ref name=\"jianwei\">{{cite journal|last1=Chengdu|first1=Urban and Rural Construction Commission|title=\u6210\u90fd\u7f16\u5236\u89c4\u5212\u4fdd\u62a4\u5ddd\u897f\u6797\u76d8\u98ce\u8c8c|journal=Urban Planning Newsreport|date=2007|volume=17|pages=8\u20139|url=http://www.cnki.com.cn/Article/CJFDTotal-CSGT200717010.htm}}</ref>\n\n==Types of Linpan Settlement==\n\n===Farming Type===\nThis type of Linpan settlement mainly focuses on agricultural production. The vegetation and buildings in this kind of Linpan Settlement should harmonize with the fields, and it is the ecological residence of the rural population who engaged in agricultural activities. It is also a typical vector, which is the symbiosis of people, fields, buildings, woods, and water. There are some unique spatial features of the farming Linpan, which provide spaces for drying cereals and corn, stacking farming tools, intensively-reared livestock, etc. These characteristics are reflected in this kind of Linpan settlement farming as the main mode of industrial structure.\n[[File:Farmhouse in Chengdu Plain.jpg|thumb|right|A farmhouse in Chengdu Plain.|245x245px]]\n\n===Ecological Type===\nWith the change of time, social development, improvement of living standards and the progress of rural-urban integration, at the same time Linpan also changing. The villagers no longer satisfied with living a life of self-sufficient farming, have moved to the urban area from Linpan Settlement, which has caused some empty Linpan Settlements. The role of these \"Empty Linpan\" is no longer for living, but has transformed to the ecological Linpan which has an ecological function for preserving the local environment.\n\n===Rural Tourism Type===\nAt present, the rapid population growth led to urban sprawl and dwindling agricultural land resources. Rural tourism as a compound of agricultural production and economic activities has become more and more popular. Thus, the Rural Tourism type of Linpan emerged in the Chengdu Plain. This type of Linpan mostly located in suburban areas, relying on agricultural production and make full use of the environment and transport advantages to develop rural inn and farmhouse catering services. It not only can satisfy local people's production and living needs, but also provide a tourism and vacation place for urban residents.\n\n===Specific Industrial Type===\nThe main function of agricultural and forest land in specific industrial Linpan is production. Generally, the requirements of landscape aesthetics are less than the other types of Linpan. This type of Linpan creates multiple agricultural eco-landscape. This kind of Linpan makes use of the traditional specific industry and enhances it, such as anti-season greenhouse vegetables and fruits, courtyard economy, livestock raising, and other specific industries.\n\n==The Threaten of Linpan in Chengdu Plain==\nWith the implementation of changes in land-use policies and urban-rural integration in China, most households are grouped together as a group-type settlement during the new rural construction. The original distribution of Linpan formula has been greatly affected by the construction practices of farmers and the government, and the distance between farmers and land is also pulled away. Many factors can cause the number of Linpan Settlement to dwindle. On one hand, many Linpan Settlements were removed or merged into a larger one. On the other hand, with the increasing number of part of the Linpan dwellers drift into cities, many Linpan Settlements are lack of management and change to be \u201cHollow Linpan\u201d. All of these lead the number of Linpan Settlement decreasing each year. [[Pi County]], a country near Chengdu, had more than 11,000 Linpan Settlement while there only has 8,000 now. A recent survey shows that the number of Linpan which holds more than 10 households living in is less than 900.<ref name=\"Fan Yanzhi\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Agriculture and Agronomy}}\n\n* [[Dujiangyan irrigation system]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.chengdu.gov.cn/ Linpan Settlement in Xinjin County] {{in lang|zh-cn}}\n*[http://www.chengdu.gov.cn/info/00020103/2010/5/12/321961info.shtml Garden City Construction and Linpan Protection] {{in lang|zh-cn}}\n{{Sichuan topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{coord missing|Sichuan}}\n\n[[Category:Sichuan|Sichuan]]\n[[Category:Culture in Sichuan]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Sichuan]]\n[[Category:Culture in Chengdu]]\n[[Category:Cultural landscapes]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|date=February 2020}}\n\n\nThe '''Linpan in Chengdu Plain''', also called ''Linpan settlement'', is a traditional rural community in [[Chengdu Plain]], [[Sichuan]], [[China]], characterized by small scale farming, rectangular fields, trees and bamboo, all supported by an ancient irrigation system, known as the [[Dujiangyan Irrigation System]]. The system melds traditional farming behavior and culture, and the rural landscape of Chengdu Plain is beautiful and unique because of the typical element of the \"Linpan\".<ref name=\"the rural landscape\">{{cite journal|last1=Yang|first1=Qingjuan|last2=Li|first2=Bei|last3=Li|first3=Kui|title=The Rural Landscape Research in Chengdu's Urban-rural Integration Development|journal=Procedia Engineering|date=2011|volume=21|issue=1|pages=780\u2013788|doi=10.1016/j.proeng.2011.11.2078|doi-access=free}}</ref> \n\nThe Linpan in Chengdu Plain originated during the [[:zh:\u53e4\u8700\u6587\u660e|Ancient Shu Civilization]] and formed after a long period of immigration.<ref name=\"Fan Yanzhi\" /> Western Sichuan Plain is an important source of Taoism, a philosophy which prioritizing pleasure, leisure, and the freedom of life, thus forming the social basis for Linpan culture. This way of life is currently under threat from development and pollution.\n[[File:A Typical Linpan unit in Pi County.jpg|center|thumb|519x519px|A Typical Linpan Unit in Pi County]]\n\n==Introduction==\nThe LinPan in Chengdu Plain, as a principle rustic landscape in the Chengdu Plain, might be defined as a complex habitation mode. Generalized Linpan in Chengdu Plain refers to the Linpan Settlement system in the region of Chengdu Plain, also known as Linpan settlement. Moreover, LinPan in Chengdu Plain is representative of farming type in western Sichuan that combines production and daily life in one landscape. It is understood that the cores of Linpan in Chengdu plain are trees and bamboo, but the main features of this landscape are water, houses, and fields. It is usually inhabited by surname or clan as settlement units showing the layout in a decentralized manner and in the form of a typical natural village. Small-scale Linpan generally has only a few dozen peasant families, however large-scale Linpan may contain hundreds of households.\n\nLinpan in Chengdu Plain originated during the [[:zh:\u53e4\u8700\u6587\u660e|Ancient Shu Civilization]] and formed in a long period of immigration, which has been thousands of years history. It is not only reflected in the local farming culture but also is the crystallization of the traditional farming civilization era. The Linpan Settlement system coordinates with local farming conditions, traditional farming behavior and living life, and plays a crucial role in preserving the environment of Chengdu Plain.<ref name=\"Fan Yanzhi\">{{cite thesis |last=Fan |first=Yanzhi |date=2009 |title=\u5ddd\u897f\u6797\u76d8\u73af\u5883\u666f\u89c2\u4fdd\u62a4\u6027\u89c4\u5212\u8bbe\u8ba1\u7814\u7a76 |trans-title= |type=MSc |chapter= |publisher=Sichuan Agricultural University |docket= |oclc= |url=http://cdmd.cnki.com.cn/Article/CDMD-10626-2009258597.htm |access-date=}}</ref> Furthermore, it has society, culture, aesthetic and ecology value and make the rural landscape of Chengdu Plain different from the other area of China. The key reasons that it came into being, can be analyzed as a natural environment, farm culture, the history of immigration, society culture.<ref name=\"Linpan book\">{{cite book|last1=Duang|first1=Peng|last2=Liu|first2=Tianhou|title=\u6797\u76d8: \u8700\u6587\u5316\u4e4b\u751f\u6001\u5bb6\u56ed|trans-title=Linpan: The ecological homeland of Shu culture|date=2004|publisher=Sichuan Science Technology Press|location=Chengdu|isbn=978-7-5364-5577-1|edition=Di 1 ban.}}</ref>\n\nThe rural landscape of Chengdu can be described as patches (the vast plain of farmland), corridors (roads and irrigation Canals), and matrixes (small matrixes are thousands of Linpans, big ones are towns). Linpan is the key element that makes Chengdu rural landscape unique.<ref name=\"the rural landscape\" />\n\n==Features==\n\n===Culture===\nLinpan Settlement in Chengdu Plain inherited Chinese traditional farming culture and has a farming history for thousands of years, but it also has its own characteristics. [[Sichuan]] is a historic and typical region of traditional intensive farming culture in China, while the Chengdu Plain, is an important place of origin and development of this culture. Chengdu Plain provides the requisite conditions for the continuation and development of the farming culture, such as pleasant environmental conditions, warm and humid climate, abundant water and fertile land.\n\nIn the second place, Linpan in Chengdu Plain combines the [[Dujiangyan irrigation system]], agricultural production, family system and lifestyle, that integrates the daily life in Chengdu Plain, production and ecological environment. It is a perfect combined spatial form of cultural symbol and use value. Linpan in Chengdu Plain formed as the basis of millennial Dujiangyan irrigation works, which solved the decisive factor, water, for the farming culture development. Formed a pattern of ecological farming, which regards the Dujiangyan irrigation system as its core, Chengdu plain as its hinterland and Longquan Range as its protective screen. The intensive Linpan Settlements fully reflect the farming culture which has the Sichuan water cultural characteristic.\n\n===Ecology===\nChengdu Plain irrigated by the Dujiangyan irrigation system is a semi-natural wetland ecosystem. It provides a habitat for birds, but also provides a food base and living space for human beings. The symbiosis of people and woods even more continues today. The mainly landscape elements in this living environment are fields, woods, farmhouse and water, and these four main elements are harmony and interdependence\uff1a\n\n*Pattern of woods-water, creates the integration of woods forest network and water network.\n*Pattern of woods-fields, shows high performance in biodiversity.\n*Pattern of woods-farm house, creates a pleasant microclimate.\nIn terms of vegetation other than crops,  the dominant plant type in Chengdu Plain is evergreen broad-leaved forest because Chengdu locates in the subtropical humid monsoon climate zone. Affected by the same rainfall and heat pattern, Linpan demonstrates similar zonal characteristics in the natural distribution of plant community structure with some distinctive variations. In the Linpan landscape, the main vegetation types surrounding residential buildings are evergreen broad-leaved forests and bamboo stands with frequencies of 25% and 32%, respectively. In contrast to the overall high biodiversity of Linpan as a rural settlement, the vegetation around houses are rather uniform. In most farming Linpan, the plant structure is dominated by a single type of tree or bamboo such as Metasequoia or Cedar. The relatively mixed forests mostly exist in Linpan aiming at developing rural tourism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u5b59\u5927\u6c5f|last2=\u9648\u5176\u5175|last3=\u80e1\u5ead\u5174|last4=\u5218\u5149\u7acb|last5=\u5b59\u5927\u8fdc|last6=\u7f57\u542f\u9ad8|date=2011|title=\u5ddd\u897f\u6797\u76d8\u7fa4\u843d\u7c7b\u578b\u53ca\u5176\u591a\u6837\u6027|url=http://www.cqvip.com/qk/91109x/201101/37279682.html|journal=\u56db\u5ddd\u519c\u4e1a\u5927\u5b66\u5b66\u62a5|volume=29|issue=1}}</ref>\n\n===Form===\nThe whole Linpan settlement in Chengdu Plain that lies between the cities and towns as roads crisscross, coupled with the water-intensive. It is in space to form a \"checkerboard\" pattern, such a network, which distributed a number of scattered Linpan landscape units.<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Zhao |first=Rongming |date=2006 |title=\u6210\u90fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8fb9\u7f18\u533a\u4e61\u6751\u805a\u843d\u89c4\u5212\u8bbe\u8ba1\u9762\u4e34\u7684\u95ee\u9898\u4e0e\u5bf9\u7b56\u7814\u7a76 |trans-title= |type=MSc |chapter= |publisher=Southwest Jiaotong University |docket= |oclc= |url=http://d.wanfangdata.com.cn/Thesis/Y1019960 |access-date=}}</ref> Linpan Settlement generally based on single-family or family group as a unit, scattered among the field.\n\nIn terms of shape, it is characterized by small-scale and recognizability. The scale of the farm village in the Chengdu Plain is very small. The radius of the buildings, surrounding courtyards and [[bamboo]]s always within 30 meters. This kind of compact small village has a strong identifiable and easy for people to grasp farming activities.\n\nThe buildings in Linpan are generally typical one-story Western Sichuan folk residential buildings with a Galley or L-shape layout built by individual households respectively. Usually, 3-5 households form a small Linpan unit, and 20-30 households form a big Linpan unit, which is surrounded by tall trees and bamboos to shelter from the wind.\n\nOne of the most significant features of Linpan and almost all Western Sichuan folk housing is that the buildings always enclose a courtyard called \u201cBaba\u201d, and \u201cBaba\u201d is where most domestic and interactive activities happen. People dry crops, hang out washed clothes, talk and play [[Mahjong]] with neighbors, and even host family banquets (Baba Yan) in the \"Baba\" courtyards.\n\n== The Causes for the Formation of Linpan Culture ==\n\n=== Geographical and Environmental Conditions ===\nChengdu Plain is a relatively independent and complete geographic unit sitting in the western [[Sichuan Basin]]. The area of Chengdu Plain is about 9100 square kilometers in size and 450\u2013750 meters in altitude. Chengdu Plain is a river alluvial plain, and its fertile soil and large open flat land provide a firm foundation for farming development. In addition, the mild subtropical monsoon climate brings rich heat and abundant rainfall, making it suitable for human habitation and production. With the warm winter and the early spring, crops and bamboos can grow year-round. Another unique advantage of the Chengdu Plain is the well-developed irrigation system.  After the construction of [[Dujiangyan]], most farmlands achieved gravity irrigation. Along with ample surface and groundwater resources, the dispersed rural living pattern became possible.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.cnki.com.cn/Article_en/CJFDTOTAL-CDDB201105014.htm|title=On Causes for Formation of Linpan Culture in West Sichuan Plain--\u300aJournal of Chengdu University(Social Sciences)\u300b2011\u5e7405\u671f|website=en.cnki.com.cn|access-date=2017-11-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Economics and Production ===\nThe relatively stable climate and advanced water irrigation and management system in western Sichuan provide a powerful guarantee for the independent farming of individual households. In order to promote crop production, farmers choose to live scattered near their own land to devote more labor to intensive rice farming. In addition, the scattered pattern solves the shortcomings of long-distance transportation in the fields. Moreover, surplus manpower and large courtyards make it possible for farmers to supplement agricultural income by operating home textiles, bamboo basket weaving or raising livestock, and grow fruits and vegetables. With all these factors, the production of the Linpan gradually evolved into the current pattern.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Migration ===\nThere have been six large-scale migrations in history from other provinces to Sichuan province, creating the unique and inclusive culture of an immigrant society. Migrants promoted the social and economic development of the region in many ways and various customs they introduced created the compatible features of a new culture. During the migration process, bloodlines were broken and the concept of clans was diluted, so rather than being bind by kinships, people were more related by geography and production approximately. In the new settlements, people could be equal regardless of their origins, allowing the Linpan culture of a scattered living pattern to flourish.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Culture and Customs ===\nWestern Sichuan Plain is an important source of [[Taoism]]. Since the [[:zh:\u53e4\u8700\u6587\u660e|Ancient Shu Civilization]], people living in the region have valued nature and freedom over careers and regulations. Later generations of the Shu in the unique geographical and cultural environment also inherited the philosophy of prioritizing pleasure, leisure, and the freedom of life, which formed the social basis for Linpan culture. Another reason explaining the settlement pattern is the tradition of living separately in single-family homes, instead of large unified homes with parents and relatives. By splitting up into smaller units, there are more initiative and flexibility for households to live and produce.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Distribution of Linpan==\nLinpan Settlement mainly distributed in the Chengdu Plain, however, Chengdu Plain belongs to the Sichuan Basin. [[Sichuan Basin]] is one of the famous big basins in China, whose terrain is relatively inaccessible. It is surrounded by 1000\u20132000 meters above sea level mountain, one of the few mountains up to an altitude of 3000\u20134000 meters. Basin covers an area of about 170,000 square kilometers, mostly in elevation between 300\u2013700 meters.\n\nThe Chengdu Plain covers an area of about 23,000 square kilometers and is the largest plain in southwestern China. It lies on the marginal region of the Sichuan Basin and rivers from the high mountains to the north and west brings soil and water supply to the vast land.<ref name=\"GO CD\">{{cite web|title=What makes Chengdu the Land of Abundance|url=http://www.gochengdu.cn/culture/city-profile/what-makes-chengdu-the-land-of-abundance-a593.html|website=GO CHENGDU|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> The Chengdu Plain located among Longquan range, [[Longmen Mountains]] and [[Qionglai Mountains]].<ref name=\"Linpan book\" /> The great [[Min River (Sichuan)|Minjiang River]], together with its tributaries, runs across the Chengdu Plain to form an expansive water network.<ref name=\"GO CD\" /> Because the formation of factors, Linpan mainly distributed in flat terrain area, that the most typical ones are in the Chengdu Plain. In addition to Sichuan in China's western provinces of [[Yunnan]], [[Guizhou]] and other places also have distribution.\n\nThe typical Linpan Settlements mainly distributed in 14 districts(cities) of Chengdu Plain are [[Longquanyi District]], [[Pi County]], [[Wenjiang District]], [[Shuangliu District]], [[Xindu District]], [[Qingbaijiang District]], [[Dayi County]], [[Xinjin County]], [[Jintang County]], [[Pujiang County, Sichuan|Pujiang County]], [[Dujiangyan City]], [[Pengzhou]], [[Chongzhou|Chongzhou City]], [[Qionglai City]], covers an area of 11,711 square kilometers. According to statistics, Linpan in Chengdu Plain demonstrates a  wide distribution (area of 9482 square kilometers). a total of 141,100 existing Linpan, Linpan total area of 67,679.87 hectares, the population living within Linpan 449.03 million, accounting for 41.50 percent of the total population of the city region, representing the city 77.09% of the total rural population; Linpan per capita area of 150 square meters. The number of existing Linpan is around 141,100, with a total area of 67,679.87 hectares. The resident population of Linpan in Chengdu is about 449.03 million, accounting for 41.50% of the total population of the city region and 77.09% of the city total rural population.<ref name=\"jianwei\">{{cite journal|last1=Chengdu|first1=Urban and Rural Construction Commission|title=\u6210\u90fd\u7f16\u5236\u89c4\u5212\u4fdd\u62a4\u5ddd\u897f\u6797\u76d8\u98ce\u8c8c|journal=Urban Planning Newsreport|date=2007|volume=17|pages=8\u20139|url=http://www.cnki.com.cn/Article/CJFDTotal-CSGT200717010.htm}}</ref>\n\n==Types of Linpan Settlement==\n\n===Farming Type===\nThis type of Linpan settlement mainly focuses on agricultural production. The vegetation and buildings in this kind of Linpan Settlement should harmonize with the fields, and it is the ecological residence of the rural population who engaged in agricultural activities. It is also a typical vector, which is the symbiosis of people, fields, buildings, woods, and water. There are some unique spatial features of the farming Linpan, which provide spaces for drying cereals and corn, stacking farming tools, intensively-reared livestock, etc. These characteristics are reflected in this kind of Linpan settlement farming as the main mode of industrial structure.\n[[File:Farmhouse in Chengdu Plain.jpg|thumb|right|A farmhouse in Chengdu Plain.|245x245px]]\n\n===Ecological Type===\nWith the change of time, social development, improvement of living standards and the progress of rural-urban integration, at the same time Linpan also changing. The villagers no longer satisfied with living a life of self-sufficient farming, have moved to the urban area from Linpan Settlement, which has caused some empty Linpan Settlements. The role of these \"Empty Linpan\" is no longer for living, but has transformed to the ecological Linpan which has an ecological function for preserving the local environment.\n\n===Rural Tourism Type===\nAt present, the rapid population growth led to urban sprawl and dwindling agricultural land resources. Rural tourism as a compound of agricultural production and economic activities has become more and more popular. Thus, the Rural Tourism type of Linpan emerged in the Chengdu Plain. This type of Linpan mostly located in suburban areas, relying on agricultural production and make full use of the environment and transport advantages to develop rural inn and farmhouse catering services. It not only can satisfy local people's production and living needs, but also provide a tourism and vacation place for urban residents.\n\n===Specific Industrial Type===\nThe main function of agricultural and forest land in specific industrial Linpan is production. Generally, the requirements of landscape aesthetics are less than the other types of Linpan. This type of Linpan creates multiple agricultural eco-landscape. This kind of Linpan makes use of the traditional specific industry and enhances it, such as anti-season greenhouse vegetables and fruits, courtyard economy, livestock raising, and other specific industries.\n\n==The Threaten of Linpan in Chengdu Plain==\nWith the implementation of changes in land-use policies and urban-rural integration in China, most households are grouped together as a group-type settlement during the new rural construction. The original distribution of Linpan formula has been greatly affected by the construction practices of farmers and the government, and the distance between farmers and land is also pulled away. Many factors can cause the number of Linpan Settlement to dwindle. On one hand, many Linpan Settlements were removed or merged into a larger one. On the other hand, with the increasing number of part of the Linpan dwellers drift into cities, many Linpan Settlements are lack of management and change to be \u201cHollow Linpan\u201d. All of these lead the number of Linpan Settlement decreasing each year. [[Pi County]], a country near Chengdu, had more than 11,000 Linpan Settlement while there only has 8,000 now. A recent survey shows that the number of Linpan which holds more than 10 households living in is less than 900.<ref name=\"Fan Yanzhi\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Agriculture and Agronomy}}\n\n* [[Dujiangyan irrigation system]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.chengdu.gov.cn/ Linpan Settlement in Xinjin County] {{in lang|zh-cn}}\n*[http://www.chengdu.gov.cn/info/00020103/2010/5/12/321961info.shtml Garden City Construction and Linpan Protection] {{in lang|zh-cn}}\n{{Sichuan topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{coord missing|Sichuan}}\n\n[[Category:Sichuan|Sichuan]]\n[[Category:Culture in Sichuan]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Sichuan]]\n[[Category:Culture in Chengdu]]\n[[Category:Cultural landscapes]]\n[[Category:Agriculture in China]]\n", "name_user": "Rxde220", "label": "safe", "comment": "Copy editing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linpan_in_Chengdu_Plain"}
{"title_page": "Bojay\u00e1 massacre", "text_new": "{{Infobox terrorist attack\n|title = Bojay\u00e1 massacre\n|image = {{Location map many | Colombia\n| width = 300\n| float = centre\n| label = Bojay\u00e1\n   | pos = right\n   | marksize = 8\n   | lat_deg = 6.523611\n   | lon_deg = -76.974444\n}}\n|caption = \n|location = [[Bojay\u00e1]], [[Choc\u00f3 Department|Choc\u00f3]]<br/>[[Colombia]]\n|target = Civilians caught in the cross fire between the [[United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia|AUC paramilitaries]] and [[FARC|FARC guerrillas]]\n|date = 2 May 2002\n|time = \n|timezone = \n|type = [[shooting]], [[mass murder]], [[massacre]]\n|fatalities = 119 civilians (including 45 children)<ref name=\"centrodememoriahistorica\">{{cite web|url= https://www.centrodememoriahistorica.gov.co/descargas/informes2010/informe_bojaya.pdf|title= Bojay\u00e1: La guerra sin l\u00edmites|publisher= centrodememoriahistorica.gov.co|accessdate= 7 May 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171021174336/http://www.centrodememoriahistorica.gov.co/descargas/informes2010/informe_bojaya.pdf|archive-date= 21 October 2017|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n|injuries = 98\n|perps = {{flagicon image|Flag of the FARC-EP.svg}} [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia|FARC]]\n|weapons = [[small arms]], [[Improvised explosive device|IEDs]]\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Colombian conflict|state=collapsed}}\n[[File:Bellavista Viejo - Church interior.jpg|thumb|304x304px|The church, after renovations.]]\nThe '''Bojay\u00e1 massacre''' ({{lang-es|La Masacre de Bojay\u00e1}}) was a [[massacre]] that occurred on May 2, 2002 in the [[Colombia]]n town of [[Bojay\u00e1|Bellavista]] in the Bojay\u00e1 municipality of the [[Choc\u00f3 Department|Choc\u00f3]] department. [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia|FARC]] [[guerrilla warfare|guerrillas]] seized the town in an attempt to take control of the [[Atrato River]] region from [[United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia|AUC]] paramilitaries. During the fighting one of  Cylinder Bombs (known in Spanish as a ''pipeta'' or ''Cilindro bomba'') launched by the FARC with a [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] at the AUC paramilitaries using the walls of the church for shelter, went trough the roof of the church, landing on the altar inside. Of the approximately 300 inhabitants that had taken refuge in the church, approximately 119 died in the explosion<ref name=\"centrodememoriahistorica\" />.\n\n==Background==\nThe Colombian government had described the area as subject to \"the armed confrontation in the region between the guerrillas and the illegal self-defence forces is very violent due to the economic and strategic interests in play, including, among others: [[drug trafficking]], the inter-oceanic connection, the development of [[megaproject]]s like the Panamerican Highway, and the proximity of ports and hydroelectric stations. The region furthermore represents advantages for these groups as a route for the import of arms and supplies from Central America and to provide favourable routes for drug trafficking.\" <ref name=DHreport>{{cite book | last= Ministerio de Defensa Nacional | title= Informe Anual Derechos Humanos y DIH 2000 |publisher= Rep\u00fablica de Colombia, Ministerio de Defensa Nacional |pages= 132, 133 }}</ref>\n\n==Preceding events==\nAt least 250 paramilitary combatants moved in to Bellavista, the administrative centre of the municipality of Bojay\u00e1, on 21 April 2002. They remained there despite protests by local residents. The UNHCHR sent an official communication to the Colombian government on April 23 expressing their concern regarding the presence of the paramilitaries and the possible consequences for the local people. The [[Ombudsman's Office of Colombia]] also visited the region on April 26 and released an early warning regarding the threat of  an armed confrontation in the area.<ref name=UNreport>{{cite book | last= UNHCHR | title= Informe de la Oficina en Colombia del Alto Comisionado de las Naciones Unidas para los Derechos Humanos sobre su Misi\u00f3n de Observaci\u00f3n en el Medio Atrato |date=20 May 2002|url= http://www.hchr.org.co/documentoseinformes/informes/tematicos/bojaya.pdf |publisher= Oficina en Colombia del Alto Comisionado de las Naciones Unidas para los Derechos Humanos |pages= }}</ref>\n\nIntense fighting broke out on May 1 in neighboring town [[Vig\u00eda del Fuerte]] and spread to Bellavista later in the day. Around 300 residents took shelter in the local church, 100 in the adjoining parsonage, and another 100 in the Augustinian Missionary residence, over the course of the night.<ref name=UNreport/><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Bojay\u00e1: La Guerra Sin L\u00edmites|collaboration=CNRR - Grupo de Memoria Hist\u00f3rica|publisher=Taurus|year=2010|isbn=978-958-758-024-2|location=Bogat\u00e1, Colombia|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Details of the attack==\nAccording to the official UN investigation report, in the morning of May 2 the AUC paramilitaries had established positions around the church, using the rare concrete buildings and the cement wall around the church yard for protection. The FARC took up positions to the north (in Barrio Pueblo Nuevo), and began launching gas cylinder bombs (''pipetas'') toward the paramilitary positions. Two landed nearby and the third went through the roof of the church, where it exploded on the altar.\n\nThe explosion resulted in approximately 119 dead and 98 wounded, though the UN was not able to verify exact numbers. A large number of the dead and wounded were children.<ref name=UNreport/>\n\nThe UN investigation found the FARC in violation of several principles of international humanitarian law, including an indiscriminate attack causing unnecessary civilian casualties, failure to distinguish between civilian and combatant, failure to take efforts to protect civilians from avoidable harm, and attacks against cultural property. Prohibitions against these acts are found in Common Article 3 of the [[Fourth Geneva Convention|1949 Geneva Conventions]] and Articles 4, 13, and 16 of Additional Protocol II. The UN also considered the FARC responsible for the forced displacement of civilians generated as a consequence of the attack on the church, placing the act in violation of Article 17 of Protocol II.<ref name=UNreport/>\n\nThe UN also found the AUC in violation of various aspects of international humanitarian law, including using civilians as human shields, failing to protect civilians from the effects of their military operations, and for causing massive forced displacement of civilian populations in the region due to their acts, threats and combat operations in the area. Given reports of theft by the AUC of goods, equipment and vehicles belonging to local residents, the UN also found the AUC guilty of pillage (a violation of Article 17 of Protocol II).<ref name=UNreport/>\n\nThe UNHCHR also found that the Colombian government failed to act in order to prevent the massive human suffering resulting from the events in Bojaya: suffering that was predicted and of which the government was explicitly warned beforehand.<ref name=UNreport/>\n\n==Responsibility of the state==\nThe First Administrative Court of [[Quibd\u00f3|Quibdo]], Choc\u00f3 sentenced the Colombian State to a billion and a half Colombian peso compensation to relatives of two of the dead victims on May 29, 2008. It ruled the State was administratively responsible and had neglected to protect its citizens, despite the warnings of the ombudsman.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://colombiareports.com/2008/05/29/colombian-state-sentenced-to-pay-compensation-to-bojaya-victims/\n|title=Colombian State sentenced to pay compensation to Bojay\u00e1 victims\n|date=May 29, 2008\n|publisher=Colombia Reports\n|access-date=2008-05-29}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Death of perpetrator==\n[[File:Casa de la Hermanas Agustinas.jpg|thumb|303x303px|The residence of the Augustinian Nuns, where around 100 people took refuge, now abandoned.]]\nAt dawn of 22 February 2012, nearly 10 years after the event, a [[Colombian Air Force]] [[Embraer Super Tucano|EMB-314]] aircraft identified the camp of FARC's 57th Front, 15 kilometers north of Bojay\u00e1 near the border with Panama. The Super Tucano dropped two high-precision bombs, destroying the camp and killing six FARC rebels, including Pedro Alfonso Alvarado alias \"Mapanao\", who are beleived to have been responsible for the massacre.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130118174804/http://www.canalrcnmsn.com/noticias/as%C3%AD_fue_atacado_por_la_fuerza_a%C3%A9rea_campamento_de_las_farc_en_choc%C3%B3 \"As\u00ed fue atacado por la Fuerza A\u00e9rea campamento de las Farc en Choc\u00f3\" (in Spanish).] ''Canal RCN, '' 23 February 2012. Retrieved 23 February 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.elpais.com.co/elpais/judicial/noticias/santos-anuncia-muerte-responsable-masacre-bojaya \"Cay\u00f3 alias \u2018mapanao\u2019, autor de la masacre de Bojay\u00e1\" (in Spanish).] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115233557/http://www.elpais.com.co/elpais/judicial/noticias/santos-anuncia-muerte-responsable-masacre-bojaya |date=2016-01-15 }} ''El Pa\u00eds, '' 22 February 2012. Retrieved 23 February 2012.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Colombia]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}<br />{{Colombia_conflict|state=collapsed}}\n{{coord missing|Colombia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bojaya massacre}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2002]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2002]]\n[[Category:Political repression in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Massacres committed by FARC]]\n[[Category:2002 crimes in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Colombian conflict (1964\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:May 2002 events in South America]]\n[[Category:2002 murders in South America]]\n[[Category:2000s murders in Colombia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox terrorist attack\n|title = Bojay\u00e1 massacre\n|image = {{Location map many | Colombia\n| width = 300\n| float = centre\n| label = Bojay\u00e1\n   | pos = right\n   | marksize = 8\n   | lat_deg = 6.523611\n   | lon_deg = -76.974444\n}}\n|caption = \n|location = [[Bojay\u00e1]], [[Choc\u00f3 Department|Choc\u00f3]]<br/>[[Colombia]]\n|target = Civilians caught in the cross fire between the [[United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia|AUC paramilitaries]] and [[FARC|FARC guerrillas]]\n|date = 2 May 2002\n|time = \n|timezone = \n|type = [[shooting]], [[mass murder]], [[massacre]]\n|fatalities = 119 civilians (including 45 children)<ref name=\"centrodememoriahistorica\">{{cite web|url= https://www.centrodememoriahistorica.gov.co/descargas/informes2010/informe_bojaya.pdf|title= Bojay\u00e1: La guerra sin l\u00edmites|publisher= centrodememoriahistorica.gov.co|accessdate= 7 May 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171021174336/http://www.centrodememoriahistorica.gov.co/descargas/informes2010/informe_bojaya.pdf|archive-date= 21 October 2017|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n|injuries = 98\n|perps = {{flagicon image|Flag of the FARC-EP.svg}} [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia|FARC]]\n|weapons = [[small arms]], [[Improvised explosive device|IEDs]]\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Colombian conflict|state=collapsed}}\n[[File:Bellavista Viejo - Church interior.jpg|thumb|304x304px|The church, after renovations.]]\nThe '''Bojay\u00e1 massacre''' ({{lang-es|La Masacre de Bojay\u00e1}}) was a [[massacre]] that occurred on May 2, 2002 in the [[Colombia]]n town of [[Bojay\u00e1|Bellavista]] in the Bojay\u00e1 municipality of the [[Choc\u00f3 Department|Choc\u00f3]] department. [[Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia|FARC]] [[guerrilla warfare|guerrillas]] seized the town in an attempt to take control of the [[Atrato River]] region from [[United Self-Defense Forces of Colombia|AUC]] paramilitaries. During the fighting one of  Cylinder Bombs (known in Spanish as a ''pipeta'' or ''Cilindro bomba'') launched by the FARC with a [[Mortar (weapon)|mortar]] at the AUC paramilitaries using the walls of the church for shelter, went trough the roof of the church, landing on the altar inside. Of the approximately 300 inhabitants that had taken refuge in the town, approximately 119 died in the explosion<ref name=\"centrodememoriahistorica\" />.\n\n==Background==\nThe Colombian government had described the area as subject to \"the armed confrontation in the region between the guerrillas and the illegal self-defence forces is very violent due to the economic and strategic interests in play, including, among others: [[drug trafficking]], the inter-oceanic connection, the development of [[megaproject]]s like the Panamerican Highway, and the proximity of ports and hydroelectric stations. The region furthermore represents advantages for these groups as a route for the import of arms and supplies from Central America and to provide favourable routes for drug trafficking.\" <ref name=DHreport>{{cite book | last= Ministerio de Defensa Nacional | title= Informe Anual Derechos Humanos y DIH 2000 |publisher= Rep\u00fablica de Colombia, Ministerio de Defensa Nacional |pages= 132, 133 }}</ref>\n\n==Preceding events==\nAt least 250 paramilitary combatants moved in to Bellavista, the administrative centre of the municipality of Bojay\u00e1, on 21 April 2002. They remained there despite protests by local residents. The UNHCHR sent an official communication to the Colombian government on April 23 expressing their concern regarding the presence of the paramilitaries and the possible consequences for the local people. The [[Ombudsman's Office of Colombia]] also visited the region on April 26 and released an early warning regarding the threat of  an armed confrontation in the area.<ref name=UNreport>{{cite book | last= UNHCHR | title= Informe de la Oficina en Colombia del Alto Comisionado de las Naciones Unidas para los Derechos Humanos sobre su Misi\u00f3n de Observaci\u00f3n en el Medio Atrato |date=20 May 2002|url= http://www.hchr.org.co/documentoseinformes/informes/tematicos/bojaya.pdf |publisher= Oficina en Colombia del Alto Comisionado de las Naciones Unidas para los Derechos Humanos |pages= }}</ref>\n\nIntense fighting broke out on May 1 in neighboring town [[Vig\u00eda del Fuerte]] and spread to Bellavista later in the day. Around 300 residents took shelter in the local church, 100 in the adjoining parsonage, and another 100 in the Augustinian Missionary residence, over the course of the night.<ref name=UNreport/><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Bojay\u00e1: La Guerra Sin L\u00edmites|collaboration=CNRR - Grupo de Memoria Hist\u00f3rica|publisher=Taurus|year=2010|isbn=978-958-758-024-2|location=Bogat\u00e1, Colombia|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Details of the attack==\nAccording to the official UN investigation report, in the morning of May 2 the AUC paramilitaries had established positions around the church, using the rare concrete buildings and the cement wall around the church yard for protection. The FARC took up positions to the north (in Barrio Pueblo Nuevo), and began launching gas cylinder bombs (''pipetas'') toward the paramilitary positions. Two landed nearby and the third went through the roof of the church, where it exploded on the altar.\n\nThe explosion resulted in approximately 119 dead and 98 wounded, though the UN was not able to verify exact numbers. A large number of the dead and wounded were children.<ref name=UNreport/>\n\nThe UN investigation found the FARC in violation of several principles of international humanitarian law, including an indiscriminate attack causing unnecessary civilian casualties, failure to distinguish between civilian and combatant, failure to take efforts to protect civilians from avoidable harm, and attacks against cultural property. Prohibitions against these acts are found in Common Article 3 of the [[Fourth Geneva Convention|1949 Geneva Conventions]] and Articles 4, 13, and 16 of Additional Protocol II. The UN also considered the FARC responsible for the forced displacement of civilians generated as a consequence of the attack on the church, placing the act in violation of Article 17 of Protocol II.<ref name=UNreport/>\n\nThe UN also found the AUC in violation of various aspects of international humanitarian law, including using civilians as human shields, failing to protect civilians from the effects of their military operations, and for causing massive forced displacement of civilian populations in the region due to their acts, threats and combat operations in the area. Given reports of theft by the AUC of goods, equipment and vehicles belonging to local residents, the UN also found the AUC guilty of pillage (a violation of Article 17 of Protocol II).<ref name=UNreport/>\n\nThe UNHCHR also found that the Colombian government failed to act in order to prevent the massive human suffering resulting from the events in Bojaya: suffering that was predicted and of which the government was explicitly warned beforehand.<ref name=UNreport/>\n\n==Responsibility of the state==\nThe First Administrative Court of [[Quibd\u00f3|Quibdo]], Choc\u00f3 sentenced the Colombian State to a billion and a half Colombian peso compensation to relatives of two of the dead victims on May 29, 2008. It ruled the State was administratively responsible and had neglected to protect its citizens, despite the warnings of the ombudsman.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://colombiareports.com/2008/05/29/colombian-state-sentenced-to-pay-compensation-to-bojaya-victims/\n|title=Colombian State sentenced to pay compensation to Bojay\u00e1 victims\n|date=May 29, 2008\n|publisher=Colombia Reports\n|access-date=2008-05-29}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Death of perpetrator==\n[[File:Casa de la Hermanas Agustinas.jpg|thumb|303x303px|The residence of the Augustinian Nuns, where around 100 people took refuge, now abandoned.]]\nAt dawn of 22 February 2012, nearly 10 years after the event, a [[Colombian Air Force]] [[Embraer Super Tucano|EMB-314]] aircraft identified the camp of FARC's 57th Front, 15 kilometers north of Bojay\u00e1 near the border with Panama. The Super Tucano dropped two high-precision bombs, destroying the camp and killing six FARC rebels, including Pedro Alfonso Alvarado alias \"Mapanao\", who are beleived to have been responsible for the massacre.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130118174804/http://www.canalrcnmsn.com/noticias/as%C3%AD_fue_atacado_por_la_fuerza_a%C3%A9rea_campamento_de_las_farc_en_choc%C3%B3 \"As\u00ed fue atacado por la Fuerza A\u00e9rea campamento de las Farc en Choc\u00f3\" (in Spanish).] ''Canal RCN, '' 23 February 2012. Retrieved 23 February 2012</ref><ref>[http://www.elpais.com.co/elpais/judicial/noticias/santos-anuncia-muerte-responsable-masacre-bojaya \"Cay\u00f3 alias \u2018mapanao\u2019, autor de la masacre de Bojay\u00e1\" (in Spanish).] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160115233557/http://www.elpais.com.co/elpais/judicial/noticias/santos-anuncia-muerte-responsable-masacre-bojaya |date=2016-01-15 }} ''El Pa\u00eds, '' 22 February 2012. Retrieved 23 February 2012.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of massacres in Colombia]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}<br />{{Colombia_conflict|state=collapsed}}\n{{coord missing|Colombia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bojaya massacre}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2002]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2002]]\n[[Category:Political repression in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Massacres committed by FARC]]\n[[Category:2002 crimes in Colombia]]\n[[Category:Colombian conflict (1964\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:May 2002 events in South America]]\n[[Category:2002 murders in South America]]\n[[Category:2000s murders in Colombia]]\n", "name_user": "Luukslegers", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bojay%C3%A1_massacre"}
{"title_page": "Death of Jeffrey Epstein", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|High-profile death of Jeffery Epstein in custody}}\n{{Infobox event\n\n| image                    = Epstein Final Mugshot.png\n| image_upright            = 0.8\n| caption                  = Epstein in his final mugshot, taken July&nbsp;8, 2019\n| date                     = {{start date and age|2019|8|10}}\n| time                     = \n| place                    = [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|Metropolitan Correctional Center]], [[New York City]]\n| coordinates              = {{Coord|40.7132|-74.0015|region:US-NY_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| cause                    = Disputed; ruled a [[suicide by hanging]]\n| participants             = \n| outcome                  = Removal of warden, indictments of guards on duty \n| reported deaths          = \n| burial                   =\n| inquiries                = FBI and DOJ investigations\n| inquest                  =\n| coroner                  = New York City Medical Examiner\n| arrests                  = Michael Thomas and Tova Noel\n| suspects                 =\n| accused                  =\n| convicted                =\n| charges                  = Record falsification and conspiracy\n| verdict                  =\n| convictions              =\n| litigation               = \n| url                      = \n| notes                    = \n}}\nOn August 10, 2019, American financier and convicted sex offender [[Jeffrey Epstein]] was found unresponsive in his [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|Metropolitan Correctional Center]] jail cell, where he was awaiting trial on new sex trafficking charges. After prison-guards performed [[CPR]], he was transported in cardiac arrest to [[New York Downtown Hospital]], where he was pronounced dead at 6:39 AM. The [[Office of Chief Medical Examiner of the City of New York|New York City medical examiner]] ruled Epstein's death a suicide by hanging, however, Epstein's lawyers challenged that conclusion and opened their own investigation. [[Michael Baden]], who was hired by Epstein's brother to oversee the autopsy, has since become the most vocal proponent of the theory of homicidal strangulation rather than suicidal hanging.\n\nAfter initially expressing suspicion, Attorney General [[William Barr]] described Epstein's death as \"a perfect storm of screw-ups.\" Both the [[FBI]] and the [[United States Department of Justice Office of the Inspector General|U.S. Department of Justice's Inspector General]] are conducting investigations into the circumstances of his death. The guards on duty were later charged with conspiracy and record falsification. As a result of his death, all charges against Epstein were dismissed, and ongoing sex-trafficking investigations shifted attention towards his alleged associates.\n\nDue to violations of normal jail procedures on the night of Epstein's death,{{efn|group=note|E.g. the removal of his cellmate without a replacement, possession of banned objects, the falling asleep of two guards who were meant to check on him.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/11/nyregion/epstein-death-manhattan-correctional-center.html |title=Before Jail Suicide, Epstein Was Left Alone and Not Closely Monitored |last=Benner |first=Katie |date=August 11, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=August 11, 2019 |last2=Ivory |first2=Danielle |last3=Oppel Jr|first3=Richard A. |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-jeffrey-epstein-cameras-idUSKCN1VI2LC |title=FBI studies two broken cameras outside cell where Epstein died: source |last=Hosenball |first=Mark |date=August 28, 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=August 29, 2019 |location=London |language=en}}</ref>}} the malfunction of two cameras in front of his cell, and his claimed knowledge of compromising information about powerful figures, his death generated speculation and [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/12/nyregion/conspiracy-theories-epstein-suicide.html|title=Epstein Conspiracy Theories: De Blasio, and Others Join Speculation|last=Gold|first=Michael|date=2019-08-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-06|last2=Bromwich|first2=Jonah Engel|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> about the possibility that he was murdered.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/12/business/jeffrey-epstein-interview.html |title=The Day Jeffrey Epstein Told Me He Had Dirt on Powerful People |last1=Stewart |first1=James B. |date=August 12, 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=August 22, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Arrest and imprisonment==\n{{further|Jeffrey Epstein#Trafficking charges}}\n[[File:MCC New York jeh.JPG|thumb|upright=1.25|[[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|The Metropolitan Correctional Center]], where Epstein was held after his 2019 arrest]]\n\nOn July 6, 2019, Jeffrey Epstein was arrested in New York on multiple charges including sex trafficking and placed at the [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|Metropolitan Correctional Center]]{{efn|group=note|Within the MCC, Epstein was placed in the Special Housing Unit to protect him from violence from inmates in the general population.<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2019/07/24/jeffrey-epstein-injured-in-federal-jail-in-manhattan.html</ref>}} in [[Lower Manhattan]].<ref>{{cite news |date=August 12, 2019 |first1=Zachary |last1=Halaschak |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/federal-jail-where-jeffrey-epstein-was-held-has-history-of-security-issues |title=Federal jail where Jeffrey Epstein was held has history of security issues |work=Washington Examiner}}</ref> He pleaded not guilty.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/08/nyregion/jeffrey-epstein-charges.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein Is Indicted on Sex Charges as Discovery of Nude Photos Is Disclosed |first1=Ali |last1=Watkins |date=July 8, 2019 |work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-jeffrey-epstein/financier-epstein-pleads-not-guilty-to-sex-trafficking-charges-involving-girls-idUSKCN1U3136 |title=Financier Epstein pleads not guilty to sex trafficking charges involving girls |first1=Brendan |last1=Pierson |date=July 8, 2019 |work=Reuters |language=en}}</ref> He had earlier faced similar charges in Florida in 2008, but escaped federal charges in a plea deal. Under the plea deal he pled guilty to two state felony charges, paid restitution to three dozen victims identified by the FBI, and registered as a sex offender in both the states of [[Florida]] and [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\"deal\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Julie K.|author-link=Julie K. Brown |title=How a future Trump Cabinet member gave a serial sex abuser the deal of a lifetime |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/article220097825.html |access-date=November 28, 2018 |work=Miami Herald |date=November 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128153832/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/article220097825.html |archive-date=November 28, 2018|url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> On July 18, 2019, Epstein was denied bail after offering [[United States dollar|US$]]600,000 to be able to wear an ankle tracker at his [[New York City]] [[Herbert N. Straus House|townhouse]]. He was viewed as a potential [[Bail in the United States#Federallaw|flight risk]] due to his 20 international flights in the prior 18 months.<ref>{{cite news |date=July 18, 2019 |first1=Bobby |last1=Allyn |first2=Brakkton |last2=Booker |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/18/741802612/jeffrey-epstein-is-denied-bail-in-sex-trafficking-case |title=Jeffrey Epstein Is Denied Bail In Sex Trafficking Case |website=NPR.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=July 18, 2019 |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Kevin |last2=Breuninger |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/07/18/jeffrey-epstein-bail-hearing-in-child-sex-traffic-case.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein's lust for young girls appears 'uncontrollable,' judge says in denying bail to accused sex trafficker |work=CNBC}}</ref> Epstein appealed the bail denial decision to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]]. At the time of his death, this case was still pending.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/07/23/jeffrey-epstein-appeals-bail-denial-decision-in-sex-trafficking-case.html|title=Jeffrey Epstein appeals bail denial decision in child sex trafficking case |first1=Kevin |last1=Breuninger |first2=Dan |last2=Mangan |date=July 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Initial suicide attempt and final weeks===\nOn July 23, Epstein was found semiconscious in his cell with injuries to his neck. He told his lawyers that he had been assaulted by his cellmate.<ref>{{cite news |work=nypost.com |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/14/epstein-told-lawyers-that-cellmate-nicholas-tartaglione-roughed-him-up/ |title=Epstein told lawyers that cellmate Nicholas Tartaglione 'roughed him up' |first1=Bruce |last1=Golding |first2=Emily |last2=Saul |date=August 15, 2019}}</ref>  His cellmate, multiple murder and drug conspiracy suspect Nicholas Tartaglione, was questioned by prison officials but denied harming Epstein.<ref>{{cite web |date=July 25, 2019 |first1=Joelle |last1=Goldstein |url=https://people.com/crime/jeffrey-epstein-found-injured-nyc-jail-cell/ |title=Jeffrey Epstein Found Injured in NYC Jail Cell as Fellow Inmate Denies Assaulting Accused Pedophile |work=People.com |access-date=November 18, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/jeffrey-epstein-former-cellmate-apparent-suicide-attempt |title=Jeffrey Epstein feared cellmate, a muscle-bound ex-cop charged in murder who was moved before financier's death: report |first1=Nicole |last1=Darrah |date=August 12, 2019 |website=Fox News |language=en}}</ref> Tartaglione claimed that he had actually saved Epstein.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-epstein-life-behind-bars-20190726-ujdvknsmz5a4rbcgzfms6cqti4-story.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein's ex-cop cellmate says he saved multimillionaire sex offender from hanging: source |first1=Stephen Rex |last1=Brown |first2=Rocco |last2=Parascandola |date=July 26, 2019 |access-date=December 18, 2019  |work=Daily News |language=en}}</ref> An internal prison investigation cleared Tartaglione in connection with the event.<ref name=\"cleared\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/crime-courts/jeffrey-epstein-s-former-cellmate-cleared-wrongdoing-incident-preceded-his-n1043341 |title=Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate cleared of wrongdoing in incident that preceded his death |last1=Schapiro |first1=Rich |last2=Dienst |first2=Johnathan |date=August 16, 2019 |work=NBC News |access-date=August 21, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> After Epstein's death, Tartaglione was reportedly threatened by jail guards and told to \"stop talking\" after describing Epstein's death and conditions in the jail to the media.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/20/jail-guards-threatening-former-epstein-cell-mate-nicholas-tartaglione-lawyer/ |title=Jail guards threatening former Epstein cellmate Nicholas Tartaglione: lawyer |first1=Emily |last1=Saul |date=August 20, 2019}}</ref> An unnamed source suggested that Epstein staged the incident in order to be transferred.<ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/news/investigations/jeffrey-epstein-found-injured-marks-his-neck-new-york-jail-n1034301</ref> [[Spencer Kuvin]], a lawyer who represented three alleged victims of Epstein, stated in a July 2019 interview following Epstein's first apparent suicide attempt, that he believed it was an attack on his life, and stated there was a high probability that he would be murdered in prison.<ref name=\"Palm\">{{cite web |url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/20190810/jeffrey-epstein-lsquohe-could-buy-anything-including-his-own-deathrsquo |title=Jeffrey Epstein: 'He could buy anything, including his own death' |last1=Ramadan |first1=Lulu |date=August 10, 2019 |website=The Palm Beach Post |language=en |access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/i-question-whether-or-not-it-was-a-true-suicide-attempt-lawyer-for-victims-worried-epstein-wont-make-it-to-trial/ |title='I Do Question Whether It Was a True Suicide Attempt': Victims' Lawyer Worries Epstein Won't Make It to Trial |last1=Clibanoff |first1=Matt |date=July 29, 2019 |work=Law & Crime |access-date=August 11, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the incident, Epstein was placed on [[suicide watch]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/epstein-taken-off-suicide-watch-before-death |title=Jeffrey Epstein was not on suicide watch before death, official says |first1=Louis |last1=Casiano |date=August 10, 2019 |website=Fox News}}</ref> He was placed in an observation cell, surrounded by windows, where lights were left on and any devices that could be used by the prisoner to [[suicide|take his own life]] were not permitted to be retained.<ref name=\"no way\">{{cite news |access-date=November 18, 2019 |first1=Bruce |last1=Golding |first2=Brad |last2=Hamilton |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/theres-no-way-jeffrey-epstein-killed-himself-a-former-nyc-jail-inmate-says |title=There's 'no way' Jeffrey Epstein killed himself, a former NYC jail inmate says |date=August 11, 2019 |website=New York Post}}</ref> Psychological staff dismissed Epstein from suicide watch after six days following a psychiatric examination.<ref name = 60minutes/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/11/jeffrey-epsteins-autopsy-results-are-expected-today-medical-examiner-says.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein's autopsy results expected as FBI and DOJ watchdog investigate apparent suicide |last1=Newburger |first1=Emma |date=August 11, 2019 |work=CNBC |access-date=August 21, 2019}}</ref> Some sources have reported that Epstein was removed from suicide watch after claiming that it was Tartaglione who \"roughed him up.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/14/epstein-told-lawyers-that-cellmate-nicholas-tartaglione-roughed-him-up/ |title=Epstein told lawyers that cellmate Nicholas Tartaglione 'roughed him up' |first1=Bruce |last1=Golding |first2=Emily |last2=Saul |date=August 15, 2019}}</ref> Epstein then returned to the SHU, where he was supposed to have a cellmate and be checked up on every 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/10/nyregion/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-watch.html |title=Why Wasn't Jeffrey Epstein on Suicide Watch When He Died? |first1=Ali |last1=Watkins |date=August 10, 2019 |access-date=December 18, 2019  |work=The New York Times |language=en}}</ref>\n\nEpstein was reportedly depositing funds into other prisoners' accounts to gain their favor or buy protection.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/17/jeffrey-epstein-tried-to-leverage-his-wealth-to-survive-in-jail-report/ |title=Jeffrey Epstein tried to leverage his wealth to survive in jail: report |first1=Eileen AJ |last1=Connelly |first2=Mara |last2=Siegler |date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> A paper note by Epstein was found in his cell after his death. In it, he complained about large bugs crawling on his body, guard Tova Noel giving him burnt food, and a guard intentionally locking him in a shower cell without clothes for an hour.{{efn|group=note|This letter was written in ball-point pen, despite the fact that no prisoners, especially those on suicide watch, were allowed to have one under jail protocol.}}<ref name = 60minutes/> On August 8, Jeffrey Epstein signed his [[Will and testament|last will and testament]], witnessed by two attorneys who knew him. The will named two longtime employees as executors, and immediately gifted  all of his assets, and any assets remaining in his estate, to a trust.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/19/jeffrey-epstein-signed-will-two-days-before-suicide/ |title=Jeffrey Epstein signed will just two days before suicide |last1=DeGregory |first1=Priscilla |last2=Sheehy |first2=Kate |date=August 19, 2019 |website=New York Post |access-date=August 20, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nThe jail informed the Justice Department, when Epstein was placed in the special housing unit (SHU), that he would have a cellmate and that a guard would look into the cell every 30 minutes. These procedures were not followed on the night he died.<ref name=\":36\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/11/nyregion/epstein-death-manhattan-correctional-center.html |title=Before Jail Suicide, Epstein Was Left Alone and Not Closely Monitored |last1=Benner |first1=Katie |date=August 11, 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=August 11, 2019 |last2=Ivory |first2=Danielle |last3=Oppel, Jr. |first3=Richard A. |language=en}}</ref> On August 9, Epstein's cellmate{{efn|group=note|This cellmate, Bill Mersey, noted that Epstein did not seem depressed or suicidal, but it was feasible for someone to hang themselves in a MCC cell.<ref>https://www.crimeonline.com/2020/03/12/jeffrey-epsteins-jailhouse-companion-says-pedophile-was-not-depressed-before-suicide/</ref>}} was transferred, and no replacement cellmate was brought in. The evening of his death, Epstein met with his lawyers, who described him as \"upbeat\" before being escorted back to the SHU at 7:49 PM by guard Tova Noel.<ref name = 60minutes>{{cite news |title=60 Minutes investigates the death of Jeffrey Epstein |first1=|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/did-jeffrey-epstein-kill-himself-60-minutes-investigates-2020-01-05/ |work=CBS |access-date=January 5, 2020 |date=January 5, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> CCTV footage shows that the two guards failed to perform the required institutional count at 10 PM and recorded Noel briefly walking by Epstein's cell at 10:30 PM, the last time the guards entered the tier where his cell was.<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/19/us/jeffrey-epstein-death-timeline/index.html |title=A timeline of what Jeffrey Epstein and his prison guards did in his final hours |last1=Levenson |first1=Eric |date=November 19, 2019 |work=CNN |access-date=December 14, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Through the night, in violation of the jail's normal procedure, Epstein was not checked every 30 minutes.<ref name=\":36\" /> The two guards who were assigned to check his cell overnight, Tova Noel and Michael Thomas, fell asleep at their desk{{efn|group=note|Their desk was about 15 feet away from Epstein's cell, but up a flight of stairs and through a locked gate<ref name = 60minutes/>}} for about three hours and later falsified related records.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/13/nyregion/jeffrey-epstein-jail-officers.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein Death: 2 Guards Slept Through Checks and Falsified Records |last1=Benner |first1=Katie |date=August 13, 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=August 14, 2019 |last2=Ivory |first2=Danielle |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-jeffrey-epstein-guards/two-jail-guards-for-jeffrey-epstein-charged-with-cover-up-in-his-suicide-idUSKBN1XT1VY |title=Two jail guards for Jeffrey Epstein charged with cover-up in his suicide |last1=Pierson |first1=brendan |date=August 13, 2019 |work=Reuters |language=en}}</ref> Two cameras in front of Epstein's cell also malfunctioned that night.<ref name=\"broken cameras\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-jeffrey-epstein-cameras-idUSKCN1VI2LC |title=FBI studies two broken cameras outside cell where Epstein died: source |last1=Hosenball |first1=Mark |date=August 28, 2019 |work=Reuters |access-date=August 29, 2019 |location=London |language=en}}</ref> Another camera had footage which was \"unusable\".<ref name=\"broken cameras\" />\n\n===Discovery===\n[[File:Epstein Body Moved From New York Hospital to Medical Examiner's Office.webm|thumb|right|Epstein's body being moved to the medical examiner's office]]\nAs the guards were distributing breakfast shortly after 6:30 AM on the morning of August 10, Epstein was found unresponsive in cardiac arrest in his cell, which was initially reported as apparent suicide.<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/>  He was found in a kneeling position with a strip of bedsheet{{efn|group=note|Epstein's possession of a bedsheet was also against jail protocol.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190814-usa-jeffrey-epstein-guards-fraud-hanging-suicide-prison-sex-trafficking |title=Jeffrey Epstein's guards placed on leave under suspicion of falsifying jail records |date=August 14, 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en}}</ref>}} wrapped around his neck. The sheet was tied to the top of his bunk.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/16/official-autopsy-shows-jeffrey-epstein-hanged-himself-in-jail-cell/ |title=Jeffrey Epstein's official autopsy confirms he hanged himself in jail cell |date=August 16, 2019 |website=New York Post |language=en}}</ref> He is believed to have been dead for about two hours. The guards performed [[CPR]] on Epstein, and other prisoners heard them yell \"Breathe, Epstein, breathe.\"<ref name = 60minutes/> At 6:33 AM, the guards pulled an alarm, notifying their supervisor, to whom Noel said, \"Epstein hung himself.\"<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/> He was rushed to the [[New York Downtown Hospital]] where he was pronounced dead at 6:39 AM.<ref>https://abcnews.go.com/US/jeffrey-epstein-accused-sex-trafficker-dies-suicide-officials/story?id=64881684</ref> His body was transported to the medical examiner's office soon after.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jeffrey-epstein-death-investigation-alleged-victims-vow-to-keep-seeking-justice/ |title=As mystery surrounding Jeffrey Epstein's death deepens, alleged victims vow to keep seeking justice |date=August 12, 2019 |work=CBS News |language=en}}</ref>  The news of the death was posted on [[4chan]] about 38 minutes before ''ABC News'' broke the news.  If it was posted by a first responder, as it has been speculated, it would likely be a violation of [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act|privacy law]].<ref>{{cite news |first1=Jane |last1=Lytvynenko |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/fdny-review-jeffrey-epstein-4chan-post |date=August 13, 2019 |title=Epstein's Death Was On 4Chan Before Officials Announced It \u2014 And Authorities Had To Look Into It |work=BuzzFeed News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/fdny-reviews-reports-that-epstein-death-leaked-on-4chan |title=FDNY reviews reports of Epstein death leaked on 4Chan |first1=Vandana |last1=Rambaran |date=August 13, 2019 |work=Fox News |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe removal of Epstein\u2019s body from his cell was a violation of protocol, as the [[Bureau of Prisons]] mandates that a suicide scene be treated with the \"same level of protection as any crime scene in which a death has occurred.\"<ref name = 60minutes/> Consequently, prison personnel also failed to photograph Epstein's body as it was found.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/01/5-takeaways-from-the-60-minutes-jeffrey-epstein-report.html|title=5 Takeaways From the 60 Minutes Jeffrey Epstein Report |last1=Raymond |first1=Adam K. |date=January 6, 2020 |work=New York Magazine |access-date=March 19, 2020 |location=New York City |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Discrepancies===\nEpstein's death was the first death ruled a suicide at the MCC in 14 years. Michael Baden and ''[[60 Minutes]]'' have questioned if Epstein, who was almost 6 feet tall and weighed 185 pounds, could have physically been able to hang himself from the lower bunk. Photos taken after the death also show bottles and medicine standing upright on the top bunk.<ref name = 60minutes/> A former inmate at the MCC described the sheets as \"paper level, not strong enough\" to support Epstein's body.<ref name=\"no way\" /> Baden questioned why Epstein didn't use other materials available in his cell as a ligature, such as wires and tubing from a [[Sleep apnea|sleep apnea machine]], which were stronger and longer.<ref name = 60minutes/>\n\n==Autopsy and medical evidence==\n[[File:Epstein neck split.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|Note the positioning on the marks on Epstein's neck. According to a pathologist, \"Marks that indicate the noose was below the hyoid bone would suggest that the hanging was staged and the actual cause of death was strangulation. Marks in the area between the chin and Adam\u2019s apple would indicate the death was more likely a hanging.\"\n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-only-thing-jeffrey-epsteins-broken-hyoid-bone-proves |title=The Only Thing Jeffrey Epstein\u2019s Broken Bone Proves |first1=Michael |last1=Daly |website=The Daily Beast |date=August 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>]]\nA four-hour autopsy on Epstein's body was conducted on August 11 by New York City's Chief Medical Examiner [[Barbara Sampson]]. Epstein's lawyers sent pathologist [[Michael Baden]] to personally observe the city's autopsy.<ref name = 60minutes/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/jeffrey-epstein-camp-sends-pathologist-michael-baden-to-watch-over-his-autopsy |title=Jeffrey Epstein Camp Sent Pathologist Michael Baden to Watch Over His Autopsy |first1=Pervaiz |last1=Shallwani |first2=Audrey |last2=McNamara |first3=Harry |last3=Siegel |date=August 11, 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Beast}}</ref> Following the autopsy, the medical examiner's office reported that Epstein had hanged himself with a sheet from his bed.<ref name=\"Sisak\">{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/a947e0d85d31496eb5bd9ff4994c9718 |first1=Michael R. |last1=Sisak |first2=Michael |last2=Balsamo |first3=Larry |last3=Neumeister |title=Medical examiner rules Epstein death a suicide by hanging |date=August 17, 2019 |work=AP News |language=en}}</ref> On August 14, unofficial sources reported that broken bones were found in Epstein's neck, although this can occur in the suicide of the elderly. They are said to be \"more common in victims of homicide by strangulation\",<ref name=\"broken bones\" /> though multiple studies have found different percentages for both manners of death.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/08/jeffrey-epstein-hyoid-bone-broken-neck/ |title=Jeffrey Epstein's Broken Hyoid Neck Bone: How Common Is It? |first1=Jessica |last1=McBride |date=August 15, 2019}}</ref> Epstein's lawyers released a joint statement following the report of the medical examiner, expressing that they were not satisfied, challenging the conclusions and saying that a more complete response was forthcoming. They also indicated that the defense team fully intends to continue its own independent and complete investigation into the circumstances and cause of their client's death,<ref>{{cite news |first1=Mike |last1=Brest |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/epsteins-lawyers-not-satisfied-with-the-conclusions-of-the-medical-examiner |title=Epstein's lawyers 'not satisfied with the conclusions of the medical examiner' |date=August 18, 2019 |work=Washington Examiner |language=en}}</ref> including taking legal action, if necessary, to view the pivotal camera footage near his cell during the night of his death.<ref name=\"Frias\">{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jeffrey-epsteins-lawyers-to-launch-own-investigation-into-his-death-2019-8 |title=Jeffrey Epstein's lawyers blast 'medieval conditions' at federal jail where he died by suicide and say they are launching their own investigation |last1=Frias |first1=Lauren |date=August 16, 2019 |work=Business Insider |access-date=August 19, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> They later said that the evidence concerning Epstein's death was \"far more consistent\" with murder than suicide.<ref name=\":39\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/epstein-death-murder-suicide-victims-hearing-1456397 |title=Epstein Lawyers say evidence 'far more consistent' with murder than suicide |last1=Stockler |first1=Asher |date=August 27, 2019 |work=Newsweek |access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Autopsy report and criticism===\n[[File:Hyoid bone - animation.gif|thumb|left|upright=0.8|Epstein's [[hyoid bone]], among others, was broken. It is disputed whether this is more indicative of hanging or strangulation.]]\nOn August 16, Sampson announced that Epstein's death had been ruled a suicide by hanging.<ref name=\"dailybeaster\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/jeffrey-epstein-death-ruled-suicide-by-new-york-city-medical-examiner |title=Epstein's Death Was Suicide: Medical Examiner |first1=Pervaiz |last1=Shallwani |date=August 16, 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Beast |language=en}}</ref> Later conflicting reports stated that the injuries Epstein sustained were as consistent, if not more so, with strangulation or homicide as with suicide.<ref name=\"broken bones\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/autopsy-finds-broken-bones-in-jeffrey-epsteins-neck-deepening-questions-around-his-death/2019/08/14/d09ac934-bdd9-11e9-b873-63ace636af08_story.html |title=Autopsy finds broken bones in Jeffrey Epstein's neck, deepening questions around his death |first1=Carol D. |last1=Leonnig |first2=Aaron C. |last2=Davis |work=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/16/jeffrey-epstein-cause-of-death-coroner-report |title=Medical examiner says Jeffrey Epstein's death was a suicide |date=August 16, 2019 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> However, Sampson's report found that there was no [[Crime|foul play]] in Epstein's death.<ref>{{cite news |work=Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/suicide-epstein-autopsy-finds-no-sign-of-foul-play/articleshow/70720626.cms |title='Suicide': Epstein autopsy finds no sign of foul play |access-date=August 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030438/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/suicide-epstein-autopsy-finds-no-sign-of-foul-play/articleshow/70720626.cms |archive-date=August 19, 2019 |url-status=dead |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://7news.com.au/news/crime/no-foul-play-in-epstein-death-says-me-c-404030 |title=No foul play in Epstein death: US coroner |date=August 16, 2019 |work=7NEWS.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://10daily.com.au/news/a190816fviox/medical-examiner-rules-no-foul-play-in-epstein-death-20190817 |title=Jeffrey Epstein Death Ruled 'Suicide By Hanging' |date=August 17, 2019 |work=10 daily}}</ref> Three of Epstein's lawyers expressed their dissatisfaction with Sampson's conclusion of suicide, having hired forensic pathologist Dr. [[Michael Baden]] to observe the autopsy; they said they would be initiating their own investigation and will be providing a more detailed statement in the future.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abc6onyourside.com/news/nation-world/medical-examiner-rules-epsteins-death-a-suicide |title=Epstein lawyers dissatisfied with autopsy result |first1=Michael R. |last1=Sisak |first2=Michael |last2=Balsamo |first3=Larry |last3=Neumeister |agency=Associated Press |date=August 16, 2019 |website=WSYX |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jeffrey-epsteins-lawyers-to-launch-own-investigation-into-his-death-2019-8 |title=Jeffrey Epstein's lawyers blast 'medieval conditions' at federal jail where he died by suicide and say they are launching their own investigation |first1=Lauren |last1=Frias |website=Business Insider |date=August 17, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Baden observed Sampson's autopsy when it was conducted; after the autopsy he indicated that he was unable to comment due to gag orders filed by Sampson's office and \nEpstein's estate.<ref name=\"dailybeaster\" />\n\nOn October 30, 2019, Baden issued a report stating that Epstein's neck injuries were much more consistent with \"homicidal strangulation\" than suicide. He stated that Epstein \"had two fractures on the left and right sides of his [[larynx]], specifically the thyroid cartilage or [[Adam's apple]], as well as one fracture on the left hyoid bone above the Adam's apple\". In particular, Baden claimed that Epstein\u2019s [[hyoid bone]] was [[Hyoid bone fracture|broken]] in a way indicative of strangulation from behind.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.insider.com/epstein-used-his-jail-bedsheet-to-commit-suicide-by-hanging-2019-8 |title=Epstein died by suicide using his jail bed sheet while his guards slept, according to report}}</ref> Baden later said, \"Going over a thousand jail hangings, suicides in the New York City state prisons over the past 40-50 years, no one had three fractures.\"<ref name=\"60minutes\"/> However, neurosurgeon [[Sanjay Gupta]] asserts that Epstein could have easily broken his hyoid bone in a hanging due to the bone's weakening and loss of flexibility with age. Gupta also suggested that the presence of multiple broken neck-bones was more characteristic of hanging. [[Gerald Rodts]], chief of spinal surgery at [[Emory University Hospital]], also pointed to the presence of multiple broken neck-bones as consistent with hanging. Bill Lloyd, an anatomic pathologist, claimed that Epstein's broken hyoid bone was \"meaningless\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/16/media/epstein-washington-post-reliable-sources/index.html |title=The Washington Post fuels Epstein conspiracies, but experts say evidence still consistent with suicide |first1=Oliver |last1=Darcy |website=CNN |date=August 17, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe neck wound was in the center of his neck, not under his mandibles as in a typical hanging. Baden points to this as being more common when a victim is strangled by a wire or cord. Baden has also noted that the wound is much thinner than the strip of bedsheet was, and although there was blood on Epstein's neck, it was absent on the bed-sheet ligature.<ref name=\"60minutes\"/> According to the autopsy files, Epstein also had contusions on both of his wrists, an abrasion on his left forearm, and deep muscle hemorrhaging of his left deltoid or shoulder. His brother, Mark, later suggested that he was \"handcuffed and struggled.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/jeffrey-epstein-unexplained-injuries-wrists-shoulder-brother |title=Jeffrey Epstein had 'unexplained' injuries on wrists and shoulder, brother says |date=November 6, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Epstein also had hemorrhages in his eyes, which although not unheard of in hangings, are more common in strangulations.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/jeffrey-epstein-prison-cell-death-alone |title=Jeffrey Epstein was alone in prison cell the night of his death, feds say, citing video |first1=Talia |last1=Kaplan |date=November 19, 2019 |work=Fox News |language=en}}</ref> Baden has also noted that Epstein's lower legs lacked [[lividity]], suggesting that he did not die in an upright position.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/16/disturbing-evidence-in-jeffrey-epsteins-autopsy-points-to-his-murder-pathologist/ |title=Disturbing evidence in Jeffrey Epstein\u2019s autopsy points to his murder: pathologist |first1=Lee |last1=Brown |first2=Steinbush |last2=Yaron |date=January 16, 2020 |work=New York Post |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Burial===\nFollowing the autopsy, Epstein's body was claimed by an \"unidentified associate,\" later revealed to be his brother, Mark.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/crime-courts/jeffrey-epstein-s-body-claimed-unidentified-associate-n1042551 |title=Jeffrey Epstein's body claimed by unidentified 'associate' |date=August 14, 2019 |work=NBC News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/jeffrey-epsteins-body-claimed-by-brother-mark-epstein |title=Jeffrey Epstein's Body Claimed by His Brother |date=August 16, 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Beast |last1=Shallwani |first1=Pervaiz}}</ref>  On September 5, Epstein's body was buried in an unmarked tomb next to those of his parents at the IJ Morris Star of David mausoleum in [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]], Florida.  The names of his parents were also removed from their tombstone in order to prevent vandalism.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Jeffery-Epstein-buried-in-unmarked-grave-with-family-names-removed-600753 |title=Jeffery Epstein buried in unmarked grave with family names removed |date=September 5, 2019 |work=The Jerusalem Post |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n===Reaction===\n{{external media\n|width=210px\n|float=right\n|video1={{YouTube|link=no|id=vk3eZoxlkuYc|title=Trump: 'I have no idea' if Clintons were involved in Epstein's death}} (0:51)\n|video2={{YouTube|link=no|id=YPKEyID72Ew|title=Attorney General William Barr says he's \"appalled\" by Jeffrey Epstein's death in jail}} (1:50)\n}}\n[[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]] initially responded to Epstein's death by [[retweet]]ing a [[Clinton Body Count|conspiracy theory]] linking Epstein's death to former president [[Bill Clinton]] and former [[United States Secretary of State|secretary of state]] [[Hillary Clinton]], a few hours after Epstein's death was announced.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[thehill.com]] |first1=Rachel |last1=Frazin |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/456979-trump-retweets-post-promoting-conspiracy-theory-about-jeffrey |title=Trump retweets post promoting conspiracy theory about Jeffrey Epstein's death |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> At an energy speech in [[Pennsylvania]], Trump told reporters he wanted \"a full investigation.\"<ref>{{cite news |work=[[thehill.com]] |first1=Rachel |last1=Frazin |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/13/donald-trump-defends-jeffrey-epstein-bill-clinton-conspiracy-retweet/1996632001/ |title=Donald Trump defends his Jeffrey Epstein, Bill Clinton conspiracy retweet |access-date=April 8, 2020 |date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Attorney General [[William Barr]] said he was \"appalled\" by Epstein's death while in federal custody and that it \"raises serious questions that must be answered.\" He ordered an investigation by the Justice Department's [[Office of Inspector General (United States)|Inspector General]] in addition to the FBI investigation.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Jesse |last1=Byrnes |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/456959-attorney-general-barr-appalled-by-epstein-death-in-federal-custody |title=Attorney General Barr 'appalled' by Epstein death in federal custody |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Senator [[Ben Sasse]], chairman of the United States Senate Judiciary oversight subcommittee, later wrote a letter to Barr saying \"The Department of Justice failed.\" He added \"Given Epstein's previous attempted suicide, he should have been locked in a padded room under unbroken, 24/7, constant surveillance. Obviously, heads must roll.\"<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Rachel |last1=Frazin |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/456963-sasse-tells-ag-that-heads-must-roll-over-epstein-treatment-in-federal-custody |title=Sasse tells AG that 'heads must roll' over Epstein treatment in federal custody |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Rep. [[Matt Gaetz]], who sits on the [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|United States House Judiciary Committee]], called on chairman Rep. [[Jerry Nadler]]  to prioritize investigating the circumstances around Epstein's death over other probes being carried out by the committee.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Tal |last1=Axelrod |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/456949-ocasio-cortez-calls-for-answers-after-epstein-found-dead-in-jail-cell |title=Ocasio-Cortez demands 'answers' after Epstein found dead in jail cell |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 10, 201 |language=en}}</ref> Rep. [[Lois Frankel]] called for a congressional investigation into the 2008 plea deal for Epstein.<ref name=\"democrats call\">{{cite news |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/456954-democrat-calls-for-congressional-investigation-into-epstein-death |title=Democrat calls for congressional investigation after Epstein death |last1=Campisi |first1=Jessica |date=August 10, 2019 |work=The Hill |access-date=August 21, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Senators [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] and [[Rick Scott]] both called for an investigation and expressed their dissatisfaction that Epstein\u2019s victims would not find closure in a trial.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Zack |last1=Budryk |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/457019-gillibrand-calls-for-full-investigation-into-epsteins-death |title=Gillibrand calls for 'full investigation' into Epstein's death |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 11, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Tal |last1=Axelrod |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/456956-gop-senator-inexcusable-that-epstein-not-under-constant-suicide-watch |title=GOP senator: 'Inexcusable' that Epstein not under constant suicide watch |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote  = \"I do think there needs to be a full investigation about why he was taken off the suicide watch list; I think it\u2019s a strange decision, given that he attempted suicide once already. I want to know why he was left in a circumstance where suicide was even possible.\"\n | source = '''Sen. [[Kirsten Gillibrand]]'''<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Zack |last1=Budryk |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/457019-gillibrand-calls-for-full-investigation-into-epsteins-death |title=Gillibrand calls for 'full investigation' into Epstein's death |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 11, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n | width = 210px\n | align = left\n}}\nOn August 12, 2019, the leaders of the House Judiciary Committee, Chairman [[Jerry Nadler]] and ranking member [[Doug Collins (politician)|Doug Collins]], sent 23 questions to the Federal Bureau of Prisons about Epstein's death. \"The apparent suicide of this high-profile and\u2014if allegations are proven to be accurate\u2014particularly reprehensible individual while in the federal government's custody demonstrates severe miscarriages of or deficiencies in inmate protocol and has allowed the deceased to ultimately evade facing justice,\" they wrote. \"Any victims of Mr. Epstein's actions will forever be denied proper recourse and the scintilla of recompense our justice system can provide in the face of such alleged atrocities; the competency and rigor of our criminal justice system has been marred by this apparent oversight.\"<ref>{{cite news |first1=Zack |last1=Budryk |work=The Hill |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/457174-judiciary-committee-leaders-demand-answers-from-bureau-of-prisons-on-epstein |title=House Judiciary leaders demand answers from Bureau of Prisons on Epstein death |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> Later on August 13, Nebraska senator Ben Sasse, the chair of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]], wrote a letter to  Attorney General Barr urging him to \"rip up\" the 2008 non-prosecution deal for Epstein and his co-conspirators. Sasse argued that the Justice Department must bring Epstein's co-conspirators to justice despite his death, and added, \"This crooked deal cannot stand.\"<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Justin |last1=Wise |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/457288-sasse-calls-on-justice-dept-to-rip-up-epstein-non-prosecution-deal-to |title=Sasse calls on DOJ to 'rip up' Epstein nonprosecution deal to bring 'co-conspirators to justice' |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n\"For them to pull him off suicide watch is shocking,\" Cameron Lindsay, a former warden at three federal facilities, told [[NBC News]]. \"For someone this high-profile, with these allegations and this many victims, who has had a suicide attempt in the last few weeks, you can take absolutely no chances. You leave him on suicide watch until he's out of there.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/prison-experts-are-stunned-angry-jeffrey-epstein-was-taken-suicide-n1041121 |title=Prison experts are stunned and angry that Jeffrey Epstein was taken off suicide watch |date=August 10, 2019 |work=NBC News |access-date=August 21, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Federal prosecutors in the case called Epstein's death \"disturbing\" and emphasized that they would continue to seek justice for his accusers even after the financier's death. [[Geoffrey Berman]], the [[United States Attorney for the Southern District of New York]], said in a statement, \"To those brave young women who have already come forward and to the many others who have yet to do so, let me reiterate that we remain committed to standing for you, and our investigation of the conduct charged in the indictment\u2014which included a conspiracy count\u2014remains ongoing.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/sdny-us-attorneys-office-confirms-epstein-investigation-remains-ongoing-conspiracy-2019-8 |title=Federal prosecutors confirm that the Epstein sex-trafficking investigation will continue despite his death |last1=Tenbarge |first1=Kat |date=August 10, 2019 |work=Business Insider |access-date=August 21, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Investigations===\n[[File:William Barr delivers remarks at the Correctional Workers Week Memorial Service.jpg|thumb|right|Attorney General William Barr described Epstein's death as \"a perfect storm of screw-ups.\"]]\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] subsequently launched an investigation of the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death,<ref>{{cite news |date=August 10, 2019 |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/news/456957-fbi-investigating-epstein-death-in-manhattan-jail |title=FBI investigating Epstein death in Manhattan jail |newspaper=The Hill |access-date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> with Attorney General Barr saying that Justice Department officials will thoroughly investigate \"serious irregularities\" at the Metropolitan Correctional Center (MCC) where Epstein was found dead. Barr also warned that any of Epstein's alleged co-conspirators \"should not rest easy,\" noting that federal prosecutors will continue to aggressively pursue the case to ensure anyone who worked alongside Epstein will be held accountable. \"We are now learning of serious irregularities at this facility that are deeply concerning and demand a thorough investigation,\" Barr said during remarks at a law enforcement conference in New Orleans. \"The FBI and the Office of Inspector General are doing just that.\" Barr said he was \"appalled\" and \"angry\" over the developments; he insisted that the Justice Department would \"get to the bottom\" of what happened and promised accountability. \"Let me assure you this case will continue on against anyone who was complicit with Epstein,\" Barr said. \"Any co-conspirators should not rest easy. The victims deserve justice and they will get it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/457095-barr-promises-thorough-investigation-of-epstein-death-warns |title=Barr criticizes prison's 'serious irregularities' after Epstein death |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> As Barr received more information surrounding Epstein's death, he came to believe that it was only \"a perfect storm of screw-ups.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/ag-barr-epsteins-death-was-a-perfect-storm-of-screw-ups/ar-BBX9U8P |title=AG Barr: Epstein's death was a 'perfect storm of screw-ups' |work=MSN |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019 [[Kathleen Hawk Sawyer]], the director of the [[Bureau of Prisons]], told the Senate Judiciary Committee that the FBI is investigating whether a \"criminal enterprise\" was involved in Epstein's death. She added that there is \"no indication, from anything I know\" that his death \"was anything other than a suicide.\" A spokesperson later explained that she had used the phrase \"criminal enterprise\" because that was what Senator Lindsey Graham has asked her about, and that \"she was referring to looking into possible criminal conduct by staff.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/19/jeffrey-epstein-death-in-jail-under-fbi-investigation.html |title=FBI probing if Jeffrey Epstein's death was the result of a 'criminal enterprise,' prisons chief says |last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |date=November 19, 2019 |work=CNBC |access-date=November 20, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn August 13, Attorney General Barr ordered the Bureau of Prisons to temporarily reassign the warden of the MCC, Lamine N'Diaye, while the FBI and Justice Department inspector general investigate the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. James Petrucci, the warden of [[Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville|FCI Otisville]], was named acting warden.<ref name=\"warden reassigned\">{{cite news |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/13/jeffrey-epstein-warden-shirley-skipper-scott-reassigned-after-suicide/1999993001/ |title=New York warden reassigned after Jeffrey Epstein's death; two staffers placed on leave |first1=Kevin |last1=Johnson |work=USA TodaaODAY |date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Two staff members assigned to Epstein's unit have also been placed on administrative leave.<ref name=\"warden reassigned\" /><ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Morgan |last1=Chalfant |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/457281-doj-reassigns-warden-after-epstein-apparent-suicide |title=DOJ reassigns warden after Epstein's apparent suicide |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> On August 14, Manhattan federal court judge Richard Berman, who was overseeing Epstein's criminal case, wrote to the Metropolitan Correctional Centre warden Lamine N'Diaye inquiring as to whether an investigation into Epstein\u2019s death would include a probe into his prior (July 23) injuries.  Judge Berman wrote that to his knowledge it has never been definitely explained what they concluded about the incident.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/14/epstein-judge-wants-answers-about-first-incident-in-jail/ |title=Epstein judge wants answers about first incident in jail |first1=Emily |last1=Saul |date=August 14, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n{{external media\n|width=210px\n|float=left\n|video1={{YouTube|link=no|id=RQyalWtHDec|title=Ben Sasse presses prison bureau director on Jeffrey Epstein death}} (5:43)\n|video2={{YouTube|link=no|id=kFTfQ8IoHzw|title=Epstein guards appear in court}} (1:24)\n}}\n\n\nTwo French Cabinet officials [[Marl\u00e8ne Schiappa]] and [[Adrien Taquet]] subsequently called for an investigation into the \"many unanswered questions\" about Epstein's ties to France, calling for the [[Government of France|French government]] to launch its own probe. \"The US investigation has highlighted links with France,\" Schiappa and Taquet said in the statement, according to ABC. \"It thus seems to us fundamental for the victims that an investigation be opened in France so that all is brought to light.\" \"The elements received at the Paris prosecutor's office are being analyzed and cross-referenced,\" a spokesperson for the office told [[ABC News]]. \"The first audits are currently underway to determine whether an investigation should be opened in France.\"<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Zack |last1=Budryk |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/europe/457221-french-officials-call-for-investigation-of-epstein-links-with |title=French officials call for investigation of Epstein 'links with France' |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAll charges against Epstein were officially dismissed on August 29.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/29/us/jeffrey-epstein-criminal-case-dismissed/index.html |title=The criminal case against Jeffrey Epstein has been officially dismissed |last1=Adone |first1=Dakin |date=August 29, 2019 |work=CNN|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> As a result, the ongoing sex-trafficking investigations and media attention shifted attention towards his alleged associates, such as [[Prince Andrew]], [[Jean-Luc Brunel]], and [[Ghislaine Maxwell]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/epsteins-death-leaves-unanswered-questions-for-investigators-11565541496 |title=Epstein's Death Sparks Probe, Shifts Spotlight to Associates |last1=O'brien |first1=Rebecca Davis |last2=Hong |first2=Nicole |last3=Chapman |first3=Ben |last4=Gurman |first4=Sadie |date=August 11, 2019 |work=Wall Street Journal |access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/22/jeffrey-epstein-scandal-prince-andrew-kicked-out-of-buckingham-palace.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein scandal: Prince Andrew booted from Buckingham Palace, report says |last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |date=November 22, 2019 |work=CNBC |access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/lisettevoytko/2019/12/27/report-fbi-investigating-epstein-confidante-ghislaine-maxwell/#dfdd1da37158 |title=Report: FBI Investigating Epstein Confidante Ghislaine Maxwell |last1=Voytko |first1=Lisette |date=December 27, 2019 |work=Forbes |access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref> Following Epstein\u2019s death, Maxwell sued his estate, claiming that she was owed compensation for legal fees due to her close relationship with Epstein.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/19/jeffrey-epstein-associate-ghislaine-maxwell-sues-his-estate</ref>\n\n====Related criminal trials====\nOn November 19, 2019, federal prosecutors in New York indicted [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|Metropolitan Correctional Center]] guards Michael Thomas and Tova Noel, charged with creating false records and conspiracy.<ref name=\"NPR-charge\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/19/780794931/prosecutors-charge-correctional-officers-who-guarded-jeffrey-epstein-before-his- |title=Jeffrey Epstein's Prison Guards Are Indicted On Federal Charges |last1=Allyn |first1=Bobby |work=NPR |series=All Things Considered |date=November 19, 2019 |access-date=December 11, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-50480172 |title=Epstein guards charged with falsifying records |date=November 19, 2019 |access-date=November 19, 2019 |language=en-GB}}</ref> The charges were based on video footage obtained by prosecutors, indicating that Epstein was not observed by them for eight hours, while the two guards made personal searches on their computers and slept. According to [[Geoffrey Berman]], the U.S. Attorney for the Southern District of New York, during that time they repeatedly signed records affirming that they had performed the required checks.<ref name=\"NPR-charge\" /> Their bail was set at $100,000.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/19/nyregion/epstein-prison-guards-arrested.html |title=Guards Accused of Napping and Shopping Online the Night Epstein Died |first1=Michael |last1=Gold |first2=Danielle |last2=Ivory |first3=Nicole |last3=Hong |date=November 19, 2019 |newspaper=The New York Times |language=en}}</ref> They claimed that they were \"scapegoats\" for larger issues within the federal prison system.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/25/nyregion/jeffrey-epstein-guards-tova-noel-michael-thomas.html |title=Epstein Suicide: Guards Say They're Scapegoats for a Broken System |first1=Benjamin |last1=Weiser |date=November 25, 2019 |newspaper=The New York Times |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/20/us/jeffrey-epstein-prison-guard-system/index.html |title=Attorneys for Jeffrey Epstein's prison guards point the blame at the system |first1=Eric |last1=Levenson |first2=Mark |last2=Morales | first3=David |last3=Shortell |date=November 20, 2019 |newspaper=CNN |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn a December 2019 court proceeding against Epstein's cellmate Nick Tartaglione, federal prosecutors reported that the surveillance footage from outside Epstein's cell during the July 23 incident had disappeared. Tartaglione's defense had sought to use the footage to demonstrate his character while he allegedly saved Epstein. Tartaglione's lawyer had requested that the footage be retained on July 25, two days after the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/18/jeffrey-epsteins-first-suicide-attempt-video-is-missing.html |title=Jail video surveillance from Jeffrey Epstein's first suicide attempt in July is missing, prosecutor says, according to reports|last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |date=December 18, 2019 |website=The Seattle Times |access-date=December 18, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Judge Kenneth Karas requested that the government determine what had happened to the footage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/surveillance-footage-outside-jeffrey-epsteins-cell-during-suicide-attempt-is-missing/ |title=Surveillance footage outside Jeffrey Epstein's cell during suicide attempt is missing |last1=Brown |first1=Stephen Rex |date=December 18, 2019 |website=The Seattle Times |access-date=December 18, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Several days later, federal prosecutors reversed their statement, claiming that they had found the missing footage. But in January 2020, they admitted that the footage had been permanently deleted due to a \"clerical error\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/epsteins-suicide-attempt-video-preserved-prosecutors |title=Lost Jeffrey Epstein suicide attempt video is found: Prosecutors |last1=Pagones |first1=Stephanie |date=December 20, 2019 |website=The Seattle Times |access-date=December 23, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/surveillance-video-jeffrey-epstein-s-first-apparent-suicide-attempt-no-n1113166?cid=sm_npd_nn_fb_ma |title=Surveillance video from Jeffrey Epstein's first apparent suicide attempt 'no longer exists' |last1=Winter |first1=Tom |date=January 9, 2020 |website=NBC News |access-date=December 23, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Homicide suspicions and speculation==\n[[File:Conspiracy theorist (48555437426).jpg|thumb|A partisan protestor alleging outside involvement shortly after Epstein's death]]\nDue to violations of standard prison procedures, and Epstein's knowledge of compromising information about famous individuals, his death by \"apparent suicide\"<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite news |last1=Allyn |first1=Bobby |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/19/780794931/prosecutors-charge-correctional-officers-who-guarded-jeffrey-epstein-before-his- |title=Jeffrey Epstein's Prison Guards Are Indicted On Federal Charges |work=National Public Radio |date=November 19, 2019}}</ref> spawned skepticism, as well as multiple [[conspiracy theories]]. Epstein conspiracy theorists have been labeled \"Epstein Truthers,\" similar to [[9/11 Truth movement|those who dispute the accepted account of the 9/11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/qvgpm3/epstein-truthers-are-obsessed-with-a-sci-fi-book-about-child-sex-slavery-written-by-bill-barrs-dad/ |title=Epstein Truthers Are Obsessed With a Sci-Fi Book About Child Sex Slavery Written by Bill Barr\u2019s Dad|date=August 16, 2019 |website=Vie |access-date=February 2, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> A [[Rasmussen Reports|Rasmussen]] poll conducted shortly after his death in August 2019 found that only 29% of U.S. adults believed Epstein actually committed suicide, while 42% thought he was murdered to prevent him from testifying against powerful people with whom he associated, and 29% of people were undecided.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rasmussenreports.com/public_content/politics/general_politics/august_2019/americans_say_murder_more_likely_than_suicide_in_epstein_case |title=Americans Say Murder More Likely Than Suicide in Epstein Case |date=August 14, 2019 |website=[[Rasmussen Reports]] |access-date=August 24, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> By November 2019, a ''[[Business Insider]]'' poll found that those who believed Epstein was murdered outnumbered suicide proponents three to one.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jeffrey-epstein-kill-himself-poll-2019-11 |title=Almost half of Americans now believe the conspiracy theory that sex offender Jeffrey Epstein was murdered |first1=Jacob |last1=Shamsian |work=Business Insider |language=en}}</ref> In a 2020 poll, Rasmussen found that a majority of Americans believed Epstein was murdered, with just 21% believing that he committed suicide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rasmussenreports.com/public_content/lifestyle/people/january_2020/most_now_think_jeffrey_epstein_was_murdered |title=Most Now Think Jeffrey Epstein Was Murdered |date=January 9, 2020 |website=[[Rasmussen Reports]] |access-date=February 2, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[University of Chicago]] professor Eric Oliver, a conspiracy theory expert, labeled [[Populism#North America|populist]] sentiment and a [[Anti-establishment#Anti-establishment in the United States|mistrust of the political system]] as major contributors to the widespread rejection of the official narrative.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://time.com/5737975/jeffrey-epstein-death-conspiracy-theories/ |title=Feds Denounce Jeffrey Epstein Death Conspiracy Theories|date=November 23, 2019 |website=Time |access-date=December 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBecause of his connections to many wealthy and powerful people, there was speculation that some co-conspirator or participant in his sex crimes might have arranged for him to be silenced.<ref name=\"Palm\" /> In the hours after the death, the hashtag [[Clinton Body Count|#ClintonBodyCount]] and the countering #TrumpBodyCount were trending on Twitter as users accused Bill and Hillary Clinton and Donald Trump of being involved in Epstein's death.<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite news |title='Epstein Didn't Kill Himself' and the Meme-ing of Conspiracy |first1=Emma Grey |last1=Ellis |url=https://www.wired.com/story/epstein-didnt-kill-himself-conspiracy/ |work=Wired |date=November 15, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/8/10/20800195/clintonbodycount-conspiracy-theory-jeffrey-epstein |title=The conspiracy theories about the Clintons and Jeffrey Epstein's death, explained |last1=Matthews |first1=Dylan |date=August 10, 2019 |website=Vox |access-date=August 11, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Several hours after Epstein was found dead, Trump retweeted a [[conspiracy theory]] by Terrence K. Williams, a comedian and conservative commentator, suggesting that there was a connection between the Clintons and Epstein's death\u2014furthering a perennial conspiracy theory dating to the early 1990s that the Clintons have had numerous people killed to silence them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-retweets-epstein-conspiracy-theory-claiming-clinton-connection-n1041146 |title=Trump retweets Epstein conspiracy theory, claiming Clinton connection |last1=Timm |first1=Jane C. |last2=Johnstone |first2=Liz |date=August 10, 2019 |work=NBC News |access-date=August 11, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/8/10/20800195/clintonbodycount-conspiracy-theory-jeffrey-epstein |title=The conspiracy theories about the Clintons and Jeffrey Epstein's death, explained |first1=Dylan |last1=Matthews |date=August 10, 2019 |website=Vox}}</ref> The retweet was immediately showcased worldwide.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/nightly-news/video/trump-fuels-jeffrey-epstein-conspiracy-theories-on-social-media-65954373986 |title=Trump fuels Jeffrey Epstein conspiracy theories on social media |date=August 12, 2019 |work=NBC News |access-date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump retweets post implying Bill Clinton behind Jeffrey Epstein's death |first1=Sam |last1=Dorman |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/donald-trump-bill-clinton-jeffrey-epstein-suicide-theory |work=Fox News |date=August 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt an August 27 hearing, Epstein defense attorney Reid Weingarten expressed \"significant doubts\" that Epstein's death was due to suicide. According to Weingarten, when attorneys met with their client shortly before his death, \"we did not see a despairing, despondent, suicidal person\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/27/jeffrey-epsteins-lawyers-skeptical-of-suicide-ruling.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein's lawyers highly 'skeptical' of suicide ruling, say he wasn't 'despairing, despondent' before death |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Kevin |last2=Breuninger |date=August 27, 2019 |website=CNBC |language=en}}</ref> Epstein's brother, Mark, has rejected the possibility of Jeffrey's suicide, claiming, \u201cI could see if he got a life sentence, I could then see him taking himself out, but he had a bail hearing coming up.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/state/florida/article237242984.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein wasn't trafficking women \u2014 and he didn't kill himself, brother says |first1=Julie |last1=Brown |date=November 14, 2019 |website=Miami herald |language=en}}</ref> He also claimed that his \"life may also be in danger,\" if Epstein was indeed murdered.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/lifestyle/jeffrey-epstein-brother-fears-life-danger |title=Jeffrey Epstein's brother fears his life 'may also be in danger' |last1=Pagones |first1=Stephanie |date=December 23, 2019 |website=[[FOX Business]] |access-date=January 1, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> New York City mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] and podcast host [[Joe Rogan]] expressed doubts that Epstein's death was due to suicide.<ref name=\"wired\" /> Former US Attorney and Senate Judiciary Committee counsel [[Brett Tolman]] said that his death was \"more than coincidental\" considering his \"many connections to powerful people\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/11/20/ex-us-attorney-calls-epstein-suicide-more-than-coincidental/ |title=Ex-US attorney calls Epstein suicide 'more than coincidental' |first1=Bruce |last1=Golding |date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> [[Syria|Syrian]] President [[Bashar al-Assad]] asserted that \"American billionaire Jeffrey Epstein was killed several weeks ago - they said he had committed suicide in jail. However, he was killed because he knew a lot of vital secrets connected with very important people in the British and American regimes, and possibly in other countries as well.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/syria-assad-jeffrey-epstein-didnt-kill-himself-1471868 |title=Syria's Assad says Jeffrey Epstein did not kill himself |last1=O'Connor |first1=Tom |date=November 14, 2019 |website=Newsweek |access-date=November 15, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{further|Epstein didn't kill himself}}\n{{multiple image\n|total_width=350\n|image1=Epstein Bridge Nov2019 2 (cropped).jpg\n|width1=2419\n|height1=3226\n|image2=Epstein Didn't Kill Himself Sticker.png\n|width2=792\n|height2=880\n|footer= The meme appeared in a variety of forms and places, such as this graffiti on an Ohio interstate overpass or a sticker at a bus stop in [[Nova Scotia]].\n}}\nAs more information surrounding Epstein's death became public in November 2019, his death and the possibility of murder became a popular [[internet meme]], particularly in the form of the phrase \"[[Epstein didn't kill himself]]\". The meme gained prominence as it was interjected at the end of live interviews, such as by a [[United States Navy SEALs|Navy SEAL]] on FOX News, or later a [[University of Alabama]] student on MSNBC.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/nation-world/ct-nw-jeffrey-epstein-conspiracy-theories-20191123-5smcuhoeajdcrikft2fpgy7cxm-story.html |title=\u2018Epstein didn\u2019t kill himself\u2019: The feds are adamant he died by suicide. The internet isn\u2019t buying it. |first1=Michael |last1=Sisak |date=November 23, 2019 |website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/university-alabama-student-jeffrey-epstein-didnt-kill-himself-1471184 |title=Alabama Student Tells MSNBC Reporter 'Jeffrey Epstein Didn't Kill Himself'|first1=Jenni |last1=Fink|date=November 12, 2019 |website=Newsweek}}</ref> The meme often appears as a [[Non sequitur (literary device)|non sequitur]] after a body of text or within an image.<ref>{{cite news |title=Understanding the 'Jeffrey Epstein didn't kill himself' meme |last1=Poisson |first1=Jayme |last2=Merlan |first2=Anna |url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/frontburner/understanding-the-jeffrey-epstein-didn-t-kill-himself-meme-1.5365778 |work=[[CBC News]] |series=Front Burner |access-date=1 December 2019 |date=20 November 2019 |language=en |format=Audio}}</ref> NPR's [[Scott Simon]] likened the [[bait-and-switch]] aspect of the meme to [[Rickrolling]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Epstein's Death Becomes A Meme |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/16/780067957/epsteins-death-becomes-a-meme |access-date=December 27, 2019 |work=[[NPR]]|date=November 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nEpstein's death became the subject of several comedians, such as [[77th Golden Globe Awards]] host [[Ricky Gervais]] who remarked that Epstein didn\u2019t commit suicide and [[Saturday Night Live]] host [[Adam Driver]], who played a murdered Epstein in hell.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amatulli |first1=Jenna |title= Ricky Gervais Says Epstein Didn't Kill Himself, Drags Felicity Huffman At Golden Globes |url= https://www.huffpost.com/entry/ricky-gervais-opening-monologue-golden-globes-2020_n_5e0fa2d3c5b6b5a713ba297d?zwi |access-date=January 5, 2020|work=[[Huffington Post]] |date=January 5, 2020|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/01/adam-driver-snl-jeffrey-epstein-kylo-ren</ref> [[HBO]] is creating a limited series covering Epstein's life and death. [[Netflix]], [[Sony|SonyTV]], and [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] also have similar works in progress.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.inquirer.com/entertainment/tv/jeffrey-epstein-hbo-series-adam-mckay-julie-k-brown-20191031.html |title=HBO orders Jeffrey Epstein series based on book by former Daily News reporter |first1=Nick |last1=Vadala |work=Inquirer.com |date=October 31, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/jeffrey-epstein-series-hbo-adam-mckay-1203388518/ |title=Adam McKay Sets Jeffrey Epstein Limited Series at HBO Under New First-Look Deal |first1=Joe |last1=Otterson |first2=Joe |last2=Otterson |work=Variety  |date=October 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/prince-andrew-accuser-virginia-roberts-giuffre-netflix-epstein</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|New York City|Law|Human sexuality}}\n* [[Jeffrey Epstein#Legal proceedings|Jeffrey Epstein \u00a7 Legal proceedings]]\n* [[List of federal political scandals in the United States]]\n* [[List of unsolved deaths]]\n* [[Little Saint James, U.S. Virgin Islands]]\n* [[Space Relations]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*  {{cite web|title=Inside the Jail the Night Jeffrey Epstein Died|date=November 20, 2019|first=Azi |last=Paybarah|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 20, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/20/nyregion/jeffrey-epstein-death.html}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|c=category:Death of Jeffrey Epstein|b=no|n=no|q=no|voy=no|s=no|v=no|species=no}}\n*[https://drive.google.com/file/d/1WuIp6GmgqhsZrQRbFtBrdsSbXJCQsI1o/view Autopsy report]\n*[https://www.justice.gov/usao-sdny/press-release/file/1180481/download Indictment of Jeffrey Epstein]\n*[https://vault.fbi.gov/jeffrey-epstein FBI vault] \n*[https://www.motherjones.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Epstein.Docs_.redacted.pdf Redacted DOJ files]\n{{authority control}}\n{{Jeffrey Epstein Sex Trafficking Scandal}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Epstein, Jeffrey, death of}}\n[[Category:2010s in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:2019 controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:2019 in New York City]]\n[[Category:2019 controversies]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:American people who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:August 2019 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories promoted by Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Death in New York City]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jeffrey Epstein|Death]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in New York (state) detention]]\n[[Category:Unsolved deaths]]\n[[Category:Death conspiracy theories]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{short description|High-profile death of Jeffery Epstein in custody}}\n{{Infobox event\n\n| image                    = Epstein Final Mugshot.png\n| image_upright            = 0.8\n| caption                  = Epstein in his final mugshot, taken July&nbsp;8, 2019\n| date                     = {{start date and age|2019|8|10}}\n| time                     = \n| place                    = [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|Metropolitan Correctional Center]], [[New York City]]\n| coordinates              = {{Coord|40.7132|-74.0015|region:US-NY_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| cause                    = Disputed; ruled a [[suicide by hanging]]\n| participants             = \n| outcome                  = Removal of warden, indictments of guards on duty \n| reported deaths          = \n| burial                   =\n| inquiries                = FBI and DOJ investigations\n| inquest                  =\n| coroner                  = New York City Medical Examiner\n| arrests                  = Michael Thomas and Tova Noel\n| suspects                 =\n| accused                  =\n| convicted                =\n| charges                  = Record falsification and conspiracy\n| verdict                  =\n| convictions              =\n| litigation               = \n| url                      = \n| notes                    = \n}}\nOn August 10, 2019, American financier and convicted sex offender [[Jeffrey Epstein]] was found unresponsive in his [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|Metropolitan Correctional Center]] jail cell, where he was awaiting trial on new sex trafficking charges. After prison-guards performed [[CPR]], he was transported in cardiac arrest to [[New York Downtown Hospital]], where he was pronounced dead at 6:39 AM. The [[Office of Chief Medical Examiner of the City of New York|New York City medical examiner]] ruled Epstein's death a suicide by hanging, however, Epstein's lawyers challenged that conclusion and opened their own investigation. [[Michael Baden]], who was hired by Epstein's brother to oversee the autopsy, has since become the most vocal proponent of the theory of homicidal strangulation rather than suicidal hanging.\n\nAfter initially expressing suspicion, Attorney General [[William Barr]] described Epstein's death as \"a perfect storm of screw-ups.\" Both the [[FBI]] and the [[United States Department of Justice Office of the Inspector General|U.S. Department of Justice's Inspector General]] are conducting investigations into the circumstances of his death. The guards on duty were later charged with conspiracy and record falsification. As a result of his death, all charges against Epstein were dismissed, and ongoing sex-trafficking investigations shifted attention towards his alleged associates.\n\nDue to violations of normal jail procedures on the night of Epstein's death,{{efn|group=note|E.g. the removal of his cellmate without a replacement, possession of banned objects, the falling asleep of two guards who were meant to check on him.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/11/nyregion/epstein-death-manhattan-correctional-center.html |title=Before Jail Suicide, Epstein Was Left Alone and Not Closely Monitored |last=Benner |first=Katie |date=August 11, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=August 11, 2019 |last2=Ivory |first2=Danielle |last3=Oppel Jr|first3=Richard A. |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-jeffrey-epstein-cameras-idUSKCN1VI2LC |title=FBI studies two broken cameras outside cell where Epstein died: source |last=Hosenball |first=Mark |date=August 28, 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |access-date=August 29, 2019 |location=London |language=en}}</ref>}} the malfunction of two cameras in front of his cell, and his claimed knowledge of compromising information about powerful figures, his death generated speculation and [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/12/nyregion/conspiracy-theories-epstein-suicide.html|title=Epstein Conspiracy Theories: De Blasio, and Others Join Speculation|last=Gold|first=Michael|date=2019-08-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-06|last2=Bromwich|first2=Jonah Engel|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> about the possibility that he was murdered.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/12/business/jeffrey-epstein-interview.html |title=The Day Jeffrey Epstein Told Me He Had Dirt on Powerful People |last1=Stewart |first1=James B. |date=August 12, 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=August 22, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Arrest and imprisonment==\n{{further|Jeffrey Epstein#Trafficking charges}}\n[[File:MCC New York jeh.JPG|thumb|upright=1.25|[[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|The Metropolitan Correctional Center]], where Epstein was held after his 2019 arrest]]\n\nOn July 6, 2019, Jeffrey Epstein was arrested in New York on multiple charges including sex trafficking and placed at the [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|Metropolitan Correctional Center]]{{efn|group=note|Within the MCC, Epstein was placed in the Special Housing Unit to protect him from violence from inmates in the general population.<ref>https://www.cnbc.com/2019/07/24/jeffrey-epstein-injured-in-federal-jail-in-manhattan.html</ref>}} in [[Lower Manhattan]].<ref>{{cite news |date=August 12, 2019 |first1=Zachary |last1=Halaschak |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/federal-jail-where-jeffrey-epstein-was-held-has-history-of-security-issues |title=Federal jail where Jeffrey Epstein was held has history of security issues |work=Washington Examiner}}</ref> He pleaded not guilty.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/08/nyregion/jeffrey-epstein-charges.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein Is Indicted on Sex Charges as Discovery of Nude Photos Is Disclosed |first1=Ali |last1=Watkins |date=July 8, 2019 |work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-jeffrey-epstein/financier-epstein-pleads-not-guilty-to-sex-trafficking-charges-involving-girls-idUSKCN1U3136 |title=Financier Epstein pleads not guilty to sex trafficking charges involving girls |first1=Brendan |last1=Pierson |date=July 8, 2019 |work=Reuters |language=en}}</ref> He had earlier faced similar charges in Florida in 2008, but escaped federal charges in a plea deal. Under the plea deal he pled guilty to two state felony charges, paid restitution to three dozen victims identified by the FBI, and registered as a sex offender in both the states of [[Florida]] and [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\"deal\">{{cite news |last1=Brown |first1=Julie K.|author-link=Julie K. Brown |title=How a future Trump Cabinet member gave a serial sex abuser the deal of a lifetime |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/article220097825.html |access-date=November 28, 2018 |work=Miami Herald |date=November 28, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128153832/https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/article220097825.html |archive-date=November 28, 2018|url-status=live |language=en}}</ref> On July 18, 2019, Epstein was denied bail after offering [[United States dollar|US$]]600,000 to be able to wear an ankle tracker at his [[New York City]] [[Herbert N. Straus House|townhouse]]. He was viewed as a potential [[Bail in the United States#Federallaw|flight risk]] due to his 20 international flights in the prior 18 months.<ref>{{cite news |date=July 18, 2019 |first1=Bobby |last1=Allyn |first2=Brakkton |last2=Booker |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/18/741802612/jeffrey-epstein-is-denied-bail-in-sex-trafficking-case |title=Jeffrey Epstein Is Denied Bail In Sex Trafficking Case |website=NPR.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=July 18, 2019 |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Kevin |last2=Breuninger |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/07/18/jeffrey-epstein-bail-hearing-in-child-sex-traffic-case.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein's lust for young girls appears 'uncontrollable,' judge says in denying bail to accused sex trafficker |work=CNBC}}</ref> Epstein appealed the bail denial decision to the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]]. At the time of his death, this case was still pending.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/07/23/jeffrey-epstein-appeals-bail-denial-decision-in-sex-trafficking-case.html|title=Jeffrey Epstein appeals bail denial decision in child sex trafficking case |first1=Kevin |last1=Breuninger |first2=Dan |last2=Mangan |date=July 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Initial suicide attempt and final weeks===\nOn July 23, Epstein was found semiconscious in his cell with injuries to his neck. He told his lawyers that he had been assaulted by his cellmate.<ref>{{cite news |work=nypost.com |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/14/epstein-told-lawyers-that-cellmate-nicholas-tartaglione-roughed-him-up/ |title=Epstein told lawyers that cellmate Nicholas Tartaglione 'roughed him up' |first1=Bruce |last1=Golding |first2=Emily |last2=Saul |date=August 15, 2019}}</ref>  His cellmate, multiple murder and drug conspiracy suspect Nicholas Tartaglione, was questioned by prison officials but denied harming Epstein.<ref>{{cite web |date=July 25, 2019 |first1=Joelle |last1=Goldstein |url=https://people.com/crime/jeffrey-epstein-found-injured-nyc-jail-cell/ |title=Jeffrey Epstein Found Injured in NYC Jail Cell as Fellow Inmate Denies Assaulting Accused Pedophile |work=People.com |access-date=November 18, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/jeffrey-epstein-former-cellmate-apparent-suicide-attempt |title=Jeffrey Epstein feared cellmate, a muscle-bound ex-cop charged in murder who was moved before financier's death: report |first1=Nicole |last1=Darrah |date=August 12, 2019 |website=Fox News |language=en}}</ref> Tartaglione claimed that he had actually saved Epstein.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/ny-epstein-life-behind-bars-20190726-ujdvknsmz5a4rbcgzfms6cqti4-story.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein's ex-cop cellmate says he saved multimillionaire sex offender from hanging: source |first1=Stephen Rex |last1=Brown |first2=Rocco |last2=Parascandola |date=July 26, 2019 |access-date=December 18, 2019  |work=Daily News |language=en}}</ref> An internal prison investigation cleared Tartaglione in connection with the event.<ref name=\"cleared\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/crime-courts/jeffrey-epstein-s-former-cellmate-cleared-wrongdoing-incident-preceded-his-n1043341 |title=Jeffrey Epstein's former cellmate cleared of wrongdoing in incident that preceded his death |last1=Schapiro |first1=Rich |last2=Dienst |first2=Johnathan |date=August 16, 2019 |work=NBC News |access-date=August 21, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> After Epstein's death, Tartaglione was reportedly threatened by jail guards and told to \"stop talking\" after describing Epstein's death and conditions in the jail to the media.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/20/jail-guards-threatening-former-epstein-cell-mate-nicholas-tartaglione-lawyer/ |title=Jail guards threatening former Epstein cellmate Nicholas Tartaglione: lawyer |first1=Emily |last1=Saul |date=August 20, 2019}}</ref> An unnamed source suggested that Epstein staged the incident in order to be transferred.<ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/news/investigations/jeffrey-epstein-found-injured-marks-his-neck-new-york-jail-n1034301</ref> [[Spencer Kuvin]], a lawyer who represented three alleged victims of Epstein, stated in a July 2019 interview following Epstein's first apparent suicide attempt, that he believed it was an attack on his life, and stated there was a high probability that he would be murdered in prison.<ref name=\"Palm\">{{cite web |url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/20190810/jeffrey-epstein-lsquohe-could-buy-anything-including-his-own-deathrsquo |title=Jeffrey Epstein: 'He could buy anything, including his own death' |last1=Ramadan |first1=Lulu |date=August 10, 2019 |website=The Palm Beach Post |language=en |access-date=August 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/i-question-whether-or-not-it-was-a-true-suicide-attempt-lawyer-for-victims-worried-epstein-wont-make-it-to-trial/ |title='I Do Question Whether It Was a True Suicide Attempt': Victims' Lawyer Worries Epstein Won't Make It to Trial |last1=Clibanoff |first1=Matt |date=July 29, 2019 |work=Law & Crime |access-date=August 11, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the incident, Epstein was placed on [[suicide watch]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/epstein-taken-off-suicide-watch-before-death |title=Jeffrey Epstein was not on suicide watch before death, official says |first1=Louis |last1=Casiano |date=August 10, 2019 |website=Fox News}}</ref> He was placed in an observation cell, surrounded by windows, where lights were left on and any devices that could be used by the prisoner to [[suicide|take his own life]] were not permitted to be retained.<ref name=\"no way\">{{cite news |access-date=November 18, 2019 |first1=Bruce |last1=Golding |first2=Brad |last2=Hamilton |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/theres-no-way-jeffrey-epstein-killed-himself-a-former-nyc-jail-inmate-says |title=There's 'no way' Jeffrey Epstein killed himself, a former NYC jail inmate says |date=August 11, 2019 |website=New York Post}}</ref> Psychological staff dismissed Epstein from suicide watch after six days following a psychiatric examination.<ref name = 60minutes/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/11/jeffrey-epsteins-autopsy-results-are-expected-today-medical-examiner-says.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein's autopsy results expected as FBI and DOJ watchdog investigate apparent suicide |last1=Newburger |first1=Emma |date=August 11, 2019 |work=CNBC |access-date=August 21, 2019}}</ref> Some sources have reported that Epstein was removed from suicide watch after claiming that it was Tartaglione who \"roughed him up.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/14/epstein-told-lawyers-that-cellmate-nicholas-tartaglione-roughed-him-up/ |title=Epstein told lawyers that cellmate Nicholas Tartaglione 'roughed him up' |first1=Bruce |last1=Golding |first2=Emily |last2=Saul |date=August 15, 2019}}</ref> Epstein then returned to the SHU, where he was supposed to have a cellmate and be checked up on every 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/10/nyregion/jeffrey-epstein-suicide-watch.html |title=Why Wasn't Jeffrey Epstein on Suicide Watch When He Died? |first1=Ali |last1=Watkins |date=August 10, 2019 |access-date=December 18, 2019  |work=The New York Times |language=en}}</ref>\n\nEpstein was reportedly depositing funds into other prisoners' accounts to gain their favor or buy protection.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/17/jeffrey-epstein-tried-to-leverage-his-wealth-to-survive-in-jail-report/ |title=Jeffrey Epstein tried to leverage his wealth to survive in jail: report |first1=Eileen AJ |last1=Connelly |first2=Mara |last2=Siegler |date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> A paper note by Epstein was found in his cell after his death. In it, he complained about large bugs crawling on his body, guard Tova Noel giving him burnt food, and a guard intentionally locking him in a shower cell without clothes for an hour.{{efn|group=note|This letter was written in ball-point pen, despite the fact that no prisoners, especially those on suicide watch, were allowed to have one under jail protocol.}}<ref name = 60minutes/> On August 8, Jeffrey Epstein signed his [[Will and testament|last will and testament]], witnessed by two attorneys who knew him. The will named two longtime employees as executors, and immediately gifted  all of his assets, and any assets remaining in his estate, to a trust.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/19/jeffrey-epstein-signed-will-two-days-before-suicide/ |title=Jeffrey Epstein signed will just two days before suicide |last1=DeGregory |first1=Priscilla |last2=Sheehy |first2=Kate |date=August 19, 2019 |website=New York Post |access-date=August 20, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nThe jail informed the Justice Department, when Epstein was placed in the special housing unit (SHU), that he would have a cellmate and that a guard would look into the cell every 30 minutes. These procedures were not followed on the night he died.<ref name=\":36\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/11/nyregion/epstein-death-manhattan-correctional-center.html |title=Before Jail Suicide, Epstein Was Left Alone and Not Closely Monitored |last1=Benner |first1=Katie |date=August 11, 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=August 11, 2019 |last2=Ivory |first2=Danielle |last3=Oppel, Jr. |first3=Richard A. |language=en}}</ref> On August 9, Epstein's cellmate{{efn|group=note|This cellmate, Bill Mersey, noted that Epstein did not seem depressed or suicidal, but it was feasible for someone to hang themselves in a MCC cell.<ref>https://www.crimeonline.com/2020/03/12/jeffrey-epsteins-jailhouse-companion-says-pedophile-was-not-depressed-before-suicide/</ref>}} was transferred, and no replacement cellmate was brought in. The evening of his death, Epstein met with his lawyers, who described him as \"upbeat\" before being escorted back to the SHU at 7:49 PM by guard Tova Noel.<ref name = 60minutes>{{cite news |title=60 Minutes investigates the death of Jeffrey Epstein |first1=|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/did-jeffrey-epstein-kill-himself-60-minutes-investigates-2020-01-05/ |work=CBS |access-date=January 5, 2020 |date=January 5, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> CCTV footage shows that the two guards failed to perform the required institutional count at 10 PM and recorded Noel briefly walking by Epstein's cell at 10:30 PM, the last time the guards entered the tier where his cell was.<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/19/us/jeffrey-epstein-death-timeline/index.html |title=A timeline of what Jeffrey Epstein and his prison guards did in his final hours |last1=Levenson |first1=Eric |date=November 19, 2019 |work=CNN |access-date=December 14, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Through the night, in violation of the jail's normal procedure, Epstein was not checked every 30 minutes.<ref name=\":36\" /> The two guards who were assigned to check his cell overnight, Tova Noel and Michael Thomas, fell asleep at their desk{{efn|group=note|Their desk was about 15 feet away from Epstein's cell, but up a flight of stairs and through a locked gate<ref name = 60minutes/>}} for about three hours and later falsified related records.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/13/nyregion/jeffrey-epstein-jail-officers.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein Death: 2 Guards Slept Through Checks and Falsified Records |last1=Benner |first1=Katie |date=August 13, 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=August 14, 2019 |last2=Ivory |first2=Danielle |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-jeffrey-epstein-guards/two-jail-guards-for-jeffrey-epstein-charged-with-cover-up-in-his-suicide-idUSKBN1XT1VY |title=Two jail guards for Jeffrey Epstein charged with cover-up in his suicide |last1=Pierson |first1=brendan |date=August 13, 2019 |work=Reuters |language=en}}</ref> Two cameras in front of Epstein's cell also malfunctioned that night.<ref name=\"broken cameras\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-people-jeffrey-epstein-cameras-idUSKCN1VI2LC |title=FBI studies two broken cameras outside cell where Epstein died: source |last1=Hosenball |first1=Mark |date=August 28, 2019 |work=Reuters |access-date=August 29, 2019 |location=London |language=en}}</ref> Another camera had footage which was \"unusable\".<ref name=\"broken cameras\" />\n\n===Discovery===\n[[File:Epstein Body Moved From New York Hospital to Medical Examiner's Office.webm|thumb|right|Epstein's body being moved to the medical examiner's office]]\nAs the guards were distributing breakfast shortly after 6:30 AM on the morning of August 10, Epstein was found unresponsive in cardiac arrest in his cell, which was initially reported as apparent suicide.<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/>  He was found in a kneeling position with a strip of bedsheet{{efn|group=note|Epstein's possession of a bedsheet was also against jail protocol.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190814-usa-jeffrey-epstein-guards-fraud-hanging-suicide-prison-sex-trafficking |title=Jeffrey Epstein's guards placed on leave under suspicion of falsifying jail records |date=August 14, 2019 |website=France 24 |language=en}}</ref>}} wrapped around his neck. The sheet was tied to the top of his bunk.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/16/official-autopsy-shows-jeffrey-epstein-hanged-himself-in-jail-cell/ |title=Jeffrey Epstein's official autopsy confirms he hanged himself in jail cell |date=August 16, 2019 |website=New York Post |language=en}}</ref> He is believed to have been dead for about two hours. The guards performed [[CPR]] on Epstein, and other prisoners heard them yell \"Breathe, Epstein, breathe.\"<ref name = 60minutes/> At 6:33 AM, the guards pulled an alarm, notifying their supervisor, to whom Noel said, \"Epstein hung himself.\"<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/> He was rushed to the [[New York Downtown Hospital]] where he was pronounced dead at 6:39 AM.<ref>https://abcnews.go.com/US/jeffrey-epstein-accused-sex-trafficker-dies-suicide-officials/story?id=64881684</ref> His body was transported to the medical examiner's office soon after.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jeffrey-epstein-death-investigation-alleged-victims-vow-to-keep-seeking-justice/ |title=As mystery surrounding Jeffrey Epstein's death deepens, alleged victims vow to keep seeking justice |date=August 12, 2019 |work=CBS News |language=en}}</ref>  The news of the death was posted on [[4chan]] about 38 minutes before ''ABC News'' broke the news.  If it was posted by a first responder, as it has been speculated, it would likely be a violation of [[Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act|privacy law]].<ref>{{cite news |first1=Jane |last1=Lytvynenko |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/janelytvynenko/fdny-review-jeffrey-epstein-4chan-post |date=August 13, 2019 |title=Epstein's Death Was On 4Chan Before Officials Announced It \u2014 And Authorities Had To Look Into It |work=BuzzFeed News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/fdny-reviews-reports-that-epstein-death-leaked-on-4chan |title=FDNY reviews reports of Epstein death leaked on 4Chan |first1=Vandana |last1=Rambaran |date=August 13, 2019 |work=Fox News |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe removal of Epstein\u2019s body from his cell was a violation of protocol, as the [[Bureau of Prisons]] mandates that a suicide scene be treated with the \"same level of protection as any crime scene in which a death has occurred.\"<ref name = 60minutes/> Consequently, prison personnel also failed to photograph Epstein's body as it was found.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/01/5-takeaways-from-the-60-minutes-jeffrey-epstein-report.html|title=5 Takeaways From the 60 Minutes Jeffrey Epstein Report |last1=Raymond |first1=Adam K. |date=January 6, 2020 |work=New York Magazine |access-date=March 19, 2020 |location=New York City |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Discrepancies===\nEpstein's death was the first death ruled a suicide at the MCC in 14 years. Michael Baden and ''[[60 Minutes]]'' have questioned if Epstein, who was almost 6 feet tall and weighed 185 pounds, could have physically been able to hang himself from the lower bunk. Photos taken after the death also show bottles and medicine standing upright on the top bunk.<ref name = 60minutes/> A former inmate at the MCC described the sheets as \"paper level, not strong enough\" to support Epstein's body.<ref name=\"no way\" /> Baden questioned why Epstein didn't use other materials available in his cell as a ligature, such as wires and tubing from a [[Sleep apnea|sleep apnea machine]], which were stronger and longer.<ref name = 60minutes/>\n\n==Autopsy and medical evidence==\n[[File:Epstein neck split.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|Note the positioning on the marks on Epstein's neck. According to a pathologist, \"Marks that indicate the noose was below the hyoid bone would suggest that the hanging was staged and the actual cause of death was strangulation. Marks in the area between the chin and Adam\u2019s apple would indicate the death was more likely a hanging.\"\n<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-only-thing-jeffrey-epsteins-broken-hyoid-bone-proves |title=The Only Thing Jeffrey Epstein\u2019s Broken Bone Proves |first1=Michael |last1=Daly |website=The Daily Beast |date=August 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>]]\nA four-hour autopsy on Epstein's body was conducted on August 11 by New York City's Chief Medical Examiner [[Barbara Sampson]]. Epstein's lawyers sent pathologist [[Michael Baden]] to personally observe the city's autopsy.<ref name = 60minutes/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/jeffrey-epstein-camp-sends-pathologist-michael-baden-to-watch-over-his-autopsy |title=Jeffrey Epstein Camp Sent Pathologist Michael Baden to Watch Over His Autopsy |first1=Pervaiz |last1=Shallwani |first2=Audrey |last2=McNamara |first3=Harry |last3=Siegel |date=August 11, 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Beast}}</ref> Following the autopsy, the medical examiner's office reported that Epstein had hanged himself with a sheet from his bed.<ref name=\"Sisak\">{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/a947e0d85d31496eb5bd9ff4994c9718 |first1=Michael R. |last1=Sisak |first2=Michael |last2=Balsamo |first3=Larry |last3=Neumeister |title=Medical examiner rules Epstein death a suicide by hanging |date=August 17, 2019 |work=AP News |language=en}}</ref> On August 14, unofficial sources reported that broken bones were found in Epstein's neck, although this can occur in the suicide of the elderly. They are said to be \"more common in victims of homicide by strangulation\",<ref name=\"broken bones\" /> though multiple studies have found different percentages for both manners of death.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://heavy.com/news/2019/08/jeffrey-epstein-hyoid-bone-broken-neck/ |title=Jeffrey Epstein's Broken Hyoid Neck Bone: How Common Is It? |first1=Jessica |last1=McBride |date=August 15, 2019}}</ref> Epstein's lawyers released a joint statement following the report of the medical examiner, expressing that they were not satisfied, challenging the conclusions and saying that a more complete response was forthcoming. They also indicated that the defense team fully intends to continue its own independent and complete investigation into the circumstances and cause of their client's death,<ref>{{cite news |first1=Mike |last1=Brest |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/epsteins-lawyers-not-satisfied-with-the-conclusions-of-the-medical-examiner |title=Epstein's lawyers 'not satisfied with the conclusions of the medical examiner' |date=August 18, 2019 |work=Washington Examiner |language=en}}</ref> including taking legal action, if necessary, to view the pivotal camera footage near his cell during the night of his death.<ref name=\"Frias\">{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jeffrey-epsteins-lawyers-to-launch-own-investigation-into-his-death-2019-8 |title=Jeffrey Epstein's lawyers blast 'medieval conditions' at federal jail where he died by suicide and say they are launching their own investigation |last1=Frias |first1=Lauren |date=August 16, 2019 |work=Business Insider |access-date=August 19, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> They later said that the evidence concerning Epstein's death was \"far more consistent\" with murder than suicide.<ref name=\":39\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/epstein-death-murder-suicide-victims-hearing-1456397 |title=Epstein Lawyers say evidence 'far more consistent' with murder than suicide |last1=Stockler |first1=Asher |date=August 27, 2019 |work=Newsweek |access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Autopsy report and criticism===\n[[File:Hyoid bone - animation.gif|thumb|left|upright=0.8|Epstein's [[hyoid bone]], among others, was broken. It is disputed whether this is more indicative of hanging or strangulation.]]\nOn August 16, Sampson announced that Epstein's death had been ruled a suicide by hanging.<ref name=\"dailybeaster\">{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/jeffrey-epstein-death-ruled-suicide-by-new-york-city-medical-examiner |title=Epstein's Death Was Suicide: Medical Examiner |first1=Pervaiz |last1=Shallwani |date=August 16, 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Beast |language=en}}</ref> Later conflicting reports stated that the injuries Epstein sustained were as consistent, if not more so, with strangulation or homicide as with suicide.<ref name=\"broken bones\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com//politics/autopsy-finds-broken-bones-in-jeffrey-epsteins-neck-deepening-questions-around-his-death/2019/08/14/d09ac934-bdd9-11e9-b873-63ace636af08_story.html |title=Autopsy finds broken bones in Jeffrey Epstein's neck, deepening questions around his death |first1=Carol D. |last1=Leonnig |first2=Aaron C. |last2=Davis |work=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/aug/16/jeffrey-epstein-cause-of-death-coroner-report |title=Medical examiner says Jeffrey Epstein's death was a suicide |date=August 16, 2019 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> However, Sampson's report found that there was no [[Crime|foul play]] in Epstein's death.<ref>{{cite news |work=Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/suicide-epstein-autopsy-finds-no-sign-of-foul-play/articleshow/70720626.cms |title='Suicide': Epstein autopsy finds no sign of foul play |access-date=August 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819030438/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/suicide-epstein-autopsy-finds-no-sign-of-foul-play/articleshow/70720626.cms |archive-date=August 19, 2019 |url-status=dead |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://7news.com.au/news/crime/no-foul-play-in-epstein-death-says-me-c-404030 |title=No foul play in Epstein death: US coroner |date=August 16, 2019 |work=7NEWS.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://10daily.com.au/news/a190816fviox/medical-examiner-rules-no-foul-play-in-epstein-death-20190817 |title=Jeffrey Epstein Death Ruled 'Suicide By Hanging' |date=August 17, 2019 |work=10 daily}}</ref> Three of Epstein's lawyers expressed their dissatisfaction with Sampson's conclusion of suicide, having hired forensic pathologist Dr. [[Michael Baden]] to observe the autopsy; they said they would be initiating their own investigation and will be providing a more detailed statement in the future.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abc6onyourside.com/news/nation-world/medical-examiner-rules-epsteins-death-a-suicide |title=Epstein lawyers dissatisfied with autopsy result |first1=Michael R. |last1=Sisak |first2=Michael |last2=Balsamo |first3=Larry |last3=Neumeister |agency=Associated Press |date=August 16, 2019 |website=WSYX |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jeffrey-epsteins-lawyers-to-launch-own-investigation-into-his-death-2019-8 |title=Jeffrey Epstein's lawyers blast 'medieval conditions' at federal jail where he died by suicide and say they are launching their own investigation |first1=Lauren |last1=Frias |website=Business Insider |date=August 17, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Baden observed Sampson's autopsy when it was conducted; after the autopsy he indicated that he was unable to comment due to gag orders filed by Sampson's office and \nEpstein's estate.<ref name=\"dailybeaster\" />\n\nOn October 30, 2019, Baden issued a report stating that Epstein's neck injuries were much more consistent with \"homicidal strangulation\" than suicide. He stated that Epstein \"had two fractures on the left and right sides of his [[larynx]], specifically the thyroid cartilage or [[Adam's apple]], as well as one fracture on the left hyoid bone above the Adam's apple\". In particular, Baden claimed that Epstein\u2019s [[hyoid bone]] was [[Hyoid bone fracture|broken]] in a way indicative of strangulation from behind.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.insider.com/epstein-used-his-jail-bedsheet-to-commit-suicide-by-hanging-2019-8 |title=Epstein died by suicide using his jail bed sheet while his guards slept, according to report}}</ref> Baden later said, \"Going over a thousand jail hangings, suicides in the New York City state prisons over the past 40-50 years, no one had three fractures.\"<ref name=\"60minutes\"/> However, neurosurgeon [[Sanjay Gupta]] asserts that Epstein could have easily broken his hyoid bone in a hanging due to the bone's weakening and loss of flexibility with age. Gupta also suggested that the presence of multiple broken neck-bones was more characteristic of hanging. [[Gerald Rodts]], chief of spinal surgery at [[Emory University Hospital]], also pointed to the presence of multiple broken neck-bones as consistent with hanging. Bill Lloyd, an anatomic pathologist, claimed that Epstein's broken hyoid bone was \"meaningless\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/16/media/epstein-washington-post-reliable-sources/index.html |title=The Washington Post fuels Epstein conspiracies, but experts say evidence still consistent with suicide |first1=Oliver |last1=Darcy |website=CNN |date=August 17, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe neck wound was in the center of his neck, not under his mandibles as in a typical hanging. Baden points to this as being more common when a victim is strangled by a wire or cord. Baden has also noted that the wound is much thinner than the strip of bedsheet was, and although there was blood on Epstein's neck, it was absent on the bed-sheet ligature.<ref name=\"60minutes\"/> According to the autopsy files, Epstein also had contusions on both of his wrists, an abrasion on his left forearm, and deep muscle hemorrhaging of his left deltoid or shoulder. His brother, Mark, later suggested that he was \"handcuffed and struggled.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/jeffrey-epstein-unexplained-injuries-wrists-shoulder-brother |title=Jeffrey Epstein had 'unexplained' injuries on wrists and shoulder, brother says |date=November 6, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Epstein also had hemorrhages in his eyes, which although not unheard of in hangings, are more common in strangulations.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/jeffrey-epstein-prison-cell-death-alone |title=Jeffrey Epstein was alone in prison cell the night of his death, feds say, citing video |first1=Talia |last1=Kaplan |date=November 19, 2019 |work=Fox News |language=en}}</ref> Baden has also noted that Epstein's lower legs lacked [[lividity]], suggesting that he did not die in an upright position.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/16/disturbing-evidence-in-jeffrey-epsteins-autopsy-points-to-his-murder-pathologist/ |title=Disturbing evidence in Jeffrey Epstein\u2019s autopsy points to his murder: pathologist |first1=Lee |last1=Brown |first2=Steinbush |last2=Yaron |date=January 16, 2020 |work=New York Post |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Burial===\nFollowing the autopsy, Epstein's body was claimed by an \"unidentified associate,\" later revealed to be his brother, Mark.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/crime-courts/jeffrey-epstein-s-body-claimed-unidentified-associate-n1042551 |title=Jeffrey Epstein's body claimed by unidentified 'associate' |date=August 14, 2019 |work=NBC News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/jeffrey-epsteins-body-claimed-by-brother-mark-epstein |title=Jeffrey Epstein's Body Claimed by His Brother |date=August 16, 2019 |newspaper=The Daily Beast |last1=Shallwani |first1=Pervaiz}}</ref>  On September 5, Epstein's body was buried in an unmarked tomb next to those of his parents at the IJ Morris Star of David mausoleum in [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]], Florida.  The names of his parents were also removed from their tombstone in order to prevent vandalism.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/Jeffery-Epstein-buried-in-unmarked-grave-with-family-names-removed-600753 |title=Jeffery Epstein buried in unmarked grave with family names removed |date=September 5, 2019 |work=The Jerusalem Post |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\n===Reaction===\n{{external media\n|width=210px\n|float=right\n|video1={{YouTube|link=no|id=vk3eZoxlkuYc|title=Trump: 'I have no idea' if Clintons were involved in Epstein's death}} (0:51)\n|video2={{YouTube|link=no|id=YPKEyID72Ew|title=Attorney General William Barr says he's \"appalled\" by Jeffrey Epstein's death in jail}} (1:50)\n}}\n[[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Donald Trump]] initially responded to Epstein's death by [[retweet]]ing a [[Clinton Body Count|conspiracy theory]] linking Epstein's death to former president [[Bill Clinton]] and former [[United States Secretary of State|secretary of state]] [[Hillary Clinton]], a few hours after Epstein's death was announced.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[thehill.com]] |first1=Rachel |last1=Frazin |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/456979-trump-retweets-post-promoting-conspiracy-theory-about-jeffrey |title=Trump retweets post promoting conspiracy theory about Jeffrey Epstein's death |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> At an energy speech in [[Pennsylvania]], Trump told reporters he wanted \"a full investigation.\"<ref>{{cite news |work=[[thehill.com]] |first1=Rachel |last1=Frazin |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/13/donald-trump-defends-jeffrey-epstein-bill-clinton-conspiracy-retweet/1996632001/ |title=Donald Trump defends his Jeffrey Epstein, Bill Clinton conspiracy retweet |access-date=April 8, 2020 |date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Attorney General [[William Barr]] said he was \"appalled\" by Epstein's death while in federal custody and that it \"raises serious questions that must be answered.\" He ordered an investigation by the Justice Department's [[Office of Inspector General (United States)|Inspector General]] in addition to the FBI investigation.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Jesse |last1=Byrnes |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/456959-attorney-general-barr-appalled-by-epstein-death-in-federal-custody |title=Attorney General Barr 'appalled' by Epstein death in federal custody |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Senator [[Ben Sasse]], chairman of the United States Senate Judiciary oversight subcommittee, later wrote a letter to Barr saying \"The Department of Justice failed.\" He added \"Given Epstein's previous attempted suicide, he should have been locked in a padded room under unbroken, 24/7, constant surveillance. Obviously, heads must roll.\"<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Rachel |last1=Frazin |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/456963-sasse-tells-ag-that-heads-must-roll-over-epstein-treatment-in-federal-custody |title=Sasse tells AG that 'heads must roll' over Epstein treatment in federal custody |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Rep. [[Matt Gaetz]], who sits on the [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|United States House Judiciary Committee]], called on chairman Rep. [[Jerry Nadler]]  to prioritize investigating the circumstances around Epstein's death over other probes being carried out by the committee.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Tal |last1=Axelrod |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/456949-ocasio-cortez-calls-for-answers-after-epstein-found-dead-in-jail-cell |title=Ocasio-Cortez demands 'answers' after Epstein found dead in jail cell |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 10, 201 |language=en}}</ref> Rep. [[Lois Frankel]] called for a congressional investigation into the 2008 plea deal for Epstein.<ref name=\"democrats call\">{{cite news |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/456954-democrat-calls-for-congressional-investigation-into-epstein-death |title=Democrat calls for congressional investigation after Epstein death |last1=Campisi |first1=Jessica |date=August 10, 2019 |work=The Hill |access-date=August 21, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Senators [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] and [[Rick Scott]] both called for an investigation and expressed their dissatisfaction that Epstein\u2019s victims would not find closure in a trial.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Zack |last1=Budryk |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/457019-gillibrand-calls-for-full-investigation-into-epsteins-death |title=Gillibrand calls for 'full investigation' into Epstein's death |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 11, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Tal |last1=Axelrod |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/456956-gop-senator-inexcusable-that-epstein-not-under-constant-suicide-watch |title=GOP senator: 'Inexcusable' that Epstein not under constant suicide watch |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n | quote  = \"I do think there needs to be a full investigation about why he was taken off the suicide watch list; I think it\u2019s a strange decision, given that he attempted suicide once already. I want to know why he was left in a circumstance where suicide was even possible.\"\n | source = '''Sen. [[Kirsten Gillibrand]]'''<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Zack |last1=Budryk |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/sunday-talk-shows/457019-gillibrand-calls-for-full-investigation-into-epsteins-death |title=Gillibrand calls for 'full investigation' into Epstein's death |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 11, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n | width = 210px\n | align = left\n}}\nOn August 12, 2019, the leaders of the House Judiciary Committee, Chairman [[Jerry Nadler]] and ranking member [[Doug Collins (politician)|Doug Collins]], sent 23 questions to the Federal Bureau of Prisons about Epstein's death. \"The apparent suicide of this high-profile and\u2014if allegations are proven to be accurate\u2014particularly reprehensible individual while in the federal government's custody demonstrates severe miscarriages of or deficiencies in inmate protocol and has allowed the deceased to ultimately evade facing justice,\" they wrote. \"Any victims of Mr. Epstein's actions will forever be denied proper recourse and the scintilla of recompense our justice system can provide in the face of such alleged atrocities; the competency and rigor of our criminal justice system has been marred by this apparent oversight.\"<ref>{{cite news |first1=Zack |last1=Budryk |work=The Hill |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/457174-judiciary-committee-leaders-demand-answers-from-bureau-of-prisons-on-epstein |title=House Judiciary leaders demand answers from Bureau of Prisons on Epstein death |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> Later on August 13, Nebraska senator Ben Sasse, the chair of the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]], wrote a letter to  Attorney General Barr urging him to \"rip up\" the 2008 non-prosecution deal for Epstein and his co-conspirators. Sasse argued that the Justice Department must bring Epstein's co-conspirators to justice despite his death, and added, \"This crooked deal cannot stand.\"<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Justin |last1=Wise |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/457288-sasse-calls-on-justice-dept-to-rip-up-epstein-non-prosecution-deal-to |title=Sasse calls on DOJ to 'rip up' Epstein nonprosecution deal to bring 'co-conspirators to justice' |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n\"For them to pull him off suicide watch is shocking,\" Cameron Lindsay, a former warden at three federal facilities, told [[NBC News]]. \"For someone this high-profile, with these allegations and this many victims, who has had a suicide attempt in the last few weeks, you can take absolutely no chances. You leave him on suicide watch until he's out of there.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/prison-experts-are-stunned-angry-jeffrey-epstein-was-taken-suicide-n1041121 |title=Prison experts are stunned and angry that Jeffrey Epstein was taken off suicide watch |date=August 10, 2019 |work=NBC News |access-date=August 21, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Federal prosecutors in the case called Epstein's death \"disturbing\" and emphasized that they would continue to seek justice for his accusers even after the financier's death. [[Geoffrey Berman]], the [[United States Attorney for the Southern District of New York]], said in a statement, \"To those brave young women who have already come forward and to the many others who have yet to do so, let me reiterate that we remain committed to standing for you, and our investigation of the conduct charged in the indictment\u2014which included a conspiracy count\u2014remains ongoing.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/sdny-us-attorneys-office-confirms-epstein-investigation-remains-ongoing-conspiracy-2019-8 |title=Federal prosecutors confirm that the Epstein sex-trafficking investigation will continue despite his death |last1=Tenbarge |first1=Kat |date=August 10, 2019 |work=Business Insider |access-date=August 21, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Investigations===\n[[File:William Barr delivers remarks at the Correctional Workers Week Memorial Service.jpg|thumb|right|Attorney General William Barr described Epstein's death as \"a perfect storm of screw-ups.\"]]\nThe [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] subsequently launched an investigation of the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death,<ref>{{cite news |date=August 10, 2019 |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/news/456957-fbi-investigating-epstein-death-in-manhattan-jail |title=FBI investigating Epstein death in Manhattan jail |newspaper=The Hill |access-date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> with Attorney General Barr saying that Justice Department officials will thoroughly investigate \"serious irregularities\" at the Metropolitan Correctional Center (MCC) where Epstein was found dead. Barr also warned that any of Epstein's alleged co-conspirators \"should not rest easy,\" noting that federal prosecutors will continue to aggressively pursue the case to ensure anyone who worked alongside Epstein will be held accountable. \"We are now learning of serious irregularities at this facility that are deeply concerning and demand a thorough investigation,\" Barr said during remarks at a law enforcement conference in New Orleans. \"The FBI and the Office of Inspector General are doing just that.\" Barr said he was \"appalled\" and \"angry\" over the developments; he insisted that the Justice Department would \"get to the bottom\" of what happened and promised accountability. \"Let me assure you this case will continue on against anyone who was complicit with Epstein,\" Barr said. \"Any co-conspirators should not rest easy. The victims deserve justice and they will get it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/457095-barr-promises-thorough-investigation-of-epstein-death-warns |title=Barr criticizes prison's 'serious irregularities' after Epstein death |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 12, 2019}}</ref> As Barr received more information surrounding Epstein's death, he came to believe that it was only \"a perfect storm of screw-ups.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/ag-barr-epsteins-death-was-a-perfect-storm-of-screw-ups/ar-BBX9U8P |title=AG Barr: Epstein's death was a 'perfect storm of screw-ups' |work=MSN |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019 [[Kathleen Hawk Sawyer]], the director of the [[Bureau of Prisons]], told the Senate Judiciary Committee that the FBI is investigating whether a \"criminal enterprise\" was involved in Epstein's death. She added that there is \"no indication, from anything I know\" that his death \"was anything other than a suicide.\" A spokesperson later explained that she had used the phrase \"criminal enterprise\" because that was what Senator Lindsey Graham has asked her about, and that \"she was referring to looking into possible criminal conduct by staff.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/19/jeffrey-epstein-death-in-jail-under-fbi-investigation.html |title=FBI probing if Jeffrey Epstein's death was the result of a 'criminal enterprise,' prisons chief says |last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |date=November 19, 2019 |work=CNBC |access-date=November 20, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn August 13, Attorney General Barr ordered the Bureau of Prisons to temporarily reassign the warden of the MCC, Lamine N'Diaye, while the FBI and Justice Department inspector general investigate the circumstances surrounding Epstein's death. James Petrucci, the warden of [[Federal Correctional Institution, Otisville|FCI Otisville]], was named acting warden.<ref name=\"warden reassigned\">{{cite news |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/13/jeffrey-epstein-warden-shirley-skipper-scott-reassigned-after-suicide/1999993001/ |title=New York warden reassigned after Jeffrey Epstein's death; two staffers placed on leave |first1=Kevin |last1=Johnson |work=USA TodaaODAY |date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Two staff members assigned to Epstein's unit have also been placed on administrative leave.<ref name=\"warden reassigned\" /><ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Morgan |last1=Chalfant |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/457281-doj-reassigns-warden-after-epstein-apparent-suicide |title=DOJ reassigns warden after Epstein's apparent suicide |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> On August 14, Manhattan federal court judge Richard Berman, who was overseeing Epstein's criminal case, wrote to the Metropolitan Correctional Centre warden Lamine N'Diaye inquiring as to whether an investigation into Epstein\u2019s death would include a probe into his prior (July 23) injuries.  Judge Berman wrote that to his knowledge it has never been definitely explained what they concluded about the incident.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/08/14/epstein-judge-wants-answers-about-first-incident-in-jail/ |title=Epstein judge wants answers about first incident in jail |first1=Emily |last1=Saul |date=August 14, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n{{external media\n|width=210px\n|float=left\n|video1={{YouTube|link=no|id=RQyalWtHDec|title=Ben Sasse presses prison bureau director on Jeffrey Epstein death}} (5:43)\n|video2={{YouTube|link=no|id=kFTfQ8IoHzw|title=Epstein guards appear in court}} (1:24)\n}}\n\n\nTwo French Cabinet officials [[Marl\u00e8ne Schiappa]] and [[Adrien Taquet]] subsequently called for an investigation into the \"many unanswered questions\" about Epstein's ties to France, calling for the [[Government of France|French government]] to launch its own probe. \"The US investigation has highlighted links with France,\" Schiappa and Taquet said in the statement, according to ABC. \"It thus seems to us fundamental for the victims that an investigation be opened in France so that all is brought to light.\" \"The elements received at the Paris prosecutor's office are being analyzed and cross-referenced,\" a spokesperson for the office told [[ABC News]]. \"The first audits are currently underway to determine whether an investigation should be opened in France.\"<ref>{{cite news |work=The Hill |first1=Zack |last1=Budryk |url=https://thehill.com/policy/international/europe/457221-french-officials-call-for-investigation-of-epstein-links-with |title=French officials call for investigation of Epstein 'links with France' |access-date=August 13, 2019 |date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAll charges against Epstein were officially dismissed on August 29.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/29/us/jeffrey-epstein-criminal-case-dismissed/index.html |title=The criminal case against Jeffrey Epstein has been officially dismissed |last1=Adone |first1=Dakin |date=August 29, 2019 |work=CNN|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> As a result, the ongoing sex-trafficking investigations and media attention shifted attention towards his alleged associates, such as [[Prince Andrew]], [[Jean-Luc Brunel]], and [[Ghislaine Maxwell]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/epsteins-death-leaves-unanswered-questions-for-investigators-11565541496 |title=Epstein's Death Sparks Probe, Shifts Spotlight to Associates |last1=O'brien |first1=Rebecca Davis |last2=Hong |first2=Nicole |last3=Chapman |first3=Ben |last4=Gurman |first4=Sadie |date=August 11, 2019 |work=Wall Street Journal |access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/22/jeffrey-epstein-scandal-prince-andrew-kicked-out-of-buckingham-palace.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein scandal: Prince Andrew booted from Buckingham Palace, report says |last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |date=November 22, 2019 |work=CNBC |access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/lisettevoytko/2019/12/27/report-fbi-investigating-epstein-confidante-ghislaine-maxwell/#dfdd1da37158 |title=Report: FBI Investigating Epstein Confidante Ghislaine Maxwell |last1=Voytko |first1=Lisette |date=December 27, 2019 |work=Forbes |access-date=January 2, 2020}}</ref> Following Epstein\u2019s death, Maxwell sued his estate, claiming that she was owed compensation for legal fees due to her close relationship with Epstein.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/19/jeffrey-epstein-associate-ghislaine-maxwell-sues-his-estate</ref>\n\n====Related criminal trials====\nOn November 19, 2019, federal prosecutors in New York indicted [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|Metropolitan Correctional Center]] guards Michael Thomas and Tova Noel, charged with creating false records and conspiracy.<ref name=\"NPR-charge\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/19/780794931/prosecutors-charge-correctional-officers-who-guarded-jeffrey-epstein-before-his- |title=Jeffrey Epstein's Prison Guards Are Indicted On Federal Charges |last1=Allyn |first1=Bobby |work=NPR |series=All Things Considered |date=November 19, 2019 |access-date=December 11, 2019 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-50480172 |title=Epstein guards charged with falsifying records |date=November 19, 2019 |access-date=November 19, 2019 |language=en-GB}}</ref> The charges were based on video footage obtained by prosecutors, indicating that Epstein was not observed by them for eight hours, while the two guards made personal searches on their computers and slept. According to [[Geoffrey Berman]], the U.S. Attorney for the Southern District of New York, during that time they repeatedly signed records affirming that they had performed the required checks.<ref name=\"NPR-charge\" /> Their bail was set at $100,000.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/19/nyregion/epstein-prison-guards-arrested.html |title=Guards Accused of Napping and Shopping Online the Night Epstein Died |first1=Michael |last1=Gold |first2=Danielle |last2=Ivory |first3=Nicole |last3=Hong |date=November 19, 2019 |newspaper=The New York Times |language=en}}</ref> They claimed that they were \"scapegoats\" for larger issues within the federal prison system.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/25/nyregion/jeffrey-epstein-guards-tova-noel-michael-thomas.html |title=Epstein Suicide: Guards Say They're Scapegoats for a Broken System |first1=Benjamin |last1=Weiser |date=November 25, 2019 |newspaper=The New York Times |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/20/us/jeffrey-epstein-prison-guard-system/index.html |title=Attorneys for Jeffrey Epstein's prison guards point the blame at the system |first1=Eric |last1=Levenson |first2=Mark |last2=Morales | first3=David |last3=Shortell |date=November 20, 2019 |newspaper=CNN |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn a December 2019 court proceeding against Epstein's cellmate Nick Tartaglione, federal prosecutors reported that the surveillance footage from outside Epstein's cell during the July 23 incident had disappeared. Tartaglione's defense had sought to use the footage to demonstrate his character while he allegedly saved Epstein. Tartaglione's lawyer had requested that the footage be retained on July 25, two days after the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/18/jeffrey-epsteins-first-suicide-attempt-video-is-missing.html |title=Jail video surveillance from Jeffrey Epstein's first suicide attempt in July is missing, prosecutor says, according to reports|last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |date=December 18, 2019 |website=The Seattle Times |access-date=December 18, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Judge Kenneth Karas requested that the government determine what had happened to the footage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/surveillance-footage-outside-jeffrey-epsteins-cell-during-suicide-attempt-is-missing/ |title=Surveillance footage outside Jeffrey Epstein's cell during suicide attempt is missing |last1=Brown |first1=Stephen Rex |date=December 18, 2019 |website=The Seattle Times |access-date=December 18, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Several days later, federal prosecutors reversed their statement, claiming that they had found the missing footage. But in January 2020, they admitted that the footage had been permanently deleted due to a \"clerical error\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/epsteins-suicide-attempt-video-preserved-prosecutors |title=Lost Jeffrey Epstein suicide attempt video is found: Prosecutors |last1=Pagones |first1=Stephanie |date=December 20, 2019 |website=The Seattle Times |access-date=December 23, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/surveillance-video-jeffrey-epstein-s-first-apparent-suicide-attempt-no-n1113166?cid=sm_npd_nn_fb_ma |title=Surveillance video from Jeffrey Epstein's first apparent suicide attempt 'no longer exists' |last1=Winter |first1=Tom |date=January 9, 2020 |website=NBC News |access-date=December 23, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Homicide suspicions and speculation==\n[[File:Conspiracy theorist (48555437426).jpg|thumb|A partisan protestor alleging outside involvement shortly after Epstein's death]]\nDue to violations of standard prison procedures, and Epstein's knowledge of compromising information about famous individuals, his death by \"apparent suicide\"<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite news |last1=Allyn |first1=Bobby |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/19/780794931/prosecutors-charge-correctional-officers-who-guarded-jeffrey-epstein-before-his- |title=Jeffrey Epstein's Prison Guards Are Indicted On Federal Charges |work=National Public Radio |date=November 19, 2019}}</ref> spawned skepticism, as well as multiple [[conspiracy theories]]. Epstein conspiracy theorists have been labeled \"Epstein Truthers,\" similar to [[9/11 Truth movement|those who dispute the accepted account of the 9/11 attacks]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/qvgpm3/epstein-truthers-are-obsessed-with-a-sci-fi-book-about-child-sex-slavery-written-by-bill-barrs-dad/ |title=Epstein Truthers Are Obsessed With a Sci-Fi Book About Child Sex Slavery Written by Bill Barr\u2019s Dad|date=August 16, 2019 |website=Vie |access-date=February 2, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> A [[Rasmussen Reports|Rasmussen]] poll conducted shortly after his death in August 2019 found that only 29% of U.S. adults believed Epstein actually committed suicide, while 42% thought he was murdered to prevent him from testifying against powerful people with whom he associated, and 29% of people were undecided.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rasmussenreports.com/public_content/politics/general_politics/august_2019/americans_say_murder_more_likely_than_suicide_in_epstein_case |title=Americans Say Murder More Likely Than Suicide in Epstein Case |date=August 14, 2019 |website=[[Rasmussen Reports]] |access-date=August 24, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> By November 2019, a ''[[Business Insider]]'' poll found that those who believed Epstein was murdered outnumbered suicide proponents three to one.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jeffrey-epstein-kill-himself-poll-2019-11 |title=Almost half of Americans now believe the conspiracy theory that sex offender Jeffrey Epstein was murdered |first1=Jacob |last1=Shamsian |work=Business Insider |language=en}}</ref> In a 2020 poll, Rasmussen found that a majority of Americans believed Epstein was murdered, with just 21% believing that he committed suicide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rasmussenreports.com/public_content/lifestyle/people/january_2020/most_now_think_jeffrey_epstein_was_murdered |title=Most Now Think Jeffrey Epstein Was Murdered |date=January 9, 2020 |website=[[Rasmussen Reports]] |access-date=February 2, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[University of Chicago]] professor Eric Oliver, a conspiracy theory expert, labeled [[Populism#North America|populist]] sentiment and a [[Anti-establishment#Anti-establishment in the United States|mistrust of the political system]] as major contributors to the widespread rejection of the official narrative.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://time.com/5737975/jeffrey-epstein-death-conspiracy-theories/ |title=Feds Denounce Jeffrey Epstein Death Conspiracy Theories|date=November 23, 2019 |website=Time |access-date=December 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBecause of his connections to many wealthy and powerful people, there was speculation that some co-conspirator or participant in his sex crimes might have arranged for him to be silenced.<ref name=\"Palm\" /> In the hours after the death, the hashtag [[Clinton Body Count|#ClintonBodyCount]] and the countering #TrumpBodyCount were trending on Twitter as users accused Bill and Hillary Clinton and Donald Trump of being involved in Epstein's death.<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite news |title='Epstein Didn't Kill Himself' and the Meme-ing of Conspiracy |first1=Emma Grey |last1=Ellis |url=https://www.wired.com/story/epstein-didnt-kill-himself-conspiracy/ |work=Wired |date=November 15, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/8/10/20800195/clintonbodycount-conspiracy-theory-jeffrey-epstein |title=The conspiracy theories about the Clintons and Jeffrey Epstein's death, explained |last1=Matthews |first1=Dylan |date=August 10, 2019 |website=Vox |access-date=August 11, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Several hours after Epstein was found dead, Trump retweeted a [[conspiracy theory]] by Terrence K. Williams, a comedian and conservative commentator, suggesting that there was a connection between the Clintons and Epstein's death\u2014furthering a perennial conspiracy theory dating to the early 1990s that the Clintons have had numerous people killed to silence them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-retweets-epstein-conspiracy-theory-claiming-clinton-connection-n1041146 |title=Trump retweets Epstein conspiracy theory, claiming Clinton connection |last1=Timm |first1=Jane C. |last2=Johnstone |first2=Liz |date=August 10, 2019 |work=NBC News |access-date=August 11, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/8/10/20800195/clintonbodycount-conspiracy-theory-jeffrey-epstein |title=The conspiracy theories about the Clintons and Jeffrey Epstein's death, explained |first1=Dylan |last1=Matthews |date=August 10, 2019 |website=Vox}}</ref> The retweet was immediately showcased worldwide.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/nightly-news/video/trump-fuels-jeffrey-epstein-conspiracy-theories-on-social-media-65954373986 |title=Trump fuels Jeffrey Epstein conspiracy theories on social media |date=August 12, 2019 |work=NBC News |access-date=August 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Trump retweets post implying Bill Clinton behind Jeffrey Epstein's death |first1=Sam |last1=Dorman |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/donald-trump-bill-clinton-jeffrey-epstein-suicide-theory |work=Fox News |date=August 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt an August 27 hearing, Epstein defense attorney Reid Weingarten expressed \"significant doubts\" that Epstein's death was due to suicide. According to Weingarten, when attorneys met with their client shortly before his death, \"we did not see a despairing, despondent, suicidal person\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/27/jeffrey-epsteins-lawyers-skeptical-of-suicide-ruling.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein's lawyers highly 'skeptical' of suicide ruling, say he wasn't 'despairing, despondent' before death |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Kevin |last2=Breuninger |date=August 27, 2019 |website=CNBC |language=en}}</ref> Epstein's brother, Mark, has rejected the possibility of Jeffrey's suicide, claiming, \u201cI could see if he got a life sentence, I could then see him taking himself out, but he had a bail hearing coming up.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/state/florida/article237242984.html |title=Jeffrey Epstein wasn't trafficking women \u2014 and he didn't kill himself, brother says |first1=Julie |last1=Brown |date=November 14, 2019 |website=Miami herald |language=en}}</ref> He also claimed that his \"life may also be in danger,\" if Epstein was indeed murdered.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/lifestyle/jeffrey-epstein-brother-fears-life-danger |title=Jeffrey Epstein's brother fears his life 'may also be in danger' |last1=Pagones |first1=Stephanie |date=December 23, 2019 |website=[[FOX Business]] |access-date=January 1, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> New York City mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] and podcast host [[Joe Rogan]] expressed doubts that Epstein's death was due to suicide.<ref name=\"wired\" /> Former US Attorney and Senate Judiciary Committee counsel [[Brett Tolman]] said that his death was \"more than coincidental\" considering his \"many connections to powerful people\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2019/11/20/ex-us-attorney-calls-epstein-suicide-more-than-coincidental/ |title=Ex-US attorney calls Epstein suicide 'more than coincidental' |first1=Bruce |last1=Golding |date=November 20, 2019}}</ref> [[Syria|Syrian]] President [[Bashar al-Assad]] asserted that \"American billionaire Jeffrey Epstein was killed several weeks ago - they said he had committed suicide in jail. However, he was killed because he knew a lot of vital secrets connected with very important people in the British and American regimes, and possibly in other countries as well.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/syria-assad-jeffrey-epstein-didnt-kill-himself-1471868 |title=Syria's Assad says Jeffrey Epstein did not kill himself |last1=O'Connor |first1=Tom |date=November 14, 2019 |website=Newsweek |access-date=November 15, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{further|Epstein didn't kill himself}}\n{{multiple image\n|total_width=350\n|image1=Epstein Bridge Nov2019 2 (cropped).jpg\n|width1=2419\n|height1=3226\n|image2=Epstein Didn't Kill Himself Sticker.png\n|width2=792\n|height2=880\n|footer= The meme appeared in a variety of forms and places, such as this graffiti on an Ohio interstate overpass or a sticker at a bus stop in [[Nova Scotia]].\n}}\nAs more information surrounding Epstein's death became public in November 2019, his death and the possibility of murder became a popular [[internet meme]], particularly in the form of the phrase \"[[Epstein didn't kill himself]]\". The meme gained prominence as it was interjected at the end of live interviews, such as by a [[United States Navy SEALs|Navy SEAL]] on FOX News, or later a [[University of Alabama]] student on MSNBC.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/nation-world/ct-nw-jeffrey-epstein-conspiracy-theories-20191123-5smcuhoeajdcrikft2fpgy7cxm-story.html |title=\u2018Epstein didn\u2019t kill himself\u2019: The feds are adamant he died by suicide. The internet isn\u2019t buying it. |first1=Michael |last1=Sisak |date=November 23, 2019 |website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/university-alabama-student-jeffrey-epstein-didnt-kill-himself-1471184 |title=Alabama Student Tells MSNBC Reporter 'Jeffrey Epstein Didn't Kill Himself'|first1=Jenni |last1=Fink|date=November 12, 2019 |website=Newsweek}}</ref> The meme often appears as a [[Non sequitur (literary device)|non sequitur]] after a body of text or within an image.<ref>{{cite news |title=Understanding the 'Jeffrey Epstein didn't kill himself' meme |last1=Poisson |first1=Jayme |last2=Merlan |first2=Anna |url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/frontburner/understanding-the-jeffrey-epstein-didn-t-kill-himself-meme-1.5365778 |work=[[CBC News]] |series=Front Burner |access-date=1 December 2019 |date=20 November 2019 |language=en |format=Audio}}</ref> NPR's [[Scott Simon]] likened the [[bait-and-switch]] aspect of the meme to [[Rickrolling]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Epstein's Death Becomes A Meme |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/16/780067957/epsteins-death-becomes-a-meme |access-date=December 27, 2019 |work=[[NPR]]|date=November 16, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nEpstein's death became the subject of several comedians, such as [[77th Golden Globe Awards]] host [[Ricky Gervais]] who remarked that Epstein didn\u2019t commit suicide and [[Saturday Night Live]] host [[Adam Driver]], who played a murdered Epstein in hell.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amatulli |first1=Jenna |title= Ricky Gervais Says Epstein Didn't Kill Himself, Drags Felicity Huffman At Golden Globes |url= https://www.huffpost.com/entry/ricky-gervais-opening-monologue-golden-globes-2020_n_5e0fa2d3c5b6b5a713ba297d?zwi |access-date=January 5, 2020|work=[[Huffington Post]] |date=January 5, 2020|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/01/adam-driver-snl-jeffrey-epstein-kylo-ren</ref> [[HBO]] is creating a limited series covering Epstein's life and death. [[Netflix]], [[Sony|SonyTV]], and [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] also have similar works in progress.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.inquirer.com/entertainment/tv/jeffrey-epstein-hbo-series-adam-mckay-julie-k-brown-20191031.html |title=HBO orders Jeffrey Epstein series based on book by former Daily News reporter |first1=Nick |last1=Vadala |work=Inquirer.com |date=October 31, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/jeffrey-epstein-series-hbo-adam-mckay-1203388518/ |title=Adam McKay Sets Jeffrey Epstein Limited Series at HBO Under New First-Look Deal |first1=Joe |last1=Otterson |first2=Joe |last2=Otterson |work=Variety  |date=October 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/prince-andrew-accuser-virginia-roberts-giuffre-netflix-epstein</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|New York City|Law|Human sexuality}}\n* [[Jeffrey Epstein#Legal proceedings|Jeffrey Epstein \u00a7 Legal proceedings]]\n* [[List of federal political scandals in the United States]]\n* [[List of unsolved deaths]]\n* [[Little Saint James, U.S. Virgin Islands]]\n* [[Space Relations]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*  {{cite web|title=Inside the Jail the Night Jeffrey Epstein Died|date=November 20, 2019|first=Azi |last=Paybarah|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 20, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/20/nyregion/jeffrey-epstein-death.html}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|c=category:Death of Jeffrey Epstein|b=no|n=no|q=no|voy=no|s=no|v=no|species=no}}\n*[https://drive.google.com/file/d/1WuIp6GmgqhsZrQRbFtBrdsSbXJCQsI1o/view Autopsy report]\n*[https://www.justice.gov/usao-sdny/press-release/file/1180481/download Indictment of Jeffrey Epstein]\n*[https://vault.fbi.gov/jeffrey-epstein FBI vault] \n*[https://www.motherjones.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Epstein.Docs_.redacted.pdf Redacted DOJ files]\n{{authority control}}\n{{Jeffrey Epstein Sex Trafficking Scandal}}\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Epstein, Jeffrey, death of}}\n[[Category:2010s in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:2019 controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:2019 in New York City]]\n[[Category:2019 controversies]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:American people who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:August 2019 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories in the United States]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories promoted by Donald Trump]]\n[[Category:Death in New York City]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jeffrey Epstein|Death]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in New York (state) detention]]\n[[Category:Unsolved deaths]]\n[[Category:Death conspiracy theories]]\n", "name_user": "DemonDays64", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing bot mistake (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Death_of_Jeffrey_Epstein"}
{"title_page": "Paul Carey (ice hockey)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Paul Carey\n| image = Paul Carey.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|9|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Weymouth, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lb = 190\n| position = [[Centre (ice hockey)|Center]]\n| shoots = Left\n| league = [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| team = [[Boston Bruins]]\n| prospect_team = [[Providence Bruins]]\n| prospect_league = [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| former_teams = [[Colorado Avalanche]]<br>[[Washington Capitals]]<br>[[New York Rangers]]<br>[[Ottawa Senators]]\n| draft = 135th overall\n| draft_year = 2007\n| draft_team = [[Colorado Avalanche]]\n| career_start = 2012\n}}\n\n'''Paul Charles Carey''' (born September 24, 1988, [[Weymouth, Massachusetts]]) is an [[Americans|American]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Centre (ice hockey)|center]] for the [[Providence Bruins]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) while under contract to the [[Boston Bruins]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL).\n\n==Playing career==\nCarey was drafted by the [[Colorado Avalanche]] in the 5th round, 135th overall, in the [[2007 NHL Entry Draft]]. Carey played two years at Salisbury School in Connecticut before moving on to compete in the [[United States Hockey League]] with the [[Indiana Ice]] in the 2007\u201308 season and was a Rookie of the year finalist, before committing to play for the [[Boston College Eagles men's ice hockey|Boston College Eagles]] of the [[Hockey East]] in his freshman year in the [[2008\u201309 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2008\u201309 season]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ushl.com/news/story.cfm?id=1126 | title = USHL announces finalists for League Awards | publisher = [[United States Hockey League]] | date = April 2, 2008 | accessdate = January 2, 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110805085315/http://www.ushl.com/news/story.cfm?id=1126 | archivedate = August 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter capturing his first national title with the Eagles in his sophomore year, Carey repeated the feat in his senior year in [[2011\u201312 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2012]], scoring the championship winning goal against [[Ferris State University]] and earning selection to the [[Frozen Four]] All-Tournament team.<ref name =\"Signing\">{{cite web| url = http://blogs.denverpost.com/avs/2012/04/11/avalanche-sign-boston-college-paul-carey/10311/ | title = Avalanche sign Boston College forward Paul Carey | publisher = [[Denver Post]] | date = April 11, 2012 | accessdate = April 11, 2012}}</ref> Carey was subsequently signed by the Avalanche to a two-year entry level contract on April 11, 2012. He was immediately assigned on an amateur try-out to begin his professional career and finish the duration of the season with AHL affiliate, the [[Lake Erie Monsters]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://avalanche.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=627325 | title = Avalanche signs Carey | publisher = [[Colorado Avalanche]] | date = April 11, 2012 | accessdate = April 11, 2012}}</ref> He made his professional debut in a 5\u20133 victory over the [[Hamilton Bulldogs (AHL)|Hamilton Bulldogs]] on April 13, 2012.\n\nIn his first full professional season in [[2012\u201313 AHL season|2012\u201313]], Carey was an offensive contributor for the Monsters. After scoring his first professional goal and point against the [[Oklahoma City Barons]], on October 13, 2012, Carey played in 72 games to finish fourth amongst Lake Erie players with 19 goals and 41 points. During the season, Carey accounted for the team's longest individual point scoring streak at 8 games.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://lakeeriemonsters.com/news/news/?article_id=2035 | title = By the numbers: Paul Carey | publisher = [[Lake Erie Monsters]] | date = May 2, 2013 | accessdate = March 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the following [[2013\u201314 NHL season|2013\u201314 season]], despite a dip in his offensive numbers, Carey received his first NHL recall by the injury depleted Avalanche on March 11, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://avalanche.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=709208 | title = 'Avalanche way' In place for times like this | publisher = [[Colorado Avalanche]] | date = March 12, 2013 | accessdate = March 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.denverpost.com/avalanche/ci_25324106/avs-brass-networking-future-giguere-ponders-quitting-time | title = Avs brass networking future | publisher = [[Denver Post]] | date = March 11, 2013 | accessdate = February 12, 2013}}</ref> He made his NHL debut with the Avalanche in a 3\u20132 victory over the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] on March 12.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gametracker/recap/NHL_20140312_CHI@COL/varlamov-notches-100th-nhl-win-avs-edge-blackhawks | title = Varlamov notches 100th NHL win, Avs edge Blackhawks | publisher = [[CBS Sports]] | date = March 12, 2014 | accessdate = March 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCarey was assigned to the Lake Erie Monsters to begin the [[2014\u201315 NHL season|2014\u201315 season]]. Amongst the top offensive producers on the Monsters, Carey was recalled by the Avalanche on multiple occasions and on February 15, 2015, in his 17th career game he recorded his first NHL point, an assist, in a 5\u20132 victory over the [[Arizona Coyotes]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://avalanche.nhl.com/gamecenter/en/recap?id=2014020842 | title = Avalanche builds early lead, stifles Coyotes in win | publisher = [[Colorado Avalanche]] | date = February 15, 2015 | accessdate = February 15, 2015}}</ref> On March 2, 2015, Carey was traded by the Avalanche along with [[Maxime Talbot]] to his hometown team, the [[Boston Bruins]], in exchange for [[Jordan Caron]] and a 6th-round draft pick in [[2016 NHL Entry Draft|2016]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://bruins.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=756148 | title = Bruins announce trade deadline transactions | publisher = [[Boston Bruins]] | date = March 2, 2015 | accessdate = March 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 8, 2015, Carey signed as a free agent to a one-year, two-way contract with the [[Washington Capitals]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=774275 | title = Capitals sign Paul Carey | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] | date = July 8, 2015 | accessdate = July 8, 2015}}</ref> He scored his first NHL goal on February 6, 2016, against [[Cory Schneider]] of the [[New Jersey Devils]]<ref>{{cite web| url = http://espn.go.com/nhl/boxscore?gameId=400815639 | title = Capitals vs Devils boxscore | publisher = [[ESPN]] | date = February 6, 2016 | accessdate = February 6, 2016}}</ref> while playing in his third game for the Capitals. He was called up a day earlier for the second time of the season by the Capitals from the [[American Hockey League]], where he was playing for the [[Hershey Bears]].\n\nAfter two seasons within the Capitals organization, Carey left as a free agent to sign a one-year, two-way contract with the [[New York Rangers]] on July 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/rangers/news/rangers-agree-to-terms-with-free-agent-forward-paul-carey/c-290262902 | title = Rangers agree to terms with free agent forward Paul Carey | publisher = [[New York Rangers]] | date = July 1, 2017 | accessdate = July 1, 2017}}</ref> After enjoying a solid training camp and pre-season with the Rangers, and with [[Jesper Fast]] injured, Carey was named on the opening night roster to begin the [[2017\u201318 NHL season|2017\u201318 season]] for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.newsday.com/sports/hockey/rangers/rangers-return-lias-andersson-to-sweden-1.14293954 | title = Top pick Filip Chytil, 18, makes Rangers opening day roster | publisher = [[Newsday.com]] | date = October 3, 2017 | accessdate = October 3, 2017}}</ref> Carey was initially a healthy scratch before drawing into the lineup in a depth role. In contributing defensively and showing a two-way game, Carey set career markers of 7 goals and 14 points in 60 games for the Rangers in completing his first full season in the NHL.\n\nAs a free agent in the following off-season, Carey left the Rangers to sign a one-year, two-way contract with the [[Ottawa Senators]] on July 1, 2018.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/senators/news/senators-sign-centre-paul-carey-to-a-one-year-two-way-contract/c-299372012 | title = Senators sign centre Paul Carey to one-year, two-way contract | publisher = [[Ottawa Senators]] | date = July 1, 2018 | accessdate = July 1, 2018}}</ref> After participating in the Senators 2018 training camp and pre-season, Carey remained on the opening roster for the [[2018\u201319 NHL season|2018\u201319 season]]. He made debut in helping the Senators claim their first win of the campaign in a 5\u20133 decision over the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] on October 6, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/gamecenter/ott-vs-tor/2018/10/06/2018020018/recap/box-score#game=2018020018,game_state=final,lock_state=final,game_tab=box-score | title = Chabot score twice for Senators in win over Maple Leafs | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = October 6, 2018 | accessdate = October 6, 2018}}</ref> Carey was scoreless in 5 games for Ottawa before he was placed on waivers and sent to AHL affiliate, the [[Belleville Senators]], on October 24.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://twitter.com/Senators/status/1055091540048203776 | title = Sens re-assign Carey to Belleville | publisher = [[Twitter]] | author = Ottawa Senators | date = October 24, 2018 | accessdate = October 24, 2018| author-link = Ottawa Senators }}</ref> After 29 games in Belleville, Carey was traded by Ottawa and acquired for a second time by the Boston Bruins in exchange for [[Cody Goloubef]] on January 11, 2019.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/bruins/news/bruins-acquire-paul-carey-from-ottawa-in-exchange-for-cody-goloubef/c-303792412 | title = Bruins acquire Paul Carey from Ottawa in exchange for Cody Goloubef | publisher = [[Boston Bruins]] | date = January 11, 2019 | accessdate = January 11, 2019}}</ref> He was assigned to continue in the AHL with the Providence Bruins. On March 26, Carey signed a two-year, two-way contract extension with the Bruins.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bruins Sign Paul Carey To 2-Year, 2-Way Contract Extension |url=https://www.nhl.com/bruins/news/bruins-sign-paul-carey-to-2-year-2-way-contract-extension/c-306153538 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=March 27, 2019 |date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Regular season]]\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|-\n| 2007\u201308||[[Indiana Ice]]||[[United States Hockey League|USHL]]||60||34||32||66||32||4||1||2||3||2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2008\u201309 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2008\u201309]]||[[Boston College Eagles men's ice hockey|Boston College]]||[[Hockey East|HE]]||24||5||4||9||8|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2009\u201310 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2009\u201310]]||Boston College||HE||41||9||12||21||29|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2010\u201311 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2010\u201311]]||Boston College||HE||38||13||13||26||18|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2011\u201312 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2011\u201312]]||Boston College||HE||44||18||12||30||30|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2011\u201312 AHL season|2011\u201312]]||[[Lake Erie Monsters]]||[[American Hockey League|AHL]]||2||0||0||0||2|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- \n| [[2012\u201313 AHL season|2012\u201313]]||Lake Erie Monsters||AHL||72||19||22||41||29|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2013\u201314 AHL season|2013\u201314]]||Lake Erie Monsters||AHL||54||8||13||21||42|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- \n| [[2013\u201314 NHL season|2013\u201314]]||[[Colorado Avalanche]]||[[National Hockey League|NHL]]||12||0||0||0||0|| 3 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2014\u201315 AHL season|2014\u201315]]||Lake Erie Monsters||AHL||43||13||14||27||16|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- \n| [[2014\u201315 NHL season|2014\u201315]]||Colorado Avalanche||NHL||10||0||1||1||0|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2014\u201315||[[Providence Bruins]]||AHL||17||2||5||7||10|| 4 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 4\n|-\n| [[2015\u201316 AHL season|2015\u201316]]||[[Hershey Bears]]||AHL||44||13||18||31||18|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2015\u201316 NHL season|2015\u201316]]||[[Washington Capitals]]||NHL||4||1||0||1||0|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2016\u201317 AHL season|2016\u201317]]||Hershey Bears||AHL||55||24||31||55||29|| 4 || 1 || 1 || 2 || 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2016\u201317 NHL season|2016\u201317]]||Washington Capitals||NHL||6||0||0||0||0|| 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|- \n| [[2017\u201318 NHL season|2017\u201318]]||[[New York Rangers]]||NHL||60||7||7||14||20|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2018\u201319 NHL season|2018\u201319]]||[[Ottawa Senators]]||NHL||5||0||0||0||0|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- \n| [[2018\u201319 AHL season|2018\u201319]]||[[Belleville Senators]]||AHL||29||5||22||27||16|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 2018\u201319||Providence Bruins||AHL||30||22||11||33||14|| 4 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 0\n|- \n| 2018\u201319||[[Boston Bruins]]||NHL||2||0||0||0||0|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\"|NHL totals\n! 99 !! 8 !! 8 !! 16 !! 20 !! 4 !! 0 !! 0 !! 0 !! 0\n|}\n\n==Awards and honors==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Award\n! Year\n!\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"|[[United States Hockey League|USHL]]\n|-\n| Second All-Star Team\n| 2008\n| <ref>{{cite web| url = http://bceagles.cstv.com/sports/m-hockey/mtt/carey_paul00.html | title = Player Bio \u2013 Paul Carey | publisher = [[Boston College Eagles]] | date = January 2, 2010 | accessdate = March 29, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| All-Rookie Team \n| 2008\n| <ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.hockeysfuture.com/prospects/paul_carey| title = Paul Carey Biography | publisher = Hockeysfuture.com | date = March 29, 2010 | accessdate = March 29, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"|[[NCAA Division I men's ice hockey|College]]\n|-\n| [[NCAA Men's Ice Hockey Championship|NCAA]] [[List of NCAA Division I Men's Ice Hockey All-Tournament Teams|All-Tournament Team]]\n| [[2012 NCAA Division I Men's Ice Hockey Tournament|2012]]\n| <ref name = \"Signing\"/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Ice hockey stats|nhl=8474008|elite=14386|espn=|euro=|hr=c/careypa01|hockeydb=105380|legendsm=|legends=|legendstype=|tsn=}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carey, Paul}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American men's ice hockey centers]]\n[[Category:Belleville Senators players]]\n[[Category:Boston Bruins players]]\n[[Category:Boston College Eagles men's ice hockey players]]\n[[Category:Colorado Avalanche draft picks]]\n[[Category:Colorado Avalanche players]]\n[[Category:Hershey Bears players]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Indiana Ice players]]\n[[Category:Lake Erie Monsters players]]\n[[Category:New York Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Senators players]]\n[[Category:Providence Bruins players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Weymouth, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Washington Capitals players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Paul Carey\n| image = Paul Carey.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|9|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Weymouth, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lb = 190\n| position = [[Centre (ice hockey)|Center]]\n| shoots = Left\n| league = [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| team = [[Boston Bruins]]\n| prospect_team = [[Providence Bruins]]\n| prospect_league = [[American Hockey League|AHL]]\n| former_teams = [[Colorado Avalanche]]<br>[[Washington Capitals]]<br>[[New York Rangers]]<br>[[Ottawa Senators]]\n| draft = 135th overall\n| draft_year = 2007\n| draft_team = [[Colorado Avalanche]]\n| career_start = 2012\n}}\n\n'''Paul Charles Carey''' (born September 24, 1988, [[Weymouth, Massachusetts]]) is an [[Americans|American]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[Centre (ice hockey)|center]] for the [[Providence Bruins]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) while under contract to the [[Boston Bruins]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL).\n\n==Playing career==\nCarey was drafted by the [[Colorado Avalanche]] in the 5th round, 135th overall, in the [[2007 NHL Entry Draft]]. Carey played two years at Salisbury School in Connecticut before moving on to compete in the [[United States Hockey League]] with the [[Indiana Ice]] in the 2007\u201308 season and was a Rookie of the year finalist, before committing to play for the [[Boston College Eagles men's ice hockey|Boston College Eagles]] of the [[Hockey East]] in his freshman year in the [[2008\u201309 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2008\u201309 season]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ushl.com/news/story.cfm?id=1126 | title = USHL announces finalists for League Awards | publisher = [[United States Hockey League]] | date = April 2, 2008 | accessdate = January 2, 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110805085315/http://www.ushl.com/news/story.cfm?id=1126 | archivedate = August 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter capturing his first national title with the Eagles in his sophomore year, Carey repeated the feat in his senior year in [[2011\u201312 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2012]], scoring the championship winning goal against [[Ferris State University]] and earning selection to the [[Frozen Four]] All-Tournament team.<ref name =\"Signing\">{{cite web| url = http://blogs.denverpost.com/avs/2012/04/11/avalanche-sign-boston-college-paul-carey/10311/ | title = Avalanche sign Boston College forward Paul Carey | publisher = [[Denver Post]] | date = April 11, 2012 | accessdate = April 11, 2012}}</ref> Carey was subsequently signed by the Avalanche to a two-year entry level contract on April 11, 2012. He was immediately assigned on an amateur try-out to begin his professional career and finish the duration of the season with AHL affiliate, the [[Lake Erie Monsters]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://avalanche.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=627325 | title = Avalanche signs Carey | publisher = [[Colorado Avalanche]] | date = April 11, 2012 | accessdate = April 11, 2012}}</ref> He made his professional debut in a 5\u20133 victory over the [[Hamilton Bulldogs (AHL)|Hamilton Bulldogs]] on April 13, 2012.\n\nIn his first full professional season in [[2012\u201313 AHL season|2012\u201313]], Carey was an offensive contributor for the Monsters. After scoring his first professional goal and point against the [[Oklahoma City Barons]], on October 13, 2012, Carey played in 72 games to finish fourth amongst Lake Erie players with 19 goals and 41 points. During the season, Carey accounted for the teams longest individual point scoring streak at 8 games.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://lakeeriemonsters.com/news/news/?article_id=2035 | title = By the numbers: Paul Carey | publisher = [[Lake Erie Monsters]] | date = May 2, 2013 | accessdate = March 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the following [[2013\u201314 NHL season|2013\u201314 season]], despite a dip in his offensive numbers, Carey received his first NHL recall by the injury depleted Avalanche on March 11, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://avalanche.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=709208 | title = 'Avalanche way' In place for times like this | publisher = [[Colorado Avalanche]] | date = March 12, 2013 | accessdate = March 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.denverpost.com/avalanche/ci_25324106/avs-brass-networking-future-giguere-ponders-quitting-time | title = Avs brass networking future | publisher = [[Denver Post]] | date = March 11, 2013 | accessdate = February 12, 2013}}</ref> He made his NHL debut with the Avalanche in a 3\u20132 victory over the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] on March 12.<ref>{{Cite web| url = http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gametracker/recap/NHL_20140312_CHI@COL/varlamov-notches-100th-nhl-win-avs-edge-blackhawks | title = Varlamov notches 100th NHL win, Avs edge Blackhawks | publisher = [[CBS Sports]] | date = March 12, 2014 | accessdate = March 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCarey was assigned to the Lake Erie Monsters to begin the [[2014\u201315 NHL season|2014\u201315 season]]. Amongst the top offensive producers on the Monsters, Carey was recalled by the Avalanche on multiple occasions and on February 15, 2015, in his 17th career game he recorded his first NHL point, an assist, in a 5\u20132 victory over the [[Arizona Coyotes]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://avalanche.nhl.com/gamecenter/en/recap?id=2014020842 | title = Avalanche builds early lead, stifles Coyotes in win | publisher = [[Colorado Avalanche]] | date = February 15, 2015 | accessdate = February 15, 2015}}</ref> On March 2, 2015, Carey was traded by the Avalanche along with [[Maxime Talbot]] to his hometown team, the [[Boston Bruins]], in exchange for [[Jordan Caron]] and a 6th-round draft pick in [[2016 NHL Entry Draft|2016]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://bruins.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=756148 | title = Bruins announce trade deadline transactions | publisher = [[Boston Bruins]] | date = March 2, 2015 | accessdate = March 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn July 8, 2015, Carey signed as a free agent to a one-year, two-way contract with the [[Washington Capitals]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://capitals.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=774275 | title = Capitals sign Paul Carey | publisher = [[Washington Capitals]] | date = July 8, 2015 | accessdate = July 8, 2015}}</ref> He scored his first NHL goal on February 6, 2016, against [[Cory Schneider]] of the [[New Jersey Devils]]<ref>{{cite web| url = http://espn.go.com/nhl/boxscore?gameId=400815639 | title = Capitals vs Devils boxscore | publisher = [[ESPN]] | date = February 6, 2016 | accessdate = February 6, 2016}}</ref> while playing in his third game for the Capitals. He was called up a day earlier for the second time of the season by the Capitals from the [[American Hockey League]], where he was playing for the [[Hershey Bears]].\n\nAfter two seasons within the Capitals organization, Carey left as a free agent to sign a one-year, two-way contract with the [[New York Rangers]] on July 1, 2017.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/rangers/news/rangers-agree-to-terms-with-free-agent-forward-paul-carey/c-290262902 | title = Rangers agree to terms with free agent forward Paul Carey | publisher = [[New York Rangers]] | date = July 1, 2017 | accessdate = July 1, 2017}}</ref> After enjoying a solid training camp and pre-season with the Rangers, and with [[Jesper Fast]] injured, Carey was named on the opening night roster to begin the [[2017\u201318 NHL season|2017\u201318 season]] for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.newsday.com/sports/hockey/rangers/rangers-return-lias-andersson-to-sweden-1.14293954 | title = Top pick Filip Chytil, 18, makes Rangers opening day roster | publisher = [[Newsday.com]] | date = October 3, 2017 | accessdate = October 3, 2017}}</ref> Carey was initially a healthy scratch before drawing into the lineup in a depth role. In contributing defensively and showing a two-way game, Carey set career markers of 7 goals and 14 points in 60 games for the Rangers in completing his first full season in the NHL.\n\nAs a free agent in the following off-season, Carey left the Rangers to sign a one-year, two-way contract with the [[Ottawa Senators]] on July 1, 2018.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/senators/news/senators-sign-centre-paul-carey-to-a-one-year-two-way-contract/c-299372012 | title = Senators sign centre Paul Carey to one-year, two-way contract | publisher = [[Ottawa Senators]] | date = July 1, 2018 | accessdate = July 1, 2018}}</ref> After participating in the Senators 2018 training camp and pre-season, Carey remained on the opening roster for the [[2018\u201319 NHL season|2018\u201319 season]]. He made debut in helping the Senators claim their first win of the campaign in a 5\u20133 decision over the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] on October 6, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/gamecenter/ott-vs-tor/2018/10/06/2018020018/recap/box-score#game=2018020018,game_state=final,lock_state=final,game_tab=box-score | title = Chabot score twice for Senators in win over Maple Leafs | publisher = [[National Hockey League]] | date = October 6, 2018 | accessdate = October 6, 2018}}</ref> Carey was scoreless in 5 games for Ottawa before he was placed on waivers and sent to AHL affiliate, the [[Belleville Senators]], on October 24.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://twitter.com/Senators/status/1055091540048203776 | title = Sens re-assign Carey to Belleville | publisher = [[Twitter]] | author = Ottawa Senators | date = October 24, 2018 | accessdate = October 24, 2018| author-link = Ottawa Senators }}</ref> After 29 games in Belleville, Carey was traded by Ottawa and acquired for a second time by the Boston Bruins in exchange for [[Cody Goloubef]] on January 11, 2019.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.nhl.com/bruins/news/bruins-acquire-paul-carey-from-ottawa-in-exchange-for-cody-goloubef/c-303792412 | title = Bruins acquire Paul Carey from Ottawa in exchange for Cody Goloubef | publisher = [[Boston Bruins]] | date = January 11, 2019 | accessdate = January 11, 2019}}</ref> He was assigned to continue in the AHL with the Providence Bruins. On March 26, Carey signed a two-year, two-way contract extension with the Bruins.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bruins Sign Paul Carey To 2-Year, 2-Way Contract Extension |url=https://www.nhl.com/bruins/news/bruins-sign-paul-carey-to-2-year-2-way-contract-extension/c-306153538 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=March 27, 2019 |date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Regular season]]\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]]\n! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]]\n! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]]\n! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP\n! G\n! A\n! Pts\n! PIM\n|-\n| 2007\u201308||[[Indiana Ice]]||[[United States Hockey League|USHL]]||60||34||32||66||32||4||1||2||3||2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2008\u201309 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2008\u201309]]||[[Boston College Eagles men's ice hockey|Boston College]]||[[Hockey East|HE]]||24||5||4||9||8|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2009\u201310 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2009\u201310]]||Boston College||HE||41||9||12||21||29|| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2010\u201311 NCAA Division I men's ice hockey season|2010\u201311]]||Boston College||HE||38||13||13||26||18|| \u2014 || \u2014 || 