ado Avalanche players]]\n[[Category:Hershey Bears players]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Indiana Ice players]]\n[[Category:Lake Erie Monsters players]]\n[[Category:New York Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Senators players]]\n[[Category:Providence Bruins players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Weymouth, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Washington Capitals players]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlaying career:Typo fixing, replaced: teams longest \u2192 team's longest", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Carey_(ice_hockey)"}
{"title_page": "7th Heaven (1927 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1927 film by Frank Borzage}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{No plot|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = 7th Heaven\n| image          = 7th Heaven (1927 poster).jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Frank Borzage]]\n| producer       = [[William Fox (producer)|William Fox]]\n| screenplay     = [[Benjamin Glazer]]\n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Harry H. Caldwell]] (titles)|[[Katharine Hilliker]] (titles)|[[Bernard Vorhaus]] (uncredited)}}\n| based_on       = {{based on|''[[Seventh Heaven (play)|Seventh Heaven]]''|Austin Strong}}\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Janet Gaynor]]|[[Charles Farrell]]|[[Ben Bard]]}}\n| cinematography = {{ubl|[[Ernest Palmer (American cinematographer)|Ernest Palmer]]|[[Joseph Valentine|Joseph A. Valentine]]}}\n| editing        = Barney Wolf\n| distributor    = [[Fox Film Corporation]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1927|05|06|Los Angeles|1927|05|25|New York City|1927|09|10|New York City (re-release)}}\n| runtime        = 110 min\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n| country        = United States\n| budget         = $1.3 million<ref name=\"eyman114\">{{harv|Eyman|1997|p=114}}</ref>\n| gross          = $2.5 million<ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/variety106-1932-06#page/n120/mode/1up|title=Biggest Money Pictures|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 21, 1932|page=1}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''7th Heaven''''' (also known as '''''Seventh Heaven''''') is a 1927 American [[silent film|silent]] [[romantic drama]] directed by [[Frank Borzage]], and starring [[Janet Gaynor]] and [[Charles Farrell]]. The film is based upon the 1922 play ''[[Seventh Heaven (play)|Seventh Heaven]]'', by Austin Strong and was adapted for the screen by [[Benjamin Glazer]].<ref>{{harv|Goble|1999|p=447}}</ref> ''7th Heaven'' was initially released as a standard silent film in May 1927. On September 10, 1927, [[Fox Film Corporation]] re-released the film with a synchronized [[Movietone sound system|Movietone]] soundtrack with a musical score and sound effects.\n\nUpon its release, ''7th Heaven'' was a critical and commercial success and helped to establish Fox Film Corporation as a major studio. It was one of the first of three films to be nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] (then called \"Outstanding Picture\") at the [[1st Academy Awards]] held on May 16, 1929. Janet Gaynor won the first Academy Award for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for her performance in the film (she also won for her performances in 1927's ''[[Sunrise: A Song of Two Humans]]'' and 1928's ''[[Street Angel (1928 film)|Street Angel]]'').<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/09/15/obituaries/janet-gaynor-is-dead-at-77-first-best-actress-winner.html|title=Janet Gaynor Is Dead At 77; First 'Best Actress' Winner|last=Bird|first=David|date=September 15, 1984|newspaper=nytimes.com|accessdate=March 30, 2015}}</ref> Director Frank Borzage also won the first [[Academy Award for Best Director]] while screenwriter Benjamin Glazer won the first [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Academy Award for Best Writing (Adapted Screenplay)]].\n\nIn 1995, ''7th Heaven'' was selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]] as being \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=American Society of Cinematographers|date=February 1996|title=Films Chosen for Library of Congress National Film Registry|journal=[[American Cinematographer]]|publisher=ASC Holding Corp.|volume=77|issue=22|page=114|issn=0002-7928}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Janet Gaynor]] as Diane\n* [[Charles Farrell]] as Chico\n* [[Ben Bard]] as Col. Brissac\n* [[Albert Gran]] as Boul\n* [[David Butler (director)|David Butler]] as Gobin\n* [[Marie Mosquini]] as Madame Gobin\n* [[Gladys Brockwell]] as Nana\n* [[Emile Chautard]] as Father Chevillon\n* Jessie Haslett as Aunt Valentine\n* [[Brandon Hurst]] as Uncle George\n* [[George E. Stone]] as Sewer Rat\n* [[Lillian West]] as Arlette\n}}\n\n==Production notes==\n[[File:7th Heaven lobby card.jpg|thumb|Lobby card with Janet Gaynor and Charles Farrell]]\nThe Broadway play upon which the film is based starred George Gaul and [[Helen Menken]] and ran at the Booth Theatre for 704 performances.<ref>{{IBDB title|id=9142|title=Seventh Heaven}}</ref> When the play was adapted for the screen, Janet Gaynor and Charles Farrell were cast in the lead roles. The pairing proved to be so popular, the two went on to star in 11 more films together and were dubbed \"America's Favorite Lovebirds\".<ref>{{harv|Hischak|2008|p=238}}</ref><ref>{{harv|Bradley|2004|p=125}}</ref>\n\n''7th Heaven'' features the song \"[[Diane (1927 song)|Diane]]\" by [[Ern\u00f6 Rap\u00e9e]] and [[Lew Pollack]], who wrote the song specifically for the film. The song is included on the re-released version of the film.<ref name=\"Melnick 2014 293\">{{harv|Melnick|2014|p=293}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''7th Heaven'' initially premiered at the [[Carthay Circle Theatre]] in Los Angeles replacing another Fox melodrama ''[[What Price Glory? (1926 film)|What Price Glory?]]'', which had been playing since November 1926.<ref name=\"eyman114\" /> A second opening was held at the [[Sam H. Harris (producer)|Sam H. Harris Theatre]] in New York City on May 25.<ref name=\"holston\">{{harv|Holston|2012|p=56}}</ref> Both openings earned a total of $14,500.<ref>{{harv|Crafton|1999|p=528}}</ref> A series of Movietone shorts featuring [[Ben Bernie|Ben Bernie and his Orchestra]], [[Gertrude Lawrence]], [[Raquel Meller]], and [[Charles \"Chic\" Sale]] preceded the film.<ref name=\"eyman113\">{{harv|Eyman|1997|p=113}}</ref>\n\nUpon its release, ''7th Heaven'' was a critical and commercial success.<ref>{{harv|Soloman|2011|p=114}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' critic stated that the film \"grips your interest from the very beginning and even though the end is melodramatic you are glad that the sympathetic but self-satisfied Chico is brought back to his heart-broken Diane.\" The critic also praised Borzage's direction, stating that the director \"has given it all that he could put through the medium of the camera.\"<ref name=\"holston\" /> The film went on to play for 19 weeks in New York City and for 22 weeks in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"eyman113\" />\n\nDue to the film's success and the success of other Fox films featuring sound elements (''Sunrise'', ''What Price Glory?''), the studio re-released ''7th Heaven'' with a synchronized Movietone soundtrack, including a musical score arranged by Ern\u00f6 Rap\u00e9e and sound effects. The re-release version premiered at New York City's [[Roxy Theatre (New York City)|Roxy Theatre]] on September 10, 1927.<ref name=\"Melnick 2014 293\" />\n\nBy 1932, ''7th Heaven'' had become the 13th-highest-grossing American silent, earning more than $2.5 million at the box office.<ref name=\"Variety\" />\n\n==Awards and honors==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n|-\n| 1927\n| [[Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| [[Janet Gaynor]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| Academy Awards\n| [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]]\n| [[Harry Oliver]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| Academy Awards\n| [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| [[Frank Borzage]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| Academy Awards\n| [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Writing (Adapted Screenplay)]]\n| [[Benjamin Glazer]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| Academy Awards\n| [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Outstanding Picture]]\n| [[Fox Film]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| [[Kinema Junpo Awards]]\n| [[Kinema Junpo#Annual Award Categories|Best Foreign Film]]\n| [[Frank Borzage]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| [[Photoplay#Photoplay Medal of Honor|Photoplay Awards]]\n| Medal of Honor\n| [[William Fox (producer)|William Fox]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==Remakes and adaptations==\nA comparatively unknown [[Seventh Heaven (1937 film)|1937 remake]] of the film was produced as a sound feature starring [[Simone Simon]], [[James Stewart]], [[Jean Hersholt]], and [[Gregory Ratoff]], with [[Henry King (director)|Henry King]] directing. Unlike the 1927 version, the sound remake was not as financially successful.<ref>{{harv|Dyer MacCann|1996|p=106}}</ref>\n\nOn October 17, 1938, a radio adaptation of ''7th Heaven'' aired on the ''[[Lux Radio Theatre]]'', starring [[Don Ameche]] as Chico and [[Jean Arthur]] as Diane. A television adaptation was aired on October 26, 1953, on the [[anthology series]] ''[[Broadway Television Theatre]]''. The episode stars [[Hurd Hatfield]] and [[Geraldine Brooks (actress)|Geraldine Brooks]] and was directed by Robert St. Aubrey.<ref>{{harv|Dumont|2006|p=396}}</ref> On May 26, 1955, a stage musical version of the film opened at the [[August Wilson Theatre|ANTA Theatre]] starring [[Gloria DeHaven]] and [[Ricardo Montalb\u00e1n]]. It closed on July 2, 1955, after 44 performances.<ref>{{harv|Dietz|2014|p=121}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nOn December 9, 2008, ''7th Heaven'' was included in the ''Murnau, Borzage and Fox'' DVD box set released by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.silentera.com/video/seventhHeavenHV.html|title=20th Century Fox Home Entertainment 2008 DVD edition|publisher=silentera.com|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nChinese writer-director [[Yuan Muzhi]]'s 1937 film ''[[Street Angel (1937 film)|Street Angel]]'' has been cited as being influenced by elements of ''7th Heaven'' and another Frank Borzage film ''[[Street Angel (1928 film)|Street Angel]]'' (1928).<ref>{{harv|Clark|2013|p=741}}</ref>\n\nThe theatrical poster for ''7th Heaven'' is displayed on the wall of the student Watanabe's lodgings in the oldest surviving film by the Japanese director [[Yasujir\u014d Ozu]], ''[[Days of Youth|Days of Youth: A Student Romance]]'' (''Gakusei Romansu: Wakaki Hi'', 1929).<ref>{{harv|Morefield|Olson|2015|pp=4\u20135}}</ref>\n\nFilmmaker [[Damien Chazelle]] has said the ending of his 2016 [[Musical film|musical]] ''[[La La Land (film)|La La Land]]'' was inspired by the ending of ''7th Heaven''.<ref name=\"bird\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/01/movie-that-inspired-la-la-lands-ending.html|title=Damien Chazelle Reveals the Movie That Influenced La La Land\u2019s Ending|last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|date=January 5, 2017|publisher=vulture.com|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Bradley|first=Edwin M. |title=The First Hollywood Musicals: A Critical Filmography of 171 Features, 1927 through 1932|year=2004|publisher=McFarland | location = Jefferson, NC | isbn=978-0-7864-2029-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Clark|editor-first=Peter|title=The Oxford Handbook of Cities in World History|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press | location = Oxford | isbn=978-0-19-958953-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Crafton|first=Donald |title=The Talkies: American Cinema's Transition to Sound, 1926\u20131931|year=1999|publisher=University of California Press | location = New York | isbn=978-0-520-22128-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dietz|first=Dan|title=The Complete Book of 1950s Broadway Musicals|year=2014|publisher=Rowman & Littlefiel | location = Lanham, MD | isbn=978-1-4422-3505-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dumont|first=Herv\u00e9 |title=Frank Borzage: The Life and Films of a Hollywood Romantic|year=2006|publisher=McFarland | location = Jefferson, NC | isbn=978-0-7864-2187-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Dyer MacCann|editor-first=Richard|title=Films of the 1920s|year=1996|publisher=Scarecrow Press | location = Lanham, MD | isbn=978-0-8108-3256-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Eyman|first=Scott|title=The Speed of Sound: Hollywood and the Talkie Revolution 1926\u20131930|url=https://archive.org/details/speedofsoundholl00eyma|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=Simon and Schuster | location = New York | isbn=978-1-4391-0428-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Goble | first = Alan | title = The Complete Index to Literary Sources in Film | publisher = Walter de Gruyter | year = 1999 | location = Berlin | isbn = 978-3-11-095194-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hischak|first=Thomas S. |title=The Oxford Companion to the American Musical: Theatre, Film, and Television|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press | location = Oxford | isbn=978-0-19-533533-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Holston|first=Kim R. |title=Movie Roadshows: A History and Filmography of Reserved-Seat Limited Showings, 1911\u20131973|year=2012|publisher=McFarland | location = Jefferson, NC | isbn=978-0-7864-9261-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Melnick|first=Ross|title=American Showman: Samuel \"Roxy\" Rothafel and the Birth of the Entertainment Industry, 1908\u20131935|year=2014|publisher=Columbia University Press | location = New York | isbn=978-0-231-15905-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last1=Morefield|editor-first1=Kenneth R. |editor-last2=Olson|editor-first2=Nicholas S. |title=Faith and Spirituality in Masters of World Cinema, Volume III|year=2015|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing | location = Newcastle upon Tyne | isbn=978-1-4438-7498-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Soloman|first=Aubrey|title=The Fox Film Corporation, 1915\u20131935: A History and Filmography|year=2011|publisher=McFarland | location = Jefferson, NC | isbn=978-0-7864-8610-6|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|7th Heaven (1927 film)}}\n*7th Heaven essay by Aubrey Solomon on National Film Registry site [https://www.loc.gov/static/programs/national-film-preservation-board/documents/7th_heaven.pdf]\n*{{IMDb title|0018379|7th Heaven}}\n*{{allmovie|109589|Synopsis}}\n*[http://www.virtual-history.com/movie/film/5056/seventh-heaven ''7th Heaven''] at Virtual History\n*[http://www.lovingtheclassics.com/pdmovies/7th-heaven-1927.html dvd of Seventh Heaven]\n\n{{Frank Borzage}}\n\n[[Category:1927 films]]\n[[Category:1920s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Fox Film films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Frank Borzage]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by William Fox]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1910s]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Directing Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Adapted Screenplay Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Benjamin Glazer]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Bernard Vorhaus]]\n[[Category:Transitional sound films]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n[[Category:Films set on the French home front during World War I]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1927 film by Frank Borzage}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{No plot|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = 7th Heaven\n| image          = 7th Heaven (1927 poster).jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Frank Borzage]]\n| producer       = [[William Fox (producer)|William Fox]]\n| screenplay     = [[Benjamin Glazer]]\n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Harry H. Caldwell]] (titles)|[[Katharine Hilliker]] (titles)|[[Bernard Vorhaus]] (uncredited)}}\n| based_on       = {{based on|''[[Seventh Heaven (play)|Seventh Heaven]]''|Austin Strong}}\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Janet Gaynor]]|[[Charles Farrell]]|[[Ben Bard]]}}\n| cinematography = {{ubl|[[Ernest Palmer (American cinematographer)|Ernest Palmer]]|[[Joseph Valentine|Joseph A. Valentine]]}}\n| editing        = Barney Wolf\n| distributor    = [[Fox Film Corporation]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1927|05|06|Los Angeles|1927|05|25|New York City|1927|09|10|New York City (re-release)}}\n| runtime        = 110 min\n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]] (English [[intertitle]]s)\n| country        = United States\n| budget         = $1.3 million<ref name=\"eyman114\">{{harv|Eyman|1997|p=114}}</ref>\n| gross          = $2.5 million<ref name=\"Variety\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/variety106-1932-06#page/n120/mode/1up|title=Biggest Money Pictures|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 21, 1932|page=1}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''7th Heaven''''' (also known as '''''Seventh Heaven''''') is a 1927 American [[silent film|silent]] [[romantic drama]] directed by [[Frank Borzage]], and starring [[Janet Gaynor]] and [[Charles Farrell]]. The film is based upon the 1922 play ''[[Seventh Heaven (play)|Seventh Heaven]]'', by Austin Strong and was adapted for the screen by [[Benjamin Glazer]].<ref>{{harv|Goble|1999|p=447}}</ref> ''7th Heaven'' was initially released as a standard silent film in May 1927. On September 10, 1927, [[Fox Film Corporation]] re-released the film with a synchronized [[Movietone sound system|Movietone]] soundtrack with a musical score and sound effects.\n\nUpon its release, ''7th Heaven'' was a critical and commercial success and helped to establish Fox Film Corporation as a major studio. It was one of the first of three films to be nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] (then called \"Outstanding Picture\") at the [[1st Academy Awards]] held on May 16, 1929. Janet Gaynor won the first Academy Award for [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]] for her performance in the film (she also won for her performances in 1927's ''[[Sunrise: A Song of Two Humans]]'' and 1928's ''[[Street Angel (1928 film)|Street Angel]]'').<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/09/15/obituaries/janet-gaynor-is-dead-at-77-first-best-actress-winner.html|title=Janet Gaynor Is Dead At 77; First 'Best Actress' Winner|last=Bird|first=David|date=September 15, 1984|newspaper=nytimes.com|accessdate=March 30, 2015}}</ref> Director Frank Borzage also won the first [[Academy Award for Best Director]] while screenwriter Benjamin Glazer won the first [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Academy Award for Best Writing (Adapted Screenplay)]].\n\nIn 1995, ''7th Heaven'' was selected for preservation in the United States [[National Film Registry]] by the [[Library of Congress]] as being \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=American Society of Cinematographers|date=February 1996|title=Films Chosen for Library of Congress National Film Registry|journal=[[American Cinematographer]]|publisher=ASC Holding Corp.|volume=77|issue=22|page=114|issn=0002-7928}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n{{cast listing|\n* [[Janet Gaynor]] as Diane\n* [[Charles Farrell]] as Chico\n* [[Ben Bard]] as Col. Brissac\n* [[Albert Gran]] as Boul\n* [[David Butler (director)|David Butler]] as Gobin\n* [[Marie Mosquini]] as Madame Gobin\n* [[Gladys Brockwell]] as Nana\n* [[Emile Chautard]] as Father Chevillon\n* Jessie Haslett as Aunt Valentine\n* [[Brandon Hurst]] as Uncle George\n* [[George E. Stone]] as Sewer Rat\n* [[Lillian West]] as Arlette\n}}\n\n==Production notes==\n[[File:7th Heaven lobby card.jpg|thumb|Lobby card with Janet Gaynor and Charles Farrell]]\nThe Broadway play upon which the film is based starred George Gaul and [[Helen Menken]] and ran at the Booth Theatre for 704 performances.<ref>{{IBDB title|id=9142|title=Seventh Heaven}}</ref> When the play was adapted for the screen, Janet Gaynor and Charles Farrell were cast in the lead roles. The pairing proved to be so popular, the two went on to star in 11 more films together and were dubbed \"America's Favorite Lovebirds\".<ref>{{harv|Hischak|2008|p=238}}</ref><ref>{{harv|Bradley|2004|p=125}}</ref>\n\n''7th Heaven'' features the song \"[[Diane (1927 song)|Diane]]\" by [[Ern\u00f6 Rap\u00e9e]] and [[Lew Pollack]], who wrote the song specifically for the film. The song is included on the re-released version of the film.<ref name=\"Melnick 2014 293\">{{harv|Melnick|2014|p=293}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''7th Heaven'' initially premiered at the [[Carthay Circle Theatre]] in Los Angeles replacing another Fox melodrama ''[[What Price Glory? (1926 film)|What Price Glory?]]'', which had been playing since November 1926.<ref name=\"eyman114\" /> A second opening was held at the [[Sam H. Harris (producer)|Sam H. Harris Theatre]] in New York City on May 25.<ref name=\"holston\">{{harv|Holston|2012|p=56}}</ref> Both openings earned a total of $14,500.<ref>{{harv|Crafton|1999|p=528}}</ref> A series of Movietone shorts featuring [[Ben Bernie|Ben Bernie and his Orchestra]], [[Gertrude Lawrence]], [[Raquel Meller]], and [[Charles \"Chic\" Sale]] preceded the film.<ref name=\"eyman113\">{{harv|Eyman|1997|p=113}}</ref>\n\nUpon its release, ''7th Heaven'' was a critical and commercial success.<ref>{{harv|Soloman|2011|p=114}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' critic stated that the film \"grips your interest from the very beginning and even though the end is melodramatic you are glad that the sympathetic but self-satisfied Chico is brought back to his heart-broken Diane.\" The critic also praised Borzage's direction, stating that the director \"has given it all that he could put through the medium of the camera.\"<ref name=\"holston\" /> The film went on to play for 19 weeks in New York City and for 22 weeks in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"eyman113\" />\n\nDue to the film's success and the success of other Fox films featuring sound elements (''Sunrise'', ''What Price Glory?''), the studio re-released ''7th Heaven'' with a synchronized Movietone soundtrack, including a musical score arranged by Ern\u00f6 Rap\u00e9e and sound effects. The re-release version premiered at New York City's [[Roxy Theatre (New York City)|Roxy Theatre]] on September 10, 1927.<ref name=\"Melnick 2014 293\" />\n\nBy 1932, ''7th Heaven'' had become the 13th-highest-grossing American silent, earning more than $2.5 million at the box office.<ref name=\"Variety\" />\n\n==Awards and honors==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n|-\n| 1927\n| [[Academy Awards]]\n| [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]\n| [[Janet Gaynor]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| Academy Awards\n| [[Academy Award for Best Production Design|Best Art Direction]]\n| [[Harry Oliver]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| Academy Awards\n| [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]]\n| [[Frank Borzage]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| Academy Awards\n| [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Writing (Adapted Screenplay)]]\n| [[Benjamin Glazer]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| Academy Awards\n| [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Outstanding Picture]]\n| [[Fox Film]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1928\n| [[Kinema Junpo Awards]]\n| [[Kinema Junpo#Annual Award Categories|Best Foreign Film]]\n| [[Frank Borzage]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 1927\n| [[Photoplay#Photoplay Medal of Honor|Photoplay Awards]]\n| Medal of Honor\n| [[William Fox (producer)|William Fox]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n==Remakes and adaptations==\nA comparatively unknown [[Seventh Heaven (1937 film)|1937 remake]] of the film was produced as a sound feature starring [[Simone Simon]], [[James Stewart]], [[Jean Hersholt]], and [[Gregory Ratoff]], with [[Henry King (director)|Henry King]] directing. Unlike the 1927 version, the sound remake was not as financially successful.<ref>{{harv|Dyer MacCann|1996|p=106}}</ref>\n\nOn October 17, 1938, a radio adaptation of ''7th Heaven'' aired on the ''[[Lux Radio Theatre]]'', starring [[Don Ameche]] as Chico and [[Jean Arthur]] as Diane. A television adaptation was aired on October 26, 1953, on the [[anthology series]] ''[[Broadway Television Theatre]]''. The episode stars [[Hurd Hatfield]] and [[Geraldine Brooks (actress)|Geraldine Brooks]] and was directed by Robert St. Aubrey.<ref>{{harv|Dumont|2006|p=396}}</ref> On May 26, 1955, a stage musical version of the film opened at the [[August Wilson Theatre|ANTA Theatre]] starring [[Gloria DeHaven]] and [[Ricardo Montalb\u00e1n]]. It closed on July 2, 1955, after 44 performances.<ref>{{harv|Dietz|2014|p=121}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nOn December 9, 2008, ''7th Heaven'' was included in the ''Murnau, Borzage and Fox'' DVD box set released by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.silentera.com/video/seventhHeavenHV.html|title=20th Century Fox Home Entertainment 2008 DVD edition|publisher=silentera.com|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nChinese writer-director [[Yuan Muzhi]]'s 1937 film ''[[Street Angel (1937 film)|Street Angel]]'' has been cited as being influenced by elements of ''7th Heaven'' and another Frank Borzage film ''[[Street Angel (1928 film)|Street Angel]]'' (1928).<ref>{{harv|Clark|2013|p=741}}</ref>\n\nThe theatrical poster for ''7th Heaven'' is displayed on the wall of the student Watanabe's lodgings in the oldest surviving film by the Japanese director [[Yasujir\u014d Ozu]], ''[[Days of Youth|Days of Youth: A Student Romance]]'' (''Gakusei Romansu: Wakaki Hi'', 1929).<ref>{{harv|Morefield|Olson|2015|pp=4\u20135}}</ref>\n\nFilmmaker [[Damien Chazelle]] has said the ending of his 2016 [[Musical film|musical]] ''[[La La Land (film)|La La Land]]'' was inspired by the ending of ''7th Heaven''.<ref name=\"bird\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/01/movie-that-inspired-la-la-lands-ending.html|title=Damien Chazelle Reveals the Movie That Influenced La La Land\u2019s Ending|last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|date=January 5, 2017|publisher=vulture.com|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|last=Bradley|first=Edwin M. |title=The First Hollywood Musicals: A Critical Filmography of 171 Features, 1927 through 1932|year=2004|publisher=McFarland | location = Jefferson, NC | isbn=978-0-7864-2029-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Clark|editor-first=Peter|title=The Oxford Handbook of Cities in World History|year=2013|publisher=Oxford University Press | location = Oxford | isbn=978-0-19-958953-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Crafton|first=Donald |title=The Talkies: American Cinema's Transition to Sound, 1926\u20131931|year=1999|publisher=University of California Press | location = New York | isbn=978-0-520-22128-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dietz|first=Dan|title=The Complete Book of 1950s Broadway Musicals|year=2014|publisher=Rowman & Littlefiel | location = Lanham, MD | isbn=978-1-4422-3505-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Dumont|first=Herv\u00e9 |title=Frank Borzage: The Life and Films of a Hollywood Romantic|year=2006|publisher=McFarland | location = Jefferson, NC | isbn=978-0-7864-2187-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Dyer MacCann|editor-first=Richard|title=Films of the 1920s|year=1996|publisher=Scarecrow Press | location = Lanham, MD | isbn=978-0-8108-3256-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Eyman|first=Scott|title=The Speed of Sound: Hollywood and the Talkie Revolution 1926\u20131930|url=https://archive.org/details/speedofsoundholl00eyma|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=Simon and Schuster | location = New York | isbn=978-1-4391-0428-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Goble | first = Alan | title = The Complete Index to Literary Sources in Film | publisher = Walter de Gruyter | year = 1999 | location = Berlin | isbn = 978-3-11-095194-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hischak|first=Thomas S. |title=The Oxford Companion to the American Musical: Theatre, Film, and Television|year=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press | location = Oxford | isbn=978-0-19-533533-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Holston|first=Kim R. |title=Movie Roadshows: A History and Filmography of Reserved-Seat Limited Showings, 1911\u20131973|year=2012|publisher=McFarland | location = Jefferson, NC | isbn=978-0-7864-9261-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Melnick|first=Ross|title=American Showman: Samuel \"Roxy\" Rothafel and the Birth of the Entertainment Industry, 1908\u20131935|year=2014|publisher=Columbia University Press | location = New York | isbn=978-0-231-15905-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last1=Morefield|editor-first1=Kenneth R. |editor-last2=Olson|editor-first2=Nicholas S. |title=Faith and Spirituality in Masters of World Cinema, Volume III|year=2015|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing | location = Newcastle upon Tyne | isbn=978-1-4438-7498-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Soloman|first=Aubrey|title=The Fox Film Corporation, 1915\u20131935: A History and Filmography|year=2011|publisher=McFarland | location = Jefferson, NC | isbn=978-0-7864-8610-6|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|7th Heaven (1927 film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0018379|7th Heaven}}\n*{{allmovie|109589|Synopsis}}\n*[http://www.virtual-history.com/movie/film/5056/seventh-heaven ''7th Heaven''] at Virtual History\n*[http://www.lovingtheclassics.com/pdmovies/7th-heaven-1927.html dvd of Seventh Heaven]\n\n{{Frank Borzage}}\n\n[[Category:1927 films]]\n[[Category:1920s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Fox Film films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Frank Borzage]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Actress Academy Award-winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by William Fox]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1910s]]\n[[Category:Films whose director won the Best Directing Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films whose writer won the Best Adapted Screenplay Academy Award]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Benjamin Glazer]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Bernard Vorhaus]]\n[[Category:Transitional sound films]]\n[[Category:United States National Film Registry films]]\n[[Category:Films set on the French home front during World War I]]\n", "name_user": "Lee Leander", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Added link to Film essay pdf on the National Film Registry site under External Links.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/7th_Heaven_(1927_film)"}
